# fedora — distro primer
#
# fedora is the upstream feeder for RHEL: a 6-month-cadence point-release
# distro maintained by Red Hat with heavy community involvement. each
# release is supported for ~13 months (current + previous), so you upgrade
# roughly once a year and have a 1-month grace window. fedora 44 (current)
# is supported through May 2026.
#
# default stack on a fresh Workstation install:
#
#   - GNOME on Wayland (Plasma + others are official Spins)
#   - btrfs root (since F33), with @ / @home subvolumes inside; ext4 still
#     an option in anaconda for those who pick it
#   - LUKS root encryption offered in the installer (off by default on
#     Workstation; some derivatives default to on)
#   - systemd everywhere
#   - NetworkManager
#   - firewalld (zone-based; FedoraWorkstation zone by default)
#   - SELinux ENFORCING (don't disable it; targeted policy is fine)
#   - PipeWire for audio (replaced pulseaudio as default)
#   - dnf5 from Fedora 41 onwards (native C++ rewrite of dnf4 — see [[dnf]])
#   - GRUB2 + BootLoaderSpec (per-kernel .conf files in /boot/loader/entries/)
#
# editions worth knowing:
#
#   - Workstation       — GNOME desktop. the default
#   - KDE Spin / Plasma — official KDE edition (promoted to Edition in F42)
#   - Server            — text-mode + cockpit web UI; xfs root (not btrfs)
#   - Silverblue        — immutable Workstation, rpm-ostree atomic updates
#   - Kinoite           — immutable KDE, same model as Silverblue
#   - Sericea / Onyx    — immutable Sway / Budgie
#   - CoreOS            — minimal, auto-updating, container-host focused
#   - IoT               — ostree-based, ARM/x86 for edge devices
#   - Spins             — XFCE, MATE, Cinnamon, LXQt, i3, etc.
#   - Labs              — purpose-built bundles (Astronomy, Robotics,
#                         Comp Neuro, Design Suite, ...)


RELEASE / UPGRADE
-----------------

# fedora is point-release. you upgrade in place between versions with the
# system-upgrade plugin (the supported path — DON'T just edit /etc/dnf/dnf.conf
# and `dnf upgrade` your way across, that's the partial-upgrade trap).

# refresh, install the plugin (already shipped on F41+), and pull the new
# release's packages WITHOUT applying them:
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo dnf install dnf5-plugin-system-upgrade        # F41+; on F40 it's dnf-plugin-system-upgrade
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=45   # pick the target release

# stage the actual upgrade — reboots into a special target that performs
# the rpm transactions, then reboots again into the new system
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot

# what to do BEFORE the system-upgrade:
#   - merge .rpmnew / .rpmsave files in /etc:
sudo find /etc -name '*.rpmnew' -o -name '*.rpmsave'
#   - check release notes for known breakage:
#       fedoraproject.org/wiki/Releases/<n>/ChangeSet
#       discussion.fedoraproject.org (Common Issues thread)
#   - snapshot if you're on btrfs and have snapper / timeshift configured

# check current release:
cat /etc/fedora-release
rpm -E %fedora                                      # just the number

# remember: skipping releases is supported (F43 → F45) but not RECOMMENDED.
# the more versions you cross the more likely some package combination
# trips the resolver. one hop at a time is the safe path.


UPGRADE STRATEGY — STAYING SUPPORTED WITHOUT DAY-ZERO PAIN
----------------------------------------------------------

# fedora's release math gives you a wide window:
#   - 2 releases / year (~April and ~October)
#   - ~13 months of support per release
#   - so N-1 stays supported for ~7 months AFTER N releases (generous
#     overlap — use it)
#   - hard deadline: don't sit on a release once N+2 is announced. that's
#     when the EOL clock starts ticking hard.
#
# day-zero upgrades are voluntary risk. the only thing you actually
# HAVE to avoid is going EOL.


# THE T+8 RULE (recommended default)

# wait 8 weeks after a release before upgrading. by T+8:
#   - 1-2 kernel point releases have shipped (6.x.1, 6.x.2)
#   - DE patch releases (GNOME 47.1 instead of .0) have landed
#   - the worst third-party-repo lag has resolved
#   - the Common Issues thread has stabilized
#
# you give up ~2 months on the bleeding edge. you gain dramatically
# fewer "why did my system break" incidents.


# CALENDAR IN PRACTICE
#
#   fall release (~Oct/Nov)     →  upgrade in January   (past holidays,
#                                                        T+8-10 weeks)
#   spring release (~April/May) →  upgrade in June/July (T+8-10 weeks)
#
# this puts you on every release ~2 months after launch, ALWAYS one
# release ahead of EOL, never racing the clock.


# 5-POINT PRE-UPGRADE SANITY CHECK
# (run at T+8 weeks; if any item is red, wait 4 more and re-check)

# a) Common Issues thread is quiet for your stack:
#       https://discussion.fedoraproject.org/c/announcements/

# b) RPM Fusion ships for fedora N:
curl -sI https://download1.rpmfusion.org/free/fedora/releases/45/Everything/x86_64/os/

# c) akmod-nvidia is built for fedora N (only if you use nvidia — this
#    is the #1 cause of "I'm on a black screen after upgrade"):
dnf --releasever=45 list akmod-nvidia 2>/dev/null

# d) your critical COPRs have published for fedora N. check each at
#    copr.fedoraproject.org/coprs/

# e) your current install is healthy:
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo find /etc -name '*.rpmnew' -o -name '*.rpmsave'
sudo reboot                                    # confirm clean boot first


# UPGRADE — THE COMMAND SEQUENCE
# (only after the sanity check is green)

# 1. snapshot first — btrfs root + a manual snapshot gives you a
#    rollback path:
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot / /.snapshot-pre-f45

# 2. system-upgrade plugin + download:
sudo dnf install dnf5-plugin-system-upgrade
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=45

# 3. apply (reboots into a special target, performs the rpm
#    transactions, reboots again into the new release):
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot

# 4. verify post-upgrade. smoke test the things you actually use:
cat /etc/fedora-release                        # confirm version
lsmod | grep nvidia                            # if applicable
nvidia-smi                                     # if applicable
# launch your terminal, browser, dev toolchain, any niche apps.


# ROLLBACK IF SOMETHING BROKE

# btrfs rollback path (assumes you took the snapshot in step 1):
sudo btrfs subvolume set-default \
    $(sudo btrfs subvolume list / | grep '.snapshot-pre-f45' | awk '{print $2}') /
sudo reboot
# you're back on the pre-upgrade subvolume. promote it back to default
# permanently via `btrfs subvolume set-default` or by mounting the
# old @ and copying it back. this is exactly the openSUSE / Manjaro
# snapshot-rollback story, just hand-rolled instead of snapper-driven.


# SEQUENTIAL > SKIPPING

# fedora SUPPORTS skipping releases (N-2 → N) via:
#       sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=N
# but the rpm resolver gets exponentially crankier with each version
# crossed. ALWAYS upgrade sequentially:
#       N → N+1 → N+2
# one extra hour, dramatically less --allowerasing debugging.
#
# if you've been off the grid and woke up on N-2:
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=$(( $(rpm -E %fedora) + 1 ))
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot
# boot, verify, reboot to a clean state, repeat for the next hop.


# PRE-UPGRADE HARD RULES (apply to every upgrade)

# - DON'T upgrade with un-merged .rpmnew files. they carry forward and
#   bite you later. merge them on current release first.
# - DON'T upgrade from a non-default kernel. boot the standard
#   /boot/vmlinuz-<latest> first.
# - DON'T upgrade with a broken current install. fix the current release
#   first — dnf system-upgrade is not a recovery tool.
# - DISABLE third-party repos that don't ship for N yet (chrome COPRs,
#   vendor repos, etc.). re-enable after.
# - On nvidia: CONFIRM akmod-nvidia has shipped for fedora N before
#   pulling the trigger. (sanity check c above.)


# WHERE TO MONITOR

# - discussion.fedoraproject.org/c/announcements/  — official notes,
#   Common Issues per release. this is the canonical source.
# - fedoramagazine.org                             — readable summaries
# - bodhi.fedoraproject.org                        — see what's in
#   updates-testing if you want to peek ahead
# - fedoraproject.org/wiki/Releases/N/ChangeSet    — per-release
#   major changes
#
# RSS-subscribe at least the first two. the rest you check at upgrade
# time.


# WHAT THIS STRATEGY EXPLICITLY ACCEPTS

# - ~2 months behind early adopters on new features.
# - never bleeding-edge, never EOL — a permanent middle lane.
# - ~1 hour of effort every 6 months (sanity check + upgrade).
# - snapshot rollback path means worst-case recovery is minutes,
#   not a reinstall.


BACKUPS — SNAPSHOTS ARE NOT BACKUPS
-----------------------------------

# the most-skipped section of any setup primer, and the one that
# matters most the first time something goes wrong. before any tools:
# get the mental model right.


# THE MENTAL MODEL — WHY SNAPSHOTS DON'T COUNT

# btrfs snapshots (covered in UPGRADE STRATEGY) protect you against
# a software-level mistake: a bad upgrade, an `rm -rf` you ran in the
# wrong directory and noticed within hours. they DO NOT protect you
# against:
#   - the disk physically failing (snapshot and original on same disk)
#   - the controller eating the filesystem (same fs)
#   - ransomware encrypting your files (snapshot can be deleted too)
#   - theft / fire (the laptop is gone)
#   - a sync mistake that propagates the delete to the snapshot
#
# the 3-2-1 rule, modernized: 3 copies of your data, on 2 different
# storage technologies, with 1 of them PHYSICALLY OFFSITE. snapshots
# count as zero of those.


# WHAT TO BACK UP

# CRITICAL (irreplaceable):
#   - ~/.gnupg, ~/.ssh — losing these is recovery hell
#   - ~/.local/share/keyrings, ~/.config/{1Password,bitwarden} — passwords
#   - your /home in general — documents, projects, browser profiles
#   - /etc — your edited configs (small but precious)
#   - /var/lib/<service> for anything you self-host (postgres, mysql,
#     docker / podman volumes, gitea, nextcloud...)
#   - the "user-installed package" list (treat as a regenerator, not data):
sudo dnf repoquery --userinstalled --queryformat '%{name}\n' \
    | sort > ~/backup-userinstalled.txt
flatpak list --columns=application > ~/backup-flatpaks.txt

# REGENERATABLE (skip):
#   - /var/cache, /tmp, /var/tmp
#   - ~/.cache
#   - container images (re-pull)
#   - build artifacts (target/, node_modules/, .venv/, __pycache__/)
#   - /usr, /boot — package manager rebuilds these


# TOOLS — IN ORDER OF SOPHISTICATION

# 1. RSYNC — the foundation. simple, reliable. NOT a backup tool on its
#    own because it has no versioning — if you sync after a `rm -rf`
#    you've propagated the disaster. fine for "copy /home to USB" once.
rsync -aHAX --delete /home/ /run/media/$USER/backup/home/

# 2. BTRFS SEND / RECEIVE — incremental cross-machine snapshot
#    transfer. zero parsing of files, exact, fast. requires btrfs on
#    BOTH ends. great for "back up snapshots to a NAS over ssh".
#    see [[btrfs]] SEND / RECEIVE section.

# 3. BORG (borgbackup) — the most-recommended Linux backup tool.
#    deduplicated, encrypted, compressed. CLI-driven, mature.
#    repository can be local, USB, or remote over SSH. mountable for
#    browsing past states.
sudo dnf install borgbackup
borg init --encryption=repokey-blake2 /run/media/$USER/borg-repo
borg create --stats --compression zstd,3 \
    /run/media/$USER/borg-repo::"home-$(date +%F)" \
    /home/$USER \
    --exclude='/home/*/.cache' \
    --exclude='/home/*/.local/share/Trash' \
    --exclude='**/node_modules' \
    --exclude='**/target' \
    --exclude='**/.venv'
borg list /run/media/$USER/borg-repo                    # past archives
borg mount /run/media/$USER/borg-repo::home-2026-06-14 /mnt/r
borg prune --keep-daily 7 --keep-weekly 4 --keep-monthly 12 \
    /run/media/$USER/borg-repo
borg compact /run/media/$USER/borg-repo                 # reclaim space

# 4. RESTIC — borg's newer rival. similar feature set, written in go,
#    crucial difference: native support for many cloud backends
#    (S3, B2, Wasabi, Azure, GCS, OneDrive, SFTP, rclone) without
#    wrappers. pick this if you want cloud-native backups.
sudo dnf install restic
export RESTIC_REPOSITORY="b2:my-bucket:fedora-backup"
export RESTIC_PASSWORD_FILE="$HOME/.restic-password"
restic init
restic backup /home/$USER \
    --exclude="$HOME/.cache" \
    --exclude="**/node_modules" \
    --exclude="**/target"
restic snapshots
restic mount /mnt/r
restic forget --keep-daily 7 --keep-weekly 4 --keep-monthly 12 --prune

# 5. DEJA-DUP (gnome backups GUI) — wraps duplicity. easy "back up
#    /home to external drive" for non-CLI users. less capable than
#    borg/restic. ships in fedora workstation:
sudo dnf install deja-dup


# DESTINATIONS — THE 3-2-1 BREAKDOWN

# COPY 1 — your live filesystem on the laptop (doesn't count as a
#          backup; it's the original).
#
# COPY 2 — local fast storage. external USB SSD, internal second drive,
#          or NAS on the LAN. fast restore, easy to verify, cheap.
#          weak point: same physical location as the original.
#
# COPY 3 — offsite. options in 2026:
#   - cloud object storage: backblaze B2 (~$5/TB/mo), wasabi, S3,
#     hetzner storage box (european-priced)
#   - rsync.net (SSH-accessible, borg-friendly, $1.50/TB/mo at scale,
#     popular with borg users)
#   - friend's house with a NAS, swap drives quarterly
#   - work backup if your employer allows it (check policy)
#
# the offsite copy is what saves you from fire, theft, and ransomware.
# don't skip it.


# ENCRYPTION & KEY MANAGEMENT — THE WHOLE GAME

# borg and restic encrypt by default. that's good. but:
#
#   - LOSING THE PASSPHRASE = BACKUPS GONE. no recovery, no support
#     desk, no "i forgot my password" link.
#   - don't store the passphrase in ~/.config/borg/passwd on the same
#     machine you're backing up. obvious chicken-and-egg.
#
# acceptable passphrase-storage strategies:
#   - print it, store in a fire safe at home + a duplicate at a
#     trusted location (parents' house, safety deposit box)
#   - put it in a password manager whose vault you can recover via
#     a different path (e.g. 1Password / Bitwarden recovery key
#     printed and stored physically)
#   - cryptsetup luksHeaderBackup-style: a small file you keep on
#     multiple USB sticks geographically separated


# RECOMMENDED SETUP FOR A DAILY DRIVER

# a layered approach that won't burn you:
#
#   - btrfs snapshots BEFORE every -Syu via timeshift or manual
#     (rolling-release safety net; see UPGRADE STRATEGY)
#   - borg or restic to a LOCAL external SSD, WEEKLY (fast restore,
#     cheap)
#   - restic to a CLOUD backend (B2 or rsync.net), NIGHTLY
#     (the offsite leg)
#   - QUARTERLY restore drill: actually pull one file back from cloud
#     to confirm the backup works


# AUTOMATION — SYSTEMD TIMERS, NOT CRON

# don't use cron for backups on fedora. systemd timers integrate with
# the journal (you can see failures with journalctl), respect
# OnFailure= for notification hooks, and survive reboots cleanly.

# example: nightly restic backup as a user service.

mkdir -p ~/.config/systemd/user
cat >~/.config/systemd/user/restic-backup.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Nightly restic backup to B2

[Service]
Type=oneshot
Environment="RESTIC_REPOSITORY=b2:my-bucket:fedora-backup"
EnvironmentFile=%h/.config/restic/env
ExecStart=/usr/bin/restic backup %h --exclude=%h/.cache
ExecStart=/usr/bin/restic forget --keep-daily 7 --keep-weekly 4 --keep-monthly 12 --prune
EOF

cat >~/.config/systemd/user/restic-backup.timer <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Nightly restic backup

[Timer]
OnCalendar=*-*-* 02:30:00
Persistent=true
RandomizedDelaySec=900

[Install]
WantedBy=timers.target
EOF

systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable --now restic-backup.timer
systemctl --user list-timers
# verify it ran:
journalctl --user -u restic-backup.service -n 50

# user services don't run when you're logged out unless lingering
# is enabled. for a laptop that's usually fine; for a desktop that
# runs unattended:
loginctl enable-linger "$USER"


# THE QUARTERLY RESTORE DRILL

# untested backups are not backups. once a quarter:
#
#   1. pick a file you care about from the last week
#   2. restore it from your CLOUD backup (not the local SSD — the
#      cloud copy is the one whose health matters most)
#   3. diff against the live version. confirm contents identical.
#   4. for bonus points: do a full restore to a VM, confirm boot
#
# 90% of "my backups don't work" stories are from people who never
# tested.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. DATABASES NEED DUMPS, NOT FILE-LEVEL BACKUPS. backing up a live
#    postgres data directory often produces unrestorable garbage.
#    dump first, then back up the dump:
sudo -u postgres pg_dumpall -f /backup/postgres-dump.sql
#    same for mysql (mysqldump), influxdb (influxd backup), etc.
#
# 2. ACTIVE VMs — shut down before file-level backup, or use libvirt
#    snapshot capture (see VIRTUAL MACHINES section).
#
# 3. DOCKER / PODMAN VOLUMES live under /var/lib/<engine>/. for
#    podman, `podman volume export` produces a tarball you can back up.
#
# 4. BACKING UP /home INCLUDES BROWSER PROFILES. firefox / chrome
#    while RUNNING hold open SQLite files — back up while the
#    browser is closed, or accept some files will be corrupt-at-rest
#    in the backup (recoverable via journal but not pretty).
#
# 5. DON'T BACK UP YOUR PASSWORD MANAGER VAULT TO A CLOUD YOU NEED
#    THE PASSWORD MANAGER TO ACCESS. circular. keep at least one
#    out-of-band copy.
#
# 6. SNAP'S AUTO-REFRESH WILL CHANGE FILES MID-BACKUP. not a fedora
#    problem but worth knowing if you have any snaps (you shouldn't
#    on fedora; this is one of the reasons people leave ubuntu —
#    see WHY UBUNTU USERS MIGRATE section).
#
# 7. RSYNC --DELETE WILL PROPAGATE ACCIDENTAL DELETIONS. if you use
#    rsync as your "backup" you have no protection against `rm -rf`.
#    this is exactly why borg / restic are real backup tools and
#    rsync isn't.


# IF YOU NEED ONE LINE OF GUIDANCE
#
#   `sudo dnf install restic` → point it at backblaze B2 → systemd
#   timer at 02:30 nightly → print the passphrase → put it in a safe.
#
# that's a real backup. everything else is optimization.


BTRFS SNAPSHOTS — THE ROLLBACK WORKFLOW
---------------------------------------

# the BACKUPS section made the case that snapshots are NOT
# backups. this section covers what snapshots ARE for: cheap,
# instant, local rollback when a system change goes sideways.
# for the filesystem-level deep dive (mkfs, profiles, balance,
# scrub, send/receive) see the separate [[btrfs]] primer.


# MENTAL MODEL — WHY THIS IS DIFFERENT FROM A BACKUP

# - a SUBVOLUME is a named, independently-mountable tree
# - a SNAPSHOT is a writable (or read-only) clone of a subvolume
#   that shares blocks via copy-on-write
# - taking a snapshot is O(1) and uses zero extra space until
#   something diverges from the parent
# - a snapshot lives on the SAME disk as the original. if the
#   drive dies, both die together. that's why this is rollback
#   insurance, not backup. see BACKUPS for the offsite story.


# FEDORA'S DEFAULT SUBVOLUME LAYOUT

# anaconda (the fedora installer) creates two top-level subvolumes
# on a btrfs root install:
#
#   root  → mounted at /         (the OS + /var + /usr)
#   home  → mounted at /home     (your data, separated for a reason)
#
# (note: NOT `@` and `@home` — that's the Ubuntu/Mint/openSUSE
# naming. fedora uses plain `root` and `home`.)
#
# /var/log and /var/cache are NOT separate subvolumes by default
# (unlike openSUSE) — they're inside `root`. this is a deliberate
# fedora choice; rolling back root rolls back logs too. live with it,
# or restructure manually if you care.

sudo btrfs subvolume list /              # see what's there
sudo btrfs subvolume show /              # the current subvolume's info
findmnt /                                # confirm subvol= mount option


# MANUAL SNAPSHOTS — THE PRE / POST PATTERN

# the everyday discipline: before a risky change, take a snapshot.
# after, decide whether to keep or delete. costs nothing if you
# never diverge.

# read-only snapshot (the conservative default — can't be mutated
# accidentally, can still be browsed and restored from)
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot -r / /.snapshots/root-pre-$(date +%F-%H%M)

# writable snapshot (when you want to test in the snapshot itself)
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot / /.snapshots/root-pre-$(date +%F-%H%M)

# list / delete
sudo btrfs subvolume list /
sudo btrfs subvolume delete /.snapshots/root-pre-2026-06-17-1430

# when to take one manually:
#   - before `dnf upgrade --refresh` (especially across releases)
#   - before swapping NVIDIA driver branches
#   - before mass /etc edits or restoring a config from elsewhere
#   - before installing something from COPR or a vendor rpm
#   - before running someone else's install.sh

# /.snapshots is a convention, not a requirement. snapper uses it
# by default; if you go fully manual, create it yourself:
sudo mkdir -p /.snapshots
sudo chmod 750 /.snapshots


# SNAPPER — AUTOMATIC PRE / POST FOR EVERY DNF TRANSACTION

# snapper is the openSUSE-grown tool that turns the manual pattern
# into a hands-off habit: automatic snapshot before AND after every
# package transaction, with timeline cleanup so it doesn't blow up
# /.snapshots over months.

sudo dnf install snapper btrfs-assistant
sudo snapper -c root create-config /        # config for /
sudo snapper -c home create-config /home    # optional, for /home

# the dnf bridge — this is the piece that makes it automatic.
# on dnf5 (fedora 41+):
sudo dnf install python3-dnf-plugin-snapper
# (on legacy dnf4: dnf-plugin-snapper)

# now every `sudo dnf install/upgrade/remove` creates a pre+post
# snapshot pair tagged with the dnf transaction id.

# verify it works:
sudo dnf install -y htop                    # any small install
sudo snapper list                           # see the pre/post pair

# timeline cleanup tuning (in /etc/snapper/configs/root):
#   TIMELINE_LIMIT_HOURLY="5"
#   TIMELINE_LIMIT_DAILY="7"
#   TIMELINE_LIMIT_WEEKLY="4"
#   TIMELINE_LIMIT_MONTHLY="6"
#   TIMELINE_LIMIT_YEARLY="0"
#
# crank these down hard on a laptop with small SSD. snapper's
# defaults are openSUSE-style "keep a lot."


# BROWSING AND RESTORING — BTRFS-ASSISTANT (GUI)

# btrfs-assistant is the GUI to snapper + btrfs maintenance. flatpak
# version exists; the dnf package integrates more cleanly with system
# snapper configs.
btrfs-assistant      # launch; needs polkit auth

# what it gives you:
#   - browse every snapshot, see what changed file-by-file (uses
#     snapper diff)
#   - "restore this snapshot" → handles the rename + grub update
#   - configure snapper timelines without editing config files
#   - run scrub / balance on a schedule with sane defaults


# THE ROLLBACK FLOW (THE WHOLE POINT OF THIS SECTION)

# scenario: a dnf upgrade broke something. you want to be back on
# the pre-upgrade state in 60 seconds.

# OPTION A — the snapper-driven path
sudo snapper list                            # find the pre-snapshot
sudo snapper rollback <NUMBER>               # snapper handles the rest
sudo reboot
# snapper renames the current `root` aside, promotes the snapshot
# to be the new `root`, and updates the default subvolume. on
# reboot you're on the snapshot.

# OPTION B — the manual path (when snapper isn't installed)
# 1. boot from any fedora live USB
# 2. mount the btrfs root with subvolid=5 to see the top
sudo mount -o subvolid=5 /dev/mapper/luks-... /mnt
sudo mv /mnt/root /mnt/root-broken
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot /mnt/.snapshots/root-pre-... /mnt/root
sudo btrfs subvolume set-default $(sudo btrfs subvolume list /mnt | \
    awk '/path root$/ {print $2}') /mnt
sudo umount /mnt
sudo reboot

# /home is on its own subvolume — rolling back root does NOT
# touch your data. that's the whole point of fedora's split layout.


# BOOT-TIME RECOVERY — GRUB-BTRFS

# grub-btrfs adds a "btrfs snapshots" submenu to GRUB at boot, so
# you can roll back to a snapshot when the system WON'T BOOT (the
# moment you need rollback most).
sudo dnf install grub-btrfs
sudo systemctl enable --now grub-btrfsd      # watches for new snapshots
# the daemon regenerates grub on every new snapshot. pick a
# snapshot from the GRUB submenu → boots it read-only → from
# inside, run `snapper rollback` to promote it permanently.


# QUOTA / QGROUPS — KNOW THIS BEFORE YOU ENABLE IT

# qgroups let snapper compute and enforce per-snapshot space usage.
# they also have a real performance cost (especially on big
# subvolumes with many snapshots), and they've been historically
# buggy on btrfs.
sudo btrfs quota enable /
sudo btrfs qgroup show -p /

# the honest tradeoff: on a workstation, leave qgroups DISABLED
# and let snapper count by count instead of by size. enable them
# only if you've hit a real "snapshots filled the disk" problem
# and need automatic cleanup by size.


# WHAT SNAPSHOTS WILL NEVER SAVE YOU FROM

# this is worth re-saying because it's the most common mistake:
#
#   - drive failure (snapshot and original on same disk → both gone)
#   - file deletion that propagated through a sync tool
#   - ransomware that encrypts every block (snapshot is on the
#     same fs and can be deleted by the attacker)
#   - LUKS key loss (no key, no fs, no snapshots)
#   - filesystem-level corruption (rare but real on btrfs)
#
# every one of those needs a real offsite backup. see BACKUPS.


# HONEST TRADEOFFS

# snapper + dnf-plugin-snapper adds ~2 snapshots per package
# operation. on a small ~256GB SSD with default cleanup limits
# you'll burn 10-30 GB on snapshot metadata in a few months.
# this is the cost of the safety net; tune TIMELINE_LIMIT_*
# down if it bothers you.

# don't snapshot inside /var/lib/containers, /var/lib/libvirt,
# or other CoW-already filesystems — you'll get write
# amplification and ballooning. set NoCOW on those directories:
sudo chattr +C /var/lib/containers
sudo chattr +C /var/lib/libvirt/images
# (must be done on an empty directory; existing files won't be
# converted. for an existing dir: move out, set +C, move back.)

# do NOT enable snapper on /home AND let it run timeline. people's
# Downloads folder churns a lot — a year of snapshots will eat
# real space. prefer manual /home snapshots before risky moves.


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   "before I do X, take a snapshot"     → btrfs subvolume snapshot -r / /.snapshots/...
#   "auto snapshot on every dnf"         → snapper + python3-dnf-plugin-snapper
#   "see all snapshots"                  → snapper list   OR   btrfs subvolume list /
#   "diff this snapshot vs now"          → snapper diff <num>..0
#   "roll back to a snapshot"            → snapper rollback <num> && reboot
#   "can't boot — roll back from GRUB"   → grub-btrfs + grub-btrfsd
#   "GUI for all of this"                → btrfs-assistant
#   "how much space is this costing me?" → btrfs filesystem usage /
#   "kill all old snapshots"             → snapper cleanup timeline


# cross-references
# - BACKUPS section: why this is NOT a substitute for offsite backups
# - UPGRADE STRATEGY section: the snapshot-before-release-upgrade flow
# - GRUB section: BLS entries, default subvol, boot menu
# - DISK MANAGEMENT section: when /boot is on its own partition
# - [[btrfs]] primer: filesystem-level mechanics, profiles, scrub


DISK MANAGEMENT (LVM, SWAP, PARTITIONING)
-----------------------------------------

# fedora workstation has defaulted to btrfs since F33 (covered in
# [[btrfs]]). this section is everything ELSE about disk management
# on fedora: LVM, swap, partitioning, SMART monitoring, fsck.


# INSPECTING DISKS — THE EVERYDAY TOOLS

lsblk                                          # block devices + sizes + mounts
lsblk -f                                       # add filesystem + UUID
lsblk -o NAME,SIZE,FSTYPE,LABEL,UUID,MOUNTPOINT  # custom columns

blkid                                          # filesystem UUID + label
blkid /dev/nvme0n1p3                          # one device

df -h                                          # mounted fs usage
df -h --output=source,fstype,size,used,avail,target

# byte-accurate space (df can lie on btrfs — see [[btrfs]]):
ncdu /                                         # interactive disk usage
sudo dnf install dust && dust                  # modern alternative

# what's attached
lsusb                                          # USB devices
lspci | grep -iE 'sata|nvme|ahci'             # storage controllers


# ANACONDA INSTALLER LAYOUTS

# at install time anaconda offers three modes:
#
#   AUTOMATIC — "use the entire disk". on F33+ this gives you:
#       /boot/efi  fat32   ~600 MiB (UEFI only)
#       /boot      ext4    ~1 GiB
#       /          btrfs   the rest (with @ and @home subvolumes)
#       [swap]     zram    in-memory swap, no disk partition
#     if you ticked "Encrypt my data": LUKS wraps the root partition.
#
#   ADVANCED CUSTOM (BLIVET) — full manual control. pick FS per mount
#       point. supports btrfs, xfs, ext4, lvm. needed for non-default
#       layouts.
#
#   ADVANCED CUSTOM (WEBUI) — newer, simpler version of above.


# WHY BTRFS BY DEFAULT? (vs LVM + ext4 / xfs)

# the rationale fedora landed on for F33:
#   - SNAPSHOTS are first-class (timeshift, snapper, btrfs send)
#   - SUBVOLUMES replace per-mount-point partitioning — no more
#     "i sized /home too small"
#   - TRANSPARENT COMPRESSION (zstd) saves 20-40% on typical workloads
#   - CHECKSUMS catch silent data corruption
#
# LVM still makes sense when:
#   - you need a fs btrfs doesn't support (xfs for >16TB single-volume
#     workloads; ext4 for "boring is good")
#   - you're managing multiple disks as one volume group across
#     filesystem boundaries
#   - shared storage with cluster file systems
#   - production servers with strict-conservatism culture (RHEL leans
#     LVM + xfs as the supported default)


# LVM BASICS

# LVM (Logical Volume Manager) sits between physical disks and
# filesystems. three concepts:
#
#   PV  (physical volume)  — a disk or partition prepared for LVM
#   VG  (volume group)     — a pool of PVs, allocates blocks
#   LV  (logical volume)   — a "virtual partition" carved from a VG
#
# inspect:
sudo pvs                                       # physical volumes
sudo vgs                                       # volume groups
sudo lvs                                       # logical volumes
sudo pvdisplay / vgdisplay / lvdisplay         # verbose

# create from scratch (a typical 2-disk setup):
sudo pvcreate /dev/sdb /dev/sdc
sudo vgcreate datavg /dev/sdb /dev/sdc
sudo lvcreate -L 100G -n homelv datavg
sudo mkfs.xfs /dev/datavg/homelv               # or btrfs, ext4
sudo mkdir /data && sudo mount /dev/datavg/homelv /data

# extend an LV (grow a "partition" online):
sudo lvextend -L +50G /dev/datavg/homelv
sudo xfs_growfs /data                          # for xfs
# OR sudo resize2fs /dev/datavg/homelv          # for ext4

# shrink an LV (ext4 only; xfs CANNOT shrink):
sudo umount /data
sudo e2fsck -f /dev/datavg/homelv
sudo resize2fs /dev/datavg/homelv 50G
sudo lvreduce -L 50G /dev/datavg/homelv
sudo mount /dev/datavg/homelv /data

# remove an LV (DANGEROUS — data loss):
sudo umount /data
sudo lvremove /dev/datavg/homelv

# add a new disk to an existing VG:
sudo pvcreate /dev/sdd
sudo vgextend datavg /dev/sdd

# LVM SNAPSHOTS — copy-on-write at the LV layer (similar concept to
# btrfs snapshots but per-volume):
sudo lvcreate --snapshot --name homelv-snap -L 10G /dev/datavg/homelv
sudo lvremove /dev/datavg/homelv-snap         # delete it later

# snapshots are sized — they hold deltas from the original; if more
# than the snapshot size changes, the snapshot is invalidated.


# SWAP — PARTITION, SWAPFILE, OR ZRAM

# fedora workstation defaults to ZRAM-SWAP since F33: a compressed
# RAM-backed swap. no disk partition. faster than disk swap; uses RAM
# more efficiently under memory pressure.

# inspect current swap
swapon --show
free -h

# verify zram-swap status
zramctl                                        # active zram devices

# zram-swap config (already configured by zram-generator):
cat /usr/lib/systemd/zram-generator.conf
cat /etc/systemd/zram-generator.conf 2>/dev/null
# example tuning override:
sudo tee /etc/systemd/zram-generator.conf <<'EOF'
[zram0]
zram-size = ram / 2
compression-algorithm = zstd
EOF
sudo systemctl restart systemd-zram-setup@zram0


# SWAP PARTITION — for hibernation or non-zram setups

# create:
sudo mkswap /dev/sdX2                          # the partition
sudo swapon /dev/sdX2
echo 'UUID=... swap swap defaults 0 0' | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab

# permanent disable:
sudo swapoff /dev/sdX2
# remove the line from /etc/fstab


# SWAPFILE — when partitioning isn't an option

# btrfs swapfile (covered in POWER MANAGEMENT for hibernate; needs
# chattr +C):
sudo touch /swapfile
sudo chattr +C /swapfile                       # btrfs: nodatacow REQUIRED
sudo fallocate -l 8G /swapfile
sudo chmod 600 /swapfile
sudo mkswap /swapfile
sudo swapon /swapfile
echo '/swapfile none swap defaults 0 0' | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab

# ext4 / xfs swapfile (no chattr +C needed):
sudo fallocate -l 8G /swapfile
sudo chmod 600 /swapfile
sudo mkswap /swapfile
sudo swapon /swapfile

# typical swappiness tune (lower = use disk swap less aggressively):
sudo sysctl vm.swappiness=10                   # try this
echo 'vm.swappiness=10' | sudo tee /etc/sysctl.d/swap.conf


# PARTITIONING — INTERACTIVE TOOLS

# CLI (most precise):
sudo fdisk /dev/sda                            # MBR + GPT, interactive
sudo gdisk /dev/sda                            # GPT only
sudo parted /dev/sda                           # GNU parted; scriptable
sudo cfdisk /dev/sda                           # curses TUI; friendly

# GUI:
sudo dnf install gparted
sudo gparted                                   # the classic partition GUI

# GNOME Disks (preinstalled):
gnome-disks                                    # simpler GUI


# RESIZING A PARTITION + FILESYSTEM

# the safe path: shrink fs first, then partition. extend partition
# first, then fs. NEVER the reverse.

# extend an ext4:
sudo parted /dev/sda resizepart 3 100%
sudo resize2fs /dev/sda3                       # online

# extend xfs:
sudo parted /dev/sda resizepart 3 100%
sudo xfs_growfs /                              # mount point, not device

# btrfs grow (covered in [[btrfs]]):
sudo btrfs filesystem resize max /


# SMART MONITORING — CATCHING DRIVE FAILURE EARLY

# smartmontools reads SMART (self-monitoring) data from drives. catches
# pre-failure conditions days to weeks before actual failure.

sudo dnf install smartmontools

# check one drive
sudo smartctl -a /dev/sda                      # full report
sudo smartctl -H /dev/sda                      # just health summary
sudo smartctl -t short /dev/sda                # 2-min self-test
sudo smartctl -t long /dev/sda                 # hours; nightly job
sudo smartctl -l selftest /dev/sda             # past results

# what to watch:
#   - Reallocated_Sectors_Count    rising = drive is dying
#   - Current_Pending_Sectors      rising = imminent failure
#   - Wear_Leveling_Count (SSD)    falling toward 0 = wear limit
#   - Reported_Uncorrectable      any nonzero = errors during reads

# enable scheduled monitoring:
sudo systemctl enable --now smartd
# config: /etc/smartmontools/smartd.conf
#   default: monitor all drives, daily short test, weekly long test,
#   email-on-failure to root
# tune email destination:
echo 'DEVICESCAN -m you@example.com -M exec /usr/libexec/smartmontools/smartdnotify' \
    | sudo tee /etc/smartmontools/smartd.conf
sudo systemctl restart smartd


# FILESYSTEM CHECK / REPAIR

# ext4 — fsck.ext4
sudo umount /dev/sda3                          # MUST be unmounted
sudo fsck.ext4 -fy /dev/sda3                   # force check, auto-yes

# xfs — xfs_repair (no fsck; xfs_repair is the tool)
sudo umount /xfs-mount
sudo xfs_repair /dev/sda3

# btrfs — btrfs check (offline only; covered in [[btrfs]] RECOVERY)
sudo btrfs check --readonly /dev/sda3

# emergency: boot the live ISO, mount nothing, repair from there.
# all repair tools require UNMOUNTED targets — you can't repair a
# mounted root from itself.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. RAN OUT OF SPACE ON / BUT df SHOWS FREE SPACE. inode exhaustion.
#    check:
df -i                                          # inode usage
#    fix: delete lots of small files (often /tmp or /var/cache).
#    btrfs doesn't have inode limits.
#
# 2. SWAP NOT BEING USED. check vm.swappiness:
cat /proc/sys/vm/swappiness                    # default: 30
#    fedora's default is conservative; many people lower it further.
#    if swap is "off" but you expected on, check zramctl + swapon.
#
# 3. SHRINKING A PARTITION CAUSED CORRUPTION. you skipped the
#    "shrink fs first, then partition" rule. recovery: restore from
#    backup. fsck won't save you here.
#
# 4. LVM SNAPSHOT FILLED UP. snapshots are sized; if too much changes
#    on the original, the snapshot is invalidated. recover by
#    extending the snapshot LV BEFORE it fills:
sudo lvextend -L +5G /dev/datavg/homelv-snap
#
# 5. "DISK FULL" BUT DELETING FILES DOESN'T HELP. a process has a
#    file open by inode; deleting the directory entry doesn't free
#    the space. find the process:
sudo lsof | grep deleted
#    kill it or restart it to actually release the space.
#
# 6. SMART DATA UNAVAILABLE THROUGH USB ENCLOSURE. some USB-to-SATA
#    bridges don't pass SMART commands through. workarounds:
sudo smartctl -d sat /dev/sdX                 # try SAT pass-through
sudo smartctl -d sntasmedia /dev/sdX          # asmedia bridges


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   "what disks do I have"               → lsblk -f
#   "what's mounted where"               → df -h --output=source,target,fstype
#   "is my disk healthy"                 → sudo smartctl -H /dev/sdX
#   "grow a logical volume + fs"         → lvextend / resize2fs (or xfs_growfs)
#   "shrink a logical volume + fs"       → ext4 only; lvreduce + resize2fs
#   "add swap on btrfs"                  → chattr +C, fallocate, mkswap, swapon
#   "boot rescue an unbootable disk"     → live ISO + arch-chroot equivalent


SYSTEMD — THE FOUNDATIONAL GLUE
-------------------------------

# fedora is the systemd REFERENCE platform — it's where systemd is
# tested first and adopted earliest. nearly every operational task on
# fedora goes through it: services, schedules, log access, mount
# management, boot, suspend, lid handling. this section is the
# minimum mental model + daily commands.


# MENTAL MODEL

# everything systemd does is modeled as a UNIT. unit TYPES are
# distinguished by file suffix:
#
#   .service   — a process (daemon, oneshot script, etc.)
#   .timer     — a schedule that activates another unit
#   .socket    — a socket that starts a service on connect
#   .mount     — a filesystem mount point
#   .automount — auto-mount on access
#   .target    — a grouping of other units (analogous to runlevels)
#   .path      — a filesystem-watching trigger
#   .slice     — a cgroup branch (resource limits)
#   .scope     — externally-launched processes adopted into a cgroup
#
# units have a DEPENDENCY GRAPH (After=, Wants=, Requires=, etc.) and
# systemd parallelizes startup based on it. boot is "reach
# default.target via its dependency tree."
#
# there are TWO instances on every system:
#
#   SYSTEM instance (--system, the default for `systemctl ...`)
#       runs as PID 1. shared resources, network, daemons.
#   USER instance (--user, per-login-user)
#       runs as your user. background apps, user services / timers.
#       no sudo. config in ~/.config/systemd/user/.


# SYSTEMCTL — DAILY COMMANDS

# status of a service
systemctl status sshd                       # current state + last logs
systemctl is-active sshd                    # one-word answer
systemctl is-enabled sshd                   # will it start at boot?
systemctl is-failed sshd

# lifecycle
sudo systemctl start sshd
sudo systemctl stop sshd
sudo systemctl restart sshd
sudo systemctl reload sshd                  # reload config, don't restart
sudo systemctl enable sshd                  # start at boot
sudo systemctl enable --now sshd            # enable AND start now
sudo systemctl disable sshd

# mask (refuse to start, even by dep) — heavier than disable
sudo systemctl mask suspend.target          # disable suspend entirely
sudo systemctl unmask suspend.target

# listing
systemctl                                   # every active unit
systemctl list-units --type=service
systemctl list-units --state=failed         # what's currently broken
systemctl list-unit-files                   # every unit FILE (not just active)
systemctl list-unit-files --state=enabled

# inspect dependencies
systemctl list-dependencies sshd            # what sshd needs
systemctl list-dependencies sshd --reverse  # what needs sshd
systemctl show sshd                         # every property

# reload systemd's view of unit files (after editing them)
sudo systemctl daemon-reload


# JOURNALCTL — LOG ACCESS

# fedora ships systemd-journald as the canonical log destination.
# /var/log/journal/ is persistent across reboots by default on F44.

# basics
journalctl                                  # all logs, paged
journalctl -e                               # jump to end
journalctl -f                               # follow (like tail -f)
journalctl --since "2 hours ago"
journalctl --since today
journalctl --until "2026-06-16 14:00"

# scoped to a unit (the most-used form)
journalctl -u sshd                          # all sshd logs
journalctl -u sshd -f                       # follow sshd
journalctl -u sshd --since today -p err     # only errors

# scoped to a boot
journalctl -b                               # current boot
journalctl -b -1                            # previous boot
journalctl --list-boots                     # what boot IDs exist

# user-instance logs (for ~/.config/systemd/user/ services)
journalctl --user -u my-app

# priority filter (0=emerg .. 7=debug)
journalctl -p warning..err                  # warning OR err
journalctl -p err -b                        # errors this boot

# pid / command-line filters (less-known, very useful)
journalctl _PID=1234
journalctl _COMM=sshd
journalctl _UID=1000

# output format
journalctl -u sshd -o cat                   # raw messages only
journalctl -u sshd -o json                  # full structured output
journalctl -u sshd -o short-iso             # ISO timestamps

# disk usage / rotation
journalctl --disk-usage
sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=2weeks        # delete entries older than
sudo journalctl --vacuum-size=2G            # cap journal at 2 GiB


# WRITING A SERVICE FILE

# system service (root-owned daemon). path: /etc/systemd/system/foo.service
sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/myapp.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=My App
After=network-online.target
Wants=network-online.target

[Service]
Type=simple                                 # most apps
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/myapp --port 8080
ExecReload=/bin/kill -HUP $MAINPID
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=5
User=myapp                                  # run as a dedicated user
Group=myapp

# security hardening — apply unless you have a reason not to
NoNewPrivileges=yes
ProtectSystem=strict
ProtectHome=yes
PrivateTmp=yes
PrivateDevices=yes
ProtectKernelTunables=yes
ProtectKernelModules=yes
ProtectControlGroups=yes
RestrictSUIDSGID=yes
LockPersonality=yes

# write paths the service NEEDS access to (carve out from ProtectSystem)
ReadWritePaths=/var/lib/myapp

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
EOF

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable --now myapp.service
journalctl -u myapp -f

# Type= values worth knowing:
#   simple     — process is the daemon (no daemonize step)
#   exec       — like simple but waits until exec() succeeds
#   forking    — old-school: parent forks, child is the daemon
#   oneshot    — run, exit, that's normal. used with timers.
#   notify     — daemon notifies systemd when it's ready (sd_notify)

# USER SERVICE (no root needed, runs as you):
mkdir -p ~/.config/systemd/user
cat >~/.config/systemd/user/myapp.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=My user app

[Service]
ExecStart=%h/bin/myapp                       # %h = $HOME
Restart=on-failure

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target
EOF
systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable --now myapp.service


# WRITING A TIMER

# timers fire .service units on a schedule. they are the systemd
# replacement for cron. ALWAYS paired: a foo.timer plus a foo.service.

cat >~/.config/systemd/user/cleanup.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Cleanup task

[Service]
Type=oneshot
ExecStart=/usr/bin/find %h/Downloads -mtime +30 -delete
EOF

cat >~/.config/systemd/user/cleanup.timer <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Weekly cleanup

[Timer]
OnCalendar=Sun 03:00                        # every sunday at 3am
Persistent=true                             # catch up if missed
RandomizedDelaySec=600                      # 0-10min jitter

[Install]
WantedBy=timers.target
EOF

systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable --now cleanup.timer

# list / debug timers
systemctl --user list-timers                # next + last fire times
systemctl --user status cleanup.timer

# OnCalendar syntax — the most common forms:
#   *-*-* 03:30:00      — every day at 03:30
#   Mon..Fri 09:00      — weekdays at 9am
#   *-*-01 00:00:00     — first of every month at midnight
#   hourly / daily / weekly / monthly       — convenient aliases
#   minutely / *:0/15   — every 15 minutes


# LINGER — USER SERVICES WITHOUT BEING LOGGED IN

# user services and timers only run while you're logged in. for a
# laptop that's usually fine. for a desktop or server, enable linger:
loginctl enable-linger "$USER"
# now user-instance units run from boot to shutdown regardless of
# logins. backups, agents, etc. work unattended.


# DROP-INS / systemctl edit — MODIFY UNITS THE RIGHT WAY

# DON'T edit /usr/lib/systemd/system/foo.service. it'll be overwritten
# on package upgrade. use a drop-in instead:
sudo systemctl edit sshd
# editor opens an empty file under /etc/systemd/system/sshd.service.d/
# called override.conf. anything you put there OVERLAYS the original.

# example: add MaxConnectionsPerSource to sshd:
#   [Service]
#   Environment=MAX_PER_SOURCE=10

# to edit the FULL unit (start with current contents instead of empty):
sudo systemctl edit --full sshd

# revert a drop-in:
sudo systemctl revert sshd


# TARGETS — WHAT BOOT IS REACHING

# the SysV "runlevels" replacement. fedora's default targets:
#
#   default.target          — symlink to one of:
#     multi-user.target     — text login, no GUI
#     graphical.target      — gdm + GUI session (workstation default)
#
# switch on the fly without rebooting:
sudo systemctl isolate multi-user.target     # drop to text mode (kills GUI)
sudo systemctl isolate graphical.target      # back to GUI

# permanent default:
sudo systemctl set-default multi-user.target
sudo systemctl get-default

# emergency / rescue (single-user, for repair):
#   add `systemd.unit=emergency.target` to kernel cmdline at GRUB.


# BOOT ANALYSIS

systemd-analyze                              # boot time summary
systemd-analyze blame                        # which units took longest
systemd-analyze critical-chain               # the boot critical path
systemd-analyze critical-chain sshd          # critical path for one unit
systemd-analyze plot > /tmp/boot.svg         # graphical boot timeline

# verify a unit file (catches typos before you reload):
systemd-analyze verify ~/.config/systemd/user/myapp.service


# RESOURCE LIMITS — CGROUPS WITHOUT FUSS

# every service runs in a cgroup. inspect:
systemctl status myapp                       # shows cgroup tree
systemd-cgls                                 # cgroup hierarchy
systemd-cgtop                                # top-like, by cgroup

# set limits on a running service (transient, until reload):
sudo systemctl set-property myapp MemoryMax=512M
sudo systemctl set-property myapp CPUQuota=200%       # 2 cores
sudo systemctl set-property myapp IOWeight=50

# persistent: add to a drop-in via `systemctl edit`.

# AD-HOC sandboxing — run a one-off command in its own cgroup:
systemd-run --user --pty --tty -p MemoryMax=256M htop
sudo systemd-run --unit=backup-now \
    -p MemoryMax=1G -p CPUQuota=50% \
    /usr/local/bin/my-backup-script


# QUICK REFERENCE — WHAT TO REACH FOR

#   "what's broken right now"          → systemctl --failed
#   "why did X fail"                   → journalctl -u X -n 100
#   "make this start at boot"          → systemctl enable --now X
#   "run my script weekly"             → write .service + .timer
#   "boot is slow"                     → systemd-analyze blame
#   "change a setting on a packaged service" → systemctl edit
#   "drop to text mode"                → systemctl isolate multi-user.target
#   "see what's hogging RAM/CPU"       → systemd-cgtop


PERIODIC MAINTENANCE — DO I HAVE TO RUN ANYTHING?
-------------------------------------------------

# short answer: almost never. fedora ships a stack of systemd
# timers that handle the recurring chores. the right move is to
# AUDIT what's already running rather than write cron jobs.


# THE ONE COMMAND THAT TELLS YOU EVERYTHING

systemctl list-timers --all
# columns: NEXT | LEFT | LAST | PASSED | UNIT | ACTIVATES

# typical fedora 44 workstation timers you'll see:
#
#   dnf-makecache.timer           — refresh dnf metadata cache (hourly)
#   fstrim.timer                  — TRIM SSDs (weekly)
#   logrotate.timer               — rotate /var/log files (daily)
#   man-db-cache-update.timer     — rebuild apropos index after man changes
#   unbound-anchor.timer          — refresh DNSSEC root anchor
#   systemd-tmpfiles-clean.timer  — clean /tmp, /var/tmp per rules
#   plocate-updatedb.timer        — only if plocate is installed
#   sysstat-*.timer               — only if sysstat is installed
#   raid-check.timer              — md array integrity, only if RAID exists


# THINGS PEOPLE THINK THEY NEED TO RUN BY HAND (BUT DON'T)

# fstrim — discard unused SSD blocks
sudo fstrim -av
# fstrim.timer runs this weekly. AND, on the default btrfs root,
# `discard=async` is in the mount options — continuous async
# discard at the filesystem level. manual fstrim is harmless but
# redundant.
systemctl status fstrim.timer
findmnt -no OPTIONS /        # look for discard=async

# updatedb — rebuild the locate database
sudo updatedb
# only meaningful if `plocate` (fedora's mlocate replacement) is
# installed. if it is, plocate-updatedb.timer runs it daily.
# workstation does NOT install plocate by default; many folks
# default to `fd` / `rg` / `find` and never miss it.
rpm -q plocate
systemctl status plocate-updatedb.timer

# dnf makecache — refresh repo metadata
sudo dnf makecache
# dnf-makecache.timer fires hourly with a random delay. only run
# manually right before a planned upgrade if you can't wait.

# journal cleanup
sudo journalctl --vacuum-size=500M
sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=2weeks
# journald already enforces SystemMaxUse (10% of /var/log, capped
# at 4 GiB). only run manually if you tightened the limits or
# need to free space NOW.


# THINGS YOU SHOULD ACTUALLY DO PERIODICALLY (HANDS-ON)

# 1. upgrade across releases — every ~6-13 months
#    (see UPGRADE STRATEGY)
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=NN
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot

# 2. trim orphans + old kernels — every few months
sudo dnf autoremove
# fedora keeps the 3 newest kernels by default (installonly_limit=3
# in /etc/dnf/dnf.conf). lower it to 2 if /boot is tight.

# 3. firmware updates — monthly is plenty
#    (see HARDWARE / FIRMWARE — fwupd)
sudo fwupdmgr refresh
sudo fwupdmgr get-updates
sudo fwupdmgr update

# 4. flatpak housekeeping — occasionally
flatpak update
flatpak uninstall --unused

# 5. btrfs balance — only on actual symptoms
sudo btrfs filesystem usage /
sudo btrfs balance start -dusage=50 -musage=50 /
# DO NOT schedule blanket scrubs or balances. scrub is heavy;
# balance rewrites blocks. let problems prompt you, not the clock.

# 6. SMART health glance — every few months
#    (smartd handles alerts automatically — see DISK MANAGEMENT)
sudo smartctl -H /dev/nvme0n1
sudo smartctl -a /dev/nvme0n1


# WRITING YOUR OWN TIMER (THE FEDORA WAY)

# full .service + .timer template lives in SYSTEMD — THE
# FOUNDATIONAL GLUE. quick version:

sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/my-maint.service >/dev/null <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=My maintenance task
[Service]
Type=oneshot
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/my-script
EOF

sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/my-maint.timer >/dev/null <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Run my maintenance task weekly
[Timer]
OnCalendar=weekly
Persistent=true
RandomizedDelaySec=1h
[Install]
WantedBy=timers.target
EOF

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable --now my-maint.timer

# Persistent=true catches up after a missed run (laptop was off).
# RandomizedDelaySec spreads load when many hosts share the timer.


# HONEST TRADEOFFS

# don't layer your own cron jobs on top of fedora's timer stack.
# you'll get duplicate work, journald loses unified visibility,
# and troubleshooting takes twice as long.

# resist scheduling "preventive" scrubs, autoremoves, or vacuums.
# fedora's defaults are well-tuned; meddling tends to cost more
# than it saves. add a timer when you have a real recurring need,
# not because "weekly cleanup sounds responsible."


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   what's running periodically?      → systemctl list-timers --all
#   trim my SSD?                      → already automated, ignore
#   rebuild locate db?                → install plocate; timer handles it
#   free /var/log space?              → journalctl --vacuum-size=500M
#   delete old kernels?               → dnf autoremove + installonly_limit
#   update firmware?                  → fwupdmgr refresh && update
#   schedule my own task?             → .service + .timer (see SYSTEMD)


USERS, GROUPS, AND SUDO
-----------------------

# the basics of multi-user admin. most of the rest of this
# primer assumes `sudo` works and that you understand which
# group gates which capability — both of which are surprisingly
# fedora-flavored.


# THE USER MODEL — WHERE THINGS LIVE

# fedora stores its local user database in three plain-text
# files (plus shadow), inherited from every unix since the 80s:
#
#   /etc/passwd  — username, UID, GID, home, shell (world-readable)
#   /etc/shadow  — password hashes + aging (root-only readable)
#   /etc/group   — group name, GID, member list
#   /etc/gshadow — group password hashes (rare)
#   /etc/subuid  — subordinate UID ranges (used by rootless podman)
#   /etc/subgid  — subordinate GID ranges (used by rootless podman)

# UID conventions on fedora:
#   0          → root
#   1-999      → system / service accounts
#   1000+      → human users (first user from anaconda gets 1000)
#
# (fedora moved system accounts up to 1-999 from the old 1-499.
# you'll see this if you read older guides.)

# read it like a database:
getent passwd                  # everyone the system can resolve
getent passwd $USER            # one entry
getent group wheel             # one group + members
getent group | grep $USER      # which groups am I in?
id                             # my UID, GID, groups (numeric + name)
id someuser                    # same for another user

# who's logged in right now / who recently was:
who
w                              # who + what they're running
last                           # login history
loginctl                       # systemd-logind's view of sessions


# CREATING, MODIFYING, REMOVING USERS

# the everyday commands. fedora ships `useradd`, `usermod`,
# `userdel` from shadow-utils — same as every other linux.

# create a user with a home dir and the default shell (bash)
sudo useradd -m -s /bin/bash alice
sudo passwd alice                   # set a password

# create a user already in the wheel group (admins)
sudo useradd -m -G wheel alice

# add an EXISTING user to a group WITHOUT removing them from
# their current groups (the -a is the safety belt):
sudo usermod -aG wheel,docker alice
# WITHOUT -a, -G REPLACES the secondary group list. that's a
# classic foot-gun: `usermod -G docker alice` will drop alice
# from wheel, video, etc. ALWAYS use `-aG`.

# rename / change shell / change home
sudo usermod -l newname oldname
sudo usermod -s /bin/zsh alice
sudo usermod -d /home/newhome -m alice

# remove a user (keep their home dir):
sudo userdel alice
# remove them AND their home + mail spool:
sudo userdel -r alice

# lock / unlock without changing the password:
sudo usermod -L alice                # lock
sudo usermod -U alice                # unlock
# or with passwd:
sudo passwd -l alice
sudo passwd -u alice

# groups are managed the same way:
sudo groupadd developers
sudo groupmod -n devs developers
sudo groupdel devs

# group membership changes don't apply to existing sessions.
# either log out and back in, or use:
newgrp <group>                       # in the current shell


# THE WHEEL GROUP — FEDORA'S ADMIN PATH

# `wheel` is the historical "can become root" group. fedora wires
# it to two things by default:
#
#   1. sudo  — /etc/sudoers ships with this rule:
#                %wheel  ALL=(ALL)  ALL
#              meaning: any user in the wheel group can run any
#              command as any user, after typing their OWN
#              password.
#
#   2. su    — /etc/pam.d/su includes pam_wheel.so via
#              `auth required pam_wheel.so use_uid` (commented
#              by default; uncomment to restrict `su` to wheel
#              members).
#
# the first user created by anaconda is automatically added to
# wheel. to confirm or grant wheel to someone else:
sudo usermod -aG wheel alice
groups alice                          # verify

# the GNOME "Administrator" toggle in Settings → Users does
# exactly this — flipping it adds/removes the user from wheel.


# SUDOERS — THE ONE RULE: DON'T EDIT /etc/sudoers DIRECTLY

# /etc/sudoers is a single file with bizarre syntax and a global
# lock. a typo there can lock everyone out of sudo, including
# you. NEVER edit it with vi/nano/code directly.
#
# instead, drop a file into /etc/sudoers.d/ with `visudo`'s
# syntax check:

sudo visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/10-myrule
# visudo: validates syntax on save, holds the sudoers lock,
# refuses to write if you produced something illegal.

# filename conventions: a numeric prefix orders files. avoid
# dots or tildes in the name — sudoers ignores files matching
# the `~` or containing `.` by default.

# example: a NOPASSWD entry for a specific maintenance script
sudo tee /etc/sudoers.d/20-deploy <<'EOF'
%developers ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/bin/deploy-prod
EOF
sudo chmod 0440 /etc/sudoers.d/20-deploy

# verify rules without invoking them:
sudo -l                              # what can I do?
sudo -l -U alice                     # what can alice do?
sudo -lU alice -i                    # alice's rules in her env

# the "I locked myself out of sudo" recovery is the
# `init=/bin/bash` trick — see BOOT TROUBLESHOOTING AND RESCUE.


# NOPASSWD — WHEN IT'S REASONABLE

# NOPASSWD is a real escalation surface. the question to ask is
# "does this command (or args pattern) give an attacker a path
# to arbitrary code execution?" if yes, don't NOPASSWD it.
#
# reasonable:
#   - a single well-vetted script with a fixed path
#   - read-only commands (NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/journalctl)
#   - service control for one specific service:
#       NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart myapp.service
#
# NOT reasonable:
#   - NOPASSWD: ALL (you may as well give them root)
#   - NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/vim (vim can `:!sh`)
#   - NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/find (find can `-exec`)
#   - NOPASSWD: any package manager or container runtime
#
# if you find yourself wanting NOPASSWD: ALL for ergonomics,
# consider whether a longer sudo timeout solves the problem:
#   Defaults  timestamp_timeout=30  (minutes; 0 = always ask;
#                                    -1 = never expire)
sudo tee /etc/sudoers.d/05-timeout <<'EOF'
Defaults  timestamp_timeout=30
EOF


# HARDWARE-GATING GROUPS

# linux uses unix groups as a coarse capability model for
# hardware access. the common ones on fedora workstation:
#
#   wheel       — sudo (above)
#   adm         — read access to /var/log (without sudo)
#   audio       — historical; PipeWire makes this mostly irrelevant
#   video       — /dev/video* (webcams), some GPU bits
#   render      — /dev/dri/renderD* (GPU compute, vaapi)
#   input       — /dev/input/* (raw HID — careful with this one)
#   dialout     — /dev/ttyUSB*, /dev/ttyACM* (serial, microcontrollers,
#                 USB CDC devices)
#   plugdev     — historical; udev/polkit handle most of this now
#   kvm         — /dev/kvm (virtualization)
#   libvirt     — libvirtd socket (manage VMs without sudo)
#   docker      — docker daemon socket
#   wireshark   — /usr/bin/dumpcap with cap_net_raw (no sudo to capture)
#
# WHY `docker` IS EFFECTIVELY ROOT:
#   the docker daemon runs as root. membership in the docker
#   group means you can mount / into a container and chroot
#   yourself to root. THIS IS NOT A SECURITY BOUNDARY. on
#   fedora, prefer rootless `podman` (see CONTAINERS) which
#   doesn't have this problem.
#
# add a user to one of these and the change applies to NEW
# sessions only:
sudo usermod -aG dialout alice
# verify:
id alice | tr , '\n' | grep dialout


# POLKIT (pkexec) VS SUDO — WHO HANDLES GUI AUTH

# the password prompts you see in GNOME Settings, gnome-disks,
# fwupd, gnome-software, etc., are NOT sudo. they're polkit
# (formerly PolicyKit). polkit:
#
#   - asks for YOUR password (admin-flagged) or root's
#   - delegates authorization to a daemon over D-Bus
#   - uses /etc/polkit-1/rules.d/ for custom rules (JavaScript)
#   - is what GNOME / KDE / Cockpit reach for
#
# sudo is for shell-out-and-do-it. polkit is for "the GUI is
# asking permission on your behalf."

# inspect polkit:
pkaction --verbose                    # all known actions
pkcheck --action-id org.x.y --process-of $$    # would I be allowed?

# admin group for polkit on fedora workstation: also `wheel`.
# (gnome reads /etc/polkit-1/rules.d/ + the polkit defaults.)

# the GUI command-line form:
pkexec gnome-disks                    # GUI tool with elevation


# SERVICE ACCOUNTS AND nologin SHELLS

# system accounts (UID 1-999) almost never have a login shell.
# they're meant to OWN files and RUN services, not log in.
# typical entries look like:
#
#   nginx:x:991:991::/var/lib/nginx:/sbin/nologin
#   postgres:x:26:26:PostgreSQL Server:/var/lib/pgsql:/bin/bash
#
# /sbin/nologin politely refuses ssh / su attempts; /bin/false
# is rude (just exits). both are fine — use nologin for
# clarity.

# create a system account (no login, system-range UID):
sudo useradd -r -s /sbin/nologin -d /var/lib/myapp -M myapp

# the systemd `User=` directive in a service unit references
# these accounts. see SYSTEMD for the unit pattern.

# don't try to manually create UIDs in the system range — let
# `useradd -r` pick. RPM packages claim specific UIDs sometimes
# (postgres=26, mysql=27), and you'll collide.


# PASSWORD AGING AND LOCKOUT

# `chage` controls password expiration and account lockout
# windows. fedora workstation doesn't enforce expiration by
# default; this matters on hardened / multi-user systems.

# inspect:
sudo chage -l alice

# set: max 90 days, warn at 7, minimum 1 day between changes
sudo chage -M 90 -W 7 -m 1 alice

# force a change at next login:
sudo chage -d 0 alice

# lock after N failed attempts via pam_faillock:
sudo authselect select sssd with-faillock     # ↑ enables faillock
# inspect failures:
sudo faillock --user alice
# clear lockout:
sudo faillock --user alice --reset

# (the older pam_tally2 module is deprecated; faillock is the
# fedora-current path.)


# AUTHSELECT — THE PAM CONFIG META-LAYER

# fedora wraps PAM config in `authselect` so you don't hand-edit
# /etc/pam.d/* anymore. it's a finite set of profiles + features.

sudo authselect current               # what profile is active?
sudo authselect list                  # available profiles
sudo authselect list-features sssd    # features for a profile
sudo authselect select sssd with-faillock with-mkhomedir

# rule of thumb: edit pam files only when authselect has no
# feature for what you need. otherwise authselect makes your
# life much easier — and survives system upgrades.


# CENTRAL IDENTITY — ONE-PARAGRAPH POINTER

# everything above is LOCAL accounts. on a real corporate
# network, identity lives in a directory (AD, LDAP, FreeIPA)
# and fedora joins it via sssd. the join is:
sudo dnf install sssd realmd adcli oddjob oddjob-mkhomedir
sudo realm discover example.com
sudo realm join example.com -U Administrator
# users authenticate against the directory; sudo rules can come
# from sssd-sudo too. on workstation this is uncommon; on
# enterprise it's the default. out of scope here — the docs
# live at sssd.io and freeipa.org.


# HONEST TRADEOFFS

# the temptation to add yourself to the `docker` group for
# ergonomics is real. don't. prefer rootless podman (CONTAINERS
# section). if you must use docker for some tooling, accept
# that the host is effectively single-user-root.

# NOPASSWD: ALL for "my dev box" is also tempting. don't. raise
# the sudo timeout instead. the friction NOPASSWD removes isn't
# worth the security hole.

# `usermod -G` without `-a` is the most common destructive user
# command. always type `-aG` reflexively — even when you mean to
# replace, set the new list explicitly so the destruction is
# obvious.

# editing /etc/sudoers directly is the most common "I locked
# myself out" mistake. always `visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/...`.


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   "am I in the wheel group?"        → groups | grep wheel
#   "make alice an admin"             → usermod -aG wheel alice
#   "add a system service account"    → useradd -r -s /sbin/nologin myapp
#   "passwordless sudo for one cmd"   → sudoers.d/ + NOPASSWD: /full/path
#   "extend the sudo cache window"    → Defaults timestamp_timeout=30
#   "verify a sudo rule"              → sudo -l   OR   sudo -lU alice
#   "edit sudo safely"                → sudo visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/<name>
#   "GUI just asked for a password"   → that's polkit, not sudo
#   "force password change next login"→ chage -d 0 alice
#   "user is locked out"              → faillock --user alice --reset
#   "join corporate AD"               → realm discover && realm join


