TTYS — VIRTUAL TERMINALS (CTRL+ALT+F-KEYS)
------------------------------------------

# every linux system runs MULTIPLE virtual terminals (TTYs) by
# default. you never see most of them — until your GUI breaks and
# they become your only path back in.

# on fedora workstation, the typical layout:
#
#   Ctrl+Alt+F1   — GDM (graphical login manager)
#   Ctrl+Alt+F2   — your active wayland session (the desktop you
#                   logged into)
#   Ctrl+Alt+F3   — plain text-mode TTY (login from scratch)
#   Ctrl+Alt+F4   — another text TTY
#   Ctrl+Alt+F5   — another text TTY
#   Ctrl+Alt+F6   — another text TTY
#
# the F1/F2 assignment shifts with the release and whether
# auto-login is enabled. F3-F6 are always plain TTYs you can log
# into independently.


# THE RESCUE FLOW — WHEN GNOME WEDGES

# 1. Ctrl+Alt+F3 — switch to a text TTY (the GUI is still running
#    in the background but not in front)
# 2. log in as your user
# 3. diagnose:
top                                            # what's hot
journalctl -b -p err                           # recent boot errors
journalctl -fu gdm                             # display manager logs
journalctl --user -f                           # user-session logs
# 4. fix it:
sudo systemctl restart gdm                     # restart the display mgr
# 5. Ctrl+Alt+F2 (or wherever GDM landed) — back to a fresh login


# THE COMMANDS

tty                                            # which TTY am I on
who -a                                         # who's logged in where
chvt 3                                         # switch to TTY 3 from
                                                # a script (the CLI
                                                # version of Ctrl+Alt+F3)
fgconsole                                      # number of current
                                                # foreground TTY
sudo openvt -s -- bash                         # start a process on
                                                # the next free TTY


# WHEN TTY ACCESS IS YOUR ONLY OPTION

# - GNOME / KDE wedged: switch to TTY → kill the wedged session →
#   log back in
# - GDM won't load: TTY → journalctl → fix → restart gdm
# - NVIDIA broke after a kernel update: TTY → akmods --force → reboot
#   (covered in NVIDIA section's failures list)
# - Disk full and the desktop can't render dialogs: TTY → free space
# - SELinux denial preventing graphical login: TTY → ausearch → fix
# - Power-related lockup post-suspend: TTY → kill driver, modprobe


# BOOTING DIRECTLY TO TEXT MODE

# add `3` (the multi-user.target shorthand) to the kernel cmdline at
# the GRUB menu — covered in the SYSTEMD targets section. drops you
# to TTY login without starting GDM. handy when GDM itself is the
# problem.


# CONFIGURING THE TTY COUNT (rare)

# default: 6 plain TTYs. change in logind.conf:
sudo vi /etc/systemd/logind.conf
# set NAutoVTs=N (default 6). restart systemd-logind.


# AUTOLOGIN ON A TTY (for kiosks, embedded use cases)

sudo mkdir -p /etc/systemd/system/getty@tty3.service.d
sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/getty@tty3.service.d/autologin.conf <<'EOF'
[Service]
ExecStart=
ExecStart=-/sbin/agetty --autologin myuser --noclear %I $TERM
EOF
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart getty@tty3


GRUB — SHOWING THE MENU, MANAGING KERNELS
-----------------------------------------

# fedora ships GRUB2 with two layers of menu-hiding stacked on top of each
# other, which is why "I want to see the menu on boot" is a recurring
# fedora question. the layers:
#
#   1. /etc/default/grub        — GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE / GRUB_TIMEOUT
#   2. grubenv `menu_auto_hide` — fedora-specific "hide if last boot OK"
#
# you have to defeat BOTH to get a reliable menu on every boot.


# THE FIX (do all three for a permanent visible menu):

# 1. edit /etc/default/grub:
sudo vi /etc/default/grub
#    set or add:
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=menu          (default: "hidden" — this is the key flag)
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT=5                   (seconds; -1 = wait indefinitely for input)
#       GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU=true        (flatten "Advanced options" so EVERY
#                                         kernel shows at the top level instead
#                                         of being hidden in a submenu)
#       GRUB_DEFAULT=saved               (default is "saved" — remembers your
#                                         last selection. 0 = always first entry)

# 2. regenerate grub.cfg. on fedora 34+ the path is unified for BIOS + UEFI:
sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
#    older UEFI installs may still use:
#       sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/efi/EFI/fedora/grub.cfg
#    check which one exists on your system if the first command's output
#    looks too small.

# 3. disable fedora's auto-hide (the bit that hides the menu when the
#    PREVIOUS boot succeeded — independent of GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE):
sudo grub2-editenv - list                          # see current vars
sudo grub2-editenv - unset menu_auto_hide          # show menu every boot
sudo grub2-editenv - unset boot_success            # clear the "last boot ok" flag
sudo grub2-editenv - unset boot_indeterminate      # clear "boot uncertain" flag

# verify after reboot. if the menu still hides, check `boot_success` keeps
# getting set — it's written by the user-systemd unit grub-boot-success.timer
# (~2.5 minutes after login). mask it if you want to be extra sure:
systemctl --user mask grub-boot-success.timer


# ONE-SHOT SHOW MENU AT BOOT (no config changes):
#   - UEFI: hold/tap Esc (or F8 on some firmware) at POST
#   - BIOS legacy: hold Shift
# Shift on UEFI usually does NOT work — common source of "I tried shift and
# nothing happened". use Esc on modern hardware.


# UNDERSTANDING THE MENU ENTRIES — BootLoaderSpec:

# since fedora 30, GRUB entries are NOT generated into grub.cfg the old
# way. instead each kernel is a separate .conf file in /boot/loader/entries/.
# the kernel package install drops a file there; GRUB discovers them at
# boot. NO grub2-mkconfig needed when a new kernel lands.
ls /boot/loader/entries/
cat /boot/loader/entries/*.conf | head -30

# the format (one entry per .conf):
#   title    Fedora Linux 44 (Workstation Edition) (6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64)
#   version  6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64
#   linux    /vmlinuz-6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64
#   initrd   /initramfs-6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64.img
#   options  root=UUID=... ro rhgb quiet ...
#   grub_users $grub_users
#   grub_arg --unrestricted
#   grub_class fedora


# `grubby` IS THE TOOL for managing these entries (don't hand-edit):

# list every installed kernel entry
sudo grubby --info=ALL

# show just the default
sudo grubby --default-kernel
sudo grubby --default-index
sudo grubby --default-title

# set a different default
sudo grubby --set-default=/boot/vmlinuz-6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64
sudo grubby --set-default-index=2

# add a kernel command-line argument permanently (writes to every entry
# AND to /etc/kernel/cmdline so future kernels get it too)
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args='quiet splash'

# remove an argument
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --remove-args='quiet'

# remove a specific kernel entry (rare — usually let dnf handle it)
sudo grubby --remove-kernel=/boot/vmlinuz-6.10.3-200.fc44.x86_64


# KERNEL RETENTION — how many show up in the menu:

# fedora keeps the most recent 3 kernels by default. controlled by:
grep installonly_limit /etc/dnf/dnf.conf            # default: 3
#    bump it if you want more rollback options:
#       installonly_limit=5

# the rescue entry is generated once at install time as a special BLS
# entry — it's a kernel + initramfs frozen at install. don't expect it
# to track your current kernel. regenerate after a major upgrade:
sudo /etc/kernel/install.d/51-dracut-rescue.install add \
    $(uname -r) /boot $(uname -r)/initrd


# QUICK MENU INSPECTION:
sudo grub2-editenv - list                           # grubenv vars
sudo grubby --info=ALL | grep -E '^(index|title)='  # what the menu will show
ls /boot/loader/entries/                            # BLS entry files
cat /etc/default/grub                               # high-level config
cat /etc/kernel/cmdline                             # default cmdline for new kernels


# RECOMMENDED CONFIG for "show me everything, every boot":
#
#   /etc/default/grub:
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=menu
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT=5
#       GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU=true
#       GRUB_DEFAULT=saved
#
#   grubenv:
#       sudo grub2-editenv - unset menu_auto_hide
#
#   then:
#       sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
#       reboot


KERNEL CMDLINE — A CHEATSHEET
-----------------------------

# kernel boot parameters tune everything from GPU drivers to security
# mitigations to early boot debugging. they're scattered across this
# primer (NVIDIA, POWER MANAGEMENT, TPM2 LUKS, SYSTEMD targets, TTYs).
# this section is the unified reference.


# WHERE THE CMDLINE LIVES

# on fedora, kernel arguments are configured per-kernel via the
# BootLoaderSpec entries (covered in GRUB section). also tracked in
# /etc/kernel/cmdline for future kernels.
#
# inspect what's currently in effect:
cat /proc/cmdline                              # this boot's actual args
sudo grubby --info=DEFAULT                     # default entry's args
sudo grubby --info=ALL | grep args             # every entry's args
cat /etc/kernel/cmdline                        # default for new kernels


# MODIFYING — grubby IS THE TOOL

# DON'T edit /etc/default/grub for argument changes on fedora. that
# file controls grub-mkconfig output but isn't consulted by
# BootLoaderSpec. use grubby.

# add args persistently to every kernel:
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args="mitigations=off"
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args="nvidia-drm.modeset=1"

# remove an arg:
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --remove-args="quiet"

# add to just the DEFAULT kernel (not future ones):
sudo grubby --update-kernel=DEFAULT --args="acpi_osi=Linux"

# combine add + remove in one command:
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL \
    --args="mitigations=auto,nosmt" \
    --remove-args="mitigations=off"


# ONE-SHOT EDIT AT THE GRUB MENU

# you don't have to persist changes. at the GRUB menu (visible after
# the changes in the GRUB section):
#   1. highlight the kernel entry
#   2. press `e` to edit
#   3. find the `linux` line; edit the args
#   4. Ctrl+X or F10 to boot ONCE with the modified args
# next reboot reverts to the saved config. ideal for rescue: try a
# parameter, see if it helps, then make it permanent with grubby.


# COMMON PARAMETERS — BY CATEGORY

# BOOT MODE
#   quiet rhgb                       — fedora default (suppress most
#                                      output, Plymouth animation)
#   3                                — boot to multi-user.target (text
#                                      mode, no GDM). same as
#                                      systemd.unit=multi-user.target
#   1 / S / single                   — single-user rescue (root shell)
#   systemd.unit=emergency.target    — emergency target (most minimal)
#   systemd.unit=rescue.target       — rescue target (one step up
#                                      from emergency)

# GRAPHICS / DISPLAY
#   nomodeset                        — disable KMS entirely. last-resort
#                                      rescue for broken GPU drivers
#                                      (booting to a glitched display).
#   nouveau.modeset=0                — disable nouveau (do this before
#                                      installing nvidia proprietary)
#   nvidia-drm.modeset=1             — enable nvidia DRM modeset
#                                      (required for clean wayland)
#   i915.enable_psr=0                — disable intel Panel Self Refresh
#                                      (fixes display flicker on some
#                                      laptops)
#   i915.enable_fbc=0                — disable intel framebuffer
#                                      compression
#   video=eDP-1:1920x1080@60         — force a display mode (debug)
#   fbcon=rotate:1                   — rotate the framebuffer console

# POWER MANAGEMENT
#   intel_idle.max_cstate=1          — limit intel CPU C-states (rare;
#                                      kills battery, used for some
#                                      buggy chipsets)
#   processor.max_cstate=1           — same idea, broader scope
#   mem_sleep_default=deep           — prefer S3 over s2idle on
#                                      supporting hardware
#   pcie_aspm=off                    — disable PCIe Active State Power
#                                      Management (rare; fixes some
#                                      wifi card crashes)

# STORAGE / BOOT / LUKS
#   root=UUID=...                    — the root filesystem UUID
#   rootfstype=btrfs                 — explicit fs type
#   rootflags=subvol=root            — mount the @ subvolume
#   resume=UUID=...                  — hibernation resume target
#   resume_offset=N                  — for swapfile-on-btrfs hibernate
#   rd.luks.uuid=...                 — LUKS UUID to unlock at boot
#   rd.luks.options=tpm2-device=auto — TPM2 unlock (see TPM2 LUKS section)

# SECURITY / CPU MITIGATIONS
#   mitigations=off                  — disable ALL CPU mitigations
#                                      (Spectre / Meltdown / etc.).
#                                      ~5-30% perf wins on some
#                                      workloads. security cost is
#                                      real. only for trusted boxes.
#   mitigations=auto,nosmt           — auto-pick mitigations + disable
#                                      SMT/HT for stronger isolation
#   spectre_v2=off / nopti           — disable specific mitigations
#                                      individually

# VIRTUALIZATION / IOMMU
#   intel_iommu=on                   — enable Intel VT-d (for VFIO /
#                                      GPU passthrough)
#   amd_iommu=on                     — AMD equivalent
#   iommu=pt                         — passthrough mode (less overhead
#                                      for the host)
#   vfio-pci.ids=10de:1234,10de:5678 — bind specific PCI IDs to VFIO
#                                      (the GPU passthrough recipe)

# CGROUPS
#   systemd.unified_cgroup_hierarchy=0 — DISABLE cgroups v2 (revert to
#                                        v1). rare; needed for some
#                                        ancient docker setups (modern
#                                        docker / podman handle v2)

# ACPI WORKAROUNDS
#   acpi_osi=Linux                   — claim "Linux" identity in ACPI
#                                      tables (fixes some firmware
#                                      that gate-keep features on
#                                      OS detection)
#   acpi_osi='!Windows 2012'         — pretend to be older windows
#   acpi_backlight=vendor / video    — force backlight handler
#   acpi=off                         — disable ACPI entirely (NEVER
#                                      use as anything but last-resort
#                                      diagnostic)

# DEBUG / TROUBLESHOOTING
#   debug                            — verbose kernel logs
#   loglevel=7                       — show debug messages (0-7)
#   earlyprintk=vga                  — print early boot logs to VGA
#   console=tty0 console=ttyS0,115200n8  — also log to serial (useful
#                                          for remote diagnosis)
#   initcall_debug                   — log every init function called


# WORKFLOW PATTERNS

# 1. "MY GPU IS BROKEN; I CAN'T REACH GUI"
#    at GRUB: press `e`, add `nomodeset 3`, Ctrl+X. you'll boot to
#    text mode with no graphics drivers. fix from there.
#
# 2. "I WANT MAXIMUM PERF AND ACCEPT THE SECURITY TRADE"
#    sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args="mitigations=off"
#    reboot. typical wins: 5-15% on database workloads, more on heavily
#    syscall-bound code.
#
# 3. "I NEED TO DEBUG AN EARLY BOOT HANG"
#    at GRUB: press `e`, remove `quiet rhgb`, add `debug loglevel=7`.
#    boot, see the wall of dmesg as it happens.
#
# 4. "I WANT GPU PASSTHROUGH TO A VM"
#    sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args="intel_iommu=on iommu=pt"
#    plus vfio-pci.ids= with the IDs of your passthrough GPU. see
#    VIRTUAL MACHINES section.
#
# 5. "HIBERNATE BROKE AFTER A CHANGE"
#    verify the resume= arg matches your swap:
cat /proc/cmdline | grep -o 'resume=[^ ]*'
#    fix with grubby if wrong. see POWER MANAGEMENT section.
#
# 6. "WAYLAND TEARING / FLICKER ON NVIDIA OR INTEL"
#    nvidia: ensure `nvidia-drm.modeset=1` (default in modern drivers
#    but verify).
#    intel: try `i915.enable_psr=0` if you see flicker around video
#    playback.


