BOOT TROUBLESHOOTING AND RESCUE
-------------------------------

# the "something just broke, what now?" section. write this
# down BEFORE you need it — once the machine won't boot, you
# don't want to be reading docs on your phone.


# THE BOOT STAGES (KNOW WHERE YOU'RE FAILING)

# fedora's boot is a chain — each link can fail differently.
# matching the symptom to the stage is half the diagnosis.
#
#   1. firmware (UEFI or BIOS)
#        symptom: nothing on screen, "no bootable device", drive
#        not in boot order. fix lives in the firmware menu (F2 /
#        F10 / F12 / Esc — vendor-specific), not in fedora.
#
#   2. bootloader (shim → GRUB on UEFI; GRUB on BIOS)
#        symptom: "grub rescue>" prompt, GRUB hangs, EFI entry
#        gone. fix: GRUB reinstall + grub2-mkconfig, efibootmgr.
#
#   3. kernel + initramfs (loaded from /boot)
#        symptom: kernel panic, "VFS: Unable to mount root fs",
#        "you are in emergency mode" with luks/btrfs errors.
#        fix: pick an older kernel, rd.break, rebuild initramfs.
#
#   4. systemd early boot (initramfs → systemd in real root)
#        symptom: drops to emergency.target, single failing
#        service, /etc/fstab error.
#        fix: emergency / rescue target, systemctl --failed.
#
#   5. user session (GDM, wayland, gnome-shell)
#        symptom: black screen after login, no display manager,
#        "oh no, something has gone wrong."
#        fix: TTY login (Ctrl+Alt+F3), check journalctl -u gdm,
#        roll back graphics driver. that's a user-session
#        problem, not a boot problem — different toolkit.


# STAGE 2/3 RECIPES — FROM THE GRUB MENU

# the GRUB menu is your first line of defense. if you can see it,
# you can get out of almost any kernel/initramfs problem.

# show the menu reliably (covered fully in the GRUB section):
sudo grub2-editenv - unset menu_auto_hide

# pick an older kernel
#   GRUB main menu → "Advanced options for Fedora" → choose
#   previous kernel. fedora keeps 3 by default (installonly_limit).

# edit ONE boot's kernel cmdline (no permanent change)
#   highlight the entry → press `e` → edit the `linux ...` line
#   → Ctrl+x to boot with it. survives this boot only.

# useful args to APPEND for diagnostics (see KERNEL CMDLINE):
#   single                  → boot to rescue.target
#   systemd.unit=rescue.target
#   systemd.unit=emergency.target
#   systemd.unit=multi-user.target   → text mode, no GDM
#   rd.break                → shell BEFORE pivoting to real root
#   rd.shell                → shell only if initramfs fails
#   rd.debug                → very loud initramfs logging
#   plymouth.enable=0       → kill the splash; see actual messages
#   systemd.log_level=debug → wall-of-text but answers most things

# pick the btrfs snapshot submenu (if grub-btrfs is installed)
#   GRUB → "Fedora Linux snapshots" → boot a snapshot read-only
#   → from inside, `snapper rollback` to make it permanent.
#   see BTRFS SNAPSHOTS for the full flow.


# STAGE 3/4 RECIPES — TARGETS AS RECOVERY ROOMS

# systemd targets are basically "how much of the system do you
# want running while you fix it." rescue is small; emergency is
# smaller; multi-user is "normal but no GUI."

#   emergency.target   — minimal, / mounted read-only, no other
#                        filesystems, root shell. for "/etc/fstab
#                        is wedged" situations.
#   rescue.target      — single-user mode, all filesystems mounted,
#                        root shell. for "I can repair from here."
#   multi-user.target  — text-mode multi-user (think old runlevel 3).
#                        for "GUI is broken, login normally and
#                        debug from a real session."
#   graphical.target   — the default; GUI up.

# from a running system:
sudo systemctl rescue        # drops to single-user
sudo systemctl emergency     # drops to emergency shell
sudo systemctl isolate multi-user.target   # kill the GUI, stay multi-user
sudo systemctl isolate graphical.target    # bring the GUI back

# from GRUB (append to the kernel line):
systemd.unit=rescue.target
systemd.unit=emergency.target

# you'll be prompted for the root password. if root has no
# password (the modern default), see the next recipe.


# STAGE 3 ESCAPE HATCH — init=/bin/bash

# the nuclear option: replace pid 1 with a shell. NO services
# run, / is read-only by default, but you can remount and edit.
# useful when emergency target also can't authenticate (forgot
# root password, sudoers broken).

#   GRUB → `e` on a kernel → append to the linux line:
init=/bin/bash rw

# once you're in:
mount -o remount,rw /
passwd                 # reset root password
# or edit whatever was breaking:
vi /etc/fstab
touch /.autorelabel    # if you touched SELinux-labeled files
exec /sbin/init        # try to continue boot, or:
sync; reboot -f


# STAGE 3 SHELLS — RD.BREAK AND FRIENDS

# rd.break drops a shell INSIDE the initramfs, BEFORE the real
# root is mounted at /. useful for "the kernel boots but the
# real root won't mount" — usually LUKS or /etc/crypttab issues.

# append to the kernel cmdline:
rd.break

# you'll land in a dracut shell. the real root (when mounted)
# lives at /sysroot. typical recovery dance:
mount -o remount,rw /sysroot
chroot /sysroot
# now /sysroot's tree is your /
passwd                          # fix root pw, or
vi /etc/crypttab                # fix luks setup, or
dracut --force                  # rebuild initramfs

# exit twice (chroot → dracut shell) and the boot continues.

# rd.shell — only drops a shell if the initramfs FAILS. nice
# permanent addition to a flaky machine's cmdline.
# rd.debug   — enormous extra logging. pair with `systemd.log_level=debug`.


# STAGE 4 — THE SYSTEMD DEBUG SHELL

# debug-shell.service exposes a root shell on TTY9 (Ctrl+Alt+F9)
# with no auth. useful when login is broken but boot succeeded.
sudo systemctl enable --now debug-shell.service
# DO NOT leave this enabled — it's a literal authless root
# shell on a TTY. turn it off the moment you're done:
sudo systemctl disable --now debug-shell.service


# "BOOTS BUT NO SSH" RECIPE

# if the box boots into multi-user but sshd isn't up, and you
# can't get physical access:
#
#   from physical TTY:
systemctl status sshd
journalctl -u sshd -n 100
sudo systemctl start sshd
#
#   if firewalld blocked it:
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=ssh
sudo firewall-cmd --runtime-to-permanent
#
#   if SELinux blocked it (rare but happens after sshd_config
#   edits with custom ports):
sudo journalctl -t setroubleshoot -n 50
sudo semanage port -a -t ssh_port_t -p tcp <newport>


# THE BIG ONE — LIVE-USB CHROOT RECOVERY

# when nothing on the disk will boot, the standard rescue is:
# boot a fedora live USB → unlock + mount the real root →
# chroot in → fix it → exit and reboot.

# step 1 — boot any fedora workstation live USB (same major
# version is ideal but not required; rescue ISOs at
# getfedora.org/security/ work too)

# step 2 — find the disks
sudo lsblk -f
# you're looking for: an EFI partition (vfat, /boot/efi),
# the /boot partition (ext4 by default), and the LUKS
# container (crypto_LUKS) that holds your btrfs root.

# step 3 — unlock LUKS (if encrypted, which is the F44
# workstation default)
sudo cryptsetup open /dev/nvme0n1p3 luks-root
# now /dev/mapper/luks-root is the unlocked btrfs.

# step 4 — mount the btrfs root subvolume
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/sysroot
sudo mount -o subvol=root /dev/mapper/luks-root /mnt/sysroot

# step 5 — mount the other partitions inside it
sudo mount /dev/nvme0n1p2 /mnt/sysroot/boot          # /boot (ext4)
sudo mount /dev/nvme0n1p1 /mnt/sysroot/boot/efi      # EFI (vfat)
# (find your actual partition numbers from lsblk -f above.)

# step 6 — bind-mount the virtual fs so chroot tooling works
for d in dev proc sys run; do
    sudo mount --bind /$d /mnt/sysroot/$d
done
# resolv.conf so dnf can hit the network if you need it:
sudo cp /etc/resolv.conf /mnt/sysroot/etc/resolv.conf

# step 7 — chroot in
sudo chroot /mnt/sysroot /bin/bash
# you're now operating as if you booted normally.

# at this point the repair menu is open. common moves:

#   regenerate initramfs (most kernel/initramfs problems):
dracut --force --regenerate-all -v

#   regenerate GRUB config:
grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg

#   reinstall the bootloader — UEFI:
dnf reinstall grub2-efi-x64 shim-x64 grub2-efi-x64-modules
grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/efi/EFI/fedora/grub.cfg   # NOT /boot/grub2/...
#   reinstall the bootloader — BIOS (legacy):
grub2-install /dev/nvme0n1
grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg

#   re-add the boot entry to UEFI NVRAM (when efibootmgr lost it):
efibootmgr -c -d /dev/nvme0n1 -p 1 -L "Fedora" \
    -l '\EFI\fedora\shimx64.efi'

#   queue an SELinux relabel for next boot:
touch /.autorelabel
# (slow on first boot. only do this if you edited /etc as root
# in the chroot — SELinux contexts on new files will be wrong.)

#   fix /etc/fstab (typo in mount options is a common cause
#   of "boot drops to emergency.target"):
vi /etc/fstab

# step 8 — back out cleanly
exit                                         # leave chroot
for d in run sys proc dev; do
    sudo umount /mnt/sysroot/$d
done
sudo umount /mnt/sysroot/boot/efi
sudo umount /mnt/sysroot/boot
sudo umount /mnt/sysroot
sudo cryptsetup close luks-root
sudo reboot


# FILESYSTEM-LEVEL REPAIR

# do this from the live USB, NOT from a running system.
# the target filesystem MUST be unmounted.

# ext4 (e.g. /boot):
sudo e2fsck -fy /dev/nvme0n1p2

# xfs (rare on fedora workstation; common on server installs):
sudo xfs_repair /dev/sdXN

# btrfs — try to mount with rescue options BEFORE running check:
sudo mount -o ro,rescue=all /dev/mapper/luks-root /mnt/sysroot
# if that works, copy data off. if not:
sudo btrfs check /dev/mapper/luks-root            # read-only diagnosis
# DO NOT run `btrfs check --repair` unless a known-good backup
# exists and the upstream wiki recommends it for your symptom.
# it has a real history of making things worse. prefer:
sudo mount -o usebackuproot /dev/mapper/luks-root /mnt/sysroot
# (uses an older root tree generation. mount as ro until you
# verify the data looks right.)


# HONEST TRADEOFFS

# the fastest recovery is almost always: pick an older kernel
# from GRUB, OR pick a btrfs snapshot. only reach for the
# live-USB chroot when those don't work.

# do not chroot from a live USB whose fedora version is OLDER
# than the installed system — running newer userspace through
# older kernel headers usually works, but the reverse breaks
# weirdly. prefer same-version or newer rescue media.

# `touch /.autorelabel` is annoying (slow first boot) but
# rarely harmful. if in doubt, do it — wrong SELinux contexts
# cause boot-time mystery failures that are hard to debug later.

# always note which kernel was working BEFORE the bad upgrade:
#   uname -r          # before the change
#   sudo grubby --info=ALL | grep '^title' # full inventory
# this lets you boot back to a known-good kernel from GRUB
# without rescue media at all.


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   show GRUB menu                  → grub2-editenv - unset menu_auto_hide
#   boot old kernel                 → GRUB → Advanced options
#   edit one boot's cmdline         → GRUB → highlight → `e`
#   boot from a btrfs snapshot      → grub-btrfs submenu (see BTRFS SNAPSHOTS)
#   drop to single-user             → kernel cmdline: systemd.unit=rescue.target
#   drop to a shell, /             → kernel cmdline: init=/bin/bash rw
#   shell inside initramfs         → kernel cmdline: rd.break
#   shell on TTY9 (already booted) → systemctl enable --now debug-shell.service
#   live-USB chroot                → cryptsetup open + mount + bind + chroot
#   rebuild initramfs              → dracut --force --regenerate-all
#   rebuild GRUB                   → grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
#   reinstall UEFI bootloader      → dnf reinstall grub2-efi-x64 shim-x64
#   re-add UEFI NVRAM entry        → efibootmgr -c ...
#   fix SELinux labels             → touch /.autorelabel; reboot
#   read-only btrfs (last resort)  → mount -o usebackuproot,ro


