REPOS — OFFICIAL, RPM FUSION, COPR, FLATHUB
-------------------------------------------

# stock fedora repos cover free software only. enable these for the
# common "I want chrome / nvidia / mp3 codecs" needs:

# 1. RPM Fusion (free + nonfree codecs, multimedia, nvidia drivers):
sudo dnf install \
    https://mirrors.rpmfusion.org/free/fedora/rpmfusion-free-release-$(rpm -E %fedora).noarch.rpm \
    https://mirrors.rpmfusion.org/nonfree/fedora/rpmfusion-nonfree-release-$(rpm -E %fedora).noarch.rpm

# 2. flathub (cross-distro app sandboxing). fedora preconfigures a
#    filtered subset; add full flathub for everything:
flatpak remote-add --if-not-exists flathub \
    https://flathub.org/repo/flathub.flatpakrepo
flatpak remote-modify --enable flathub

# 3. COPR (community per-developer repos — same idea as the AUR, but with
#    binaries built on koji infrastructure):
sudo dnf copr enable user/project
sudo dnf install <pkg>

# multimedia codecs — the one-time setup most people want post-install:
sudo dnf swap ffmpeg-free ffmpeg --allowerasing
sudo dnf install gstreamer1-plugins-{bad-\*,good-\*,base} gstreamer1-plugin-openh264 \
    gstreamer1-plugins-bad-free-extras lame\* --exclude=gstreamer1-plugins-bad-free-devel


SELINUX — KEEP IT ENFORCING
---------------------------

# fedora's SELinux policy is mature. the right answer to AVC denials is
# almost never "permissive" or "disabled" — it's usually a missing label
# (`restorecon`) or a small policy adjustment (`audit2allow`).

# check status
sestatus
getenforce                                          # Enforcing / Permissive / Disabled

# investigate recent denials
sudo ausearch -m AVC -ts recent
sudo journalctl -b -t setroubleshoot

# auto-suggested fixes (read before applying)
sudo sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log

# common fix: relabel a file/dir to its policy-expected context
sudo restorecon -Rv /path/to/thing

# temporary permissive (next boot back to enforcing — useful for triage)
sudo setenforce 0

# DON'T disable in /etc/selinux/config unless you know exactly why.
# disabled SELinux means an unlabeled filesystem; turning it back on
# requires an autorelabel boot.


SELINUX — GOING DEEPER
----------------------

# the SELINUX section above covers the 80% answer: keep it enforcing,
# restorecon when things break, sealert for diagnostics. this section
# is the next 15% — what to do when restorecon doesn't fix it.


# THE MENTAL MODEL

# every process has a TYPE (e.g. httpd_t). every file has a TYPE
# (httpd_config_t, httpd_sys_content_t, etc.). the SELinux policy is
# a giant list of rules saying "type X can do action Y on type Z".
#
# the format you'll see everywhere is "user:role:type:level":
#   system_u:object_r:httpd_config_t:s0
#
# 95% of the time, only the TYPE (third field) matters for
# troubleshooting. user / role / level are MLS infrastructure for
# multi-level secure systems that desktop fedora doesn't use.
#
# inspect labels:
ls -Z /etc/httpd/conf/                           # files
ps -Z                                            # running processes
id -Z                                            # current user / process


# THE AUDIT2ALLOW WORKFLOW

# the canonical "write a tiny policy module to allow a denial":
#
# 1. reproduce the denial (run the thing that's failing)
# 2. read the AVC:
sudo ausearch -m AVC -ts recent
#    (or sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log for the friendly version)
#
# 3. pipe the AVC into audit2allow to generate a policy module:
sudo ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | audit2allow -M my-customrule
#    creates: my-customrule.te (source) + my-customrule.pp (compiled)
#
# 4. READ THE GENERATED .te FILE BEFORE INSTALLING.
#    if it's allowing something that looks too broad ("allow X type Y
#    *" with wildcards), narrow it manually before installing. don't
#    just trust audit2allow's output.
cat my-customrule.te
#
# 5. install:
sudo semodule -i my-customrule.pp
#
# 6. verify it worked:
sudo semodule -l | grep my-customrule
#    rerun the failing operation; the denial should be gone.

# common iteration pattern:
sudo ausearch -m AVC --start recent --raw | audit2allow -M attempt1
# inspect, refine, install. if more denials surface (rules often
# cascade), repeat.


# BOOLEANS — TOGGLE COMMON POLICY DECISIONS

# many common "should this be allowed" decisions are exposed as
# BOOLEANS — pre-shipped toggles that don't require writing custom
# policy.

getsebool -a                                     # all booleans
getsebool -a | grep -i http                      # filter
semanage boolean -l                              # with descriptions

# toggle (the -P makes it persist across reboot — without it, reverts
# on the next boot):
sudo setsebool -P httpd_can_network_connect on
sudo setsebool -P samba_export_all_rw on

# booleans worth knowing on a typical fedora workstation:
#
#   httpd_can_network_connect           — let apache make outbound conns
#   httpd_can_network_connect_db        — apache → database server
#   httpd_unified                       — apache write to its own dirs
#   samba_export_all_rw                 — samba serve any path RW
#   samba_share_nfs                     — samba share an NFS-mounted dir
#   nfs_export_all_rw                   — let NFS export any RW path
#   virt_use_nfs                        — VMs can read NFS shares
#   virt_use_samba                      — VMs can read SMB shares
#   container_use_devices               — containers can use /dev/*
#   ssh_chroot_rw_homedirs              — ssh chroot can write to home
#   use_nfs_home_dirs                   — home dirs on NFS
#   xserver_object_manager              — for some X11 / wayland tools
#
# the boolean approach is preferred over custom policy when one exists
# — fewer moving parts, fewer security surprises.


# FILE CONTEXTS — RELABELING THE RIGHT WAY

# files inherit type from their PARENT DIRECTORY by default. moving a
# file from /var/www/html to /home/me preserves the OLD type, which
# breaks apache.

# inspect what type SHOULD be assigned:
sudo matchpathcon /var/www/html/index.html
sudo matchpathcon -V /var/www/html/index.html    # is it correct?

# restorecon — apply the policy's "correct" labels (most common fix):
sudo restorecon -Rv /var/www/html               # recursive, verbose
sudo restorecon -RFv /var/www/html              # force (re-label every
                                                # file, not just wrong)

# chcon — change context BUT not in policy. survives until next
# `restorecon` (volatile). useful for ONE-OFF experimentation.
sudo chcon -t httpd_sys_content_t /tmp/test.html

# semanage fcontext — change the POLICY's idea of what a path should
# be labeled. then restorecon to apply. permanent.
sudo semanage fcontext -a -t httpd_sys_content_t '/srv/www(/.*)?'
sudo restorecon -Rv /srv/www

# delete a policy file-context entry:
sudo semanage fcontext -d '/srv/www(/.*)?'

# list custom file-context entries (everything YOU added):
sudo semanage fcontext -l -C


# PORT LABELING — RUNNING SERVICES ON NON-STANDARD PORTS

# sshd on port 22 = labeled ssh_port_t. sshd on port 2222 = labeled
# unreserved_port_t which sshd's policy doesn't allow it to bind to.
# the failure mode is "the service starts but exits immediately."

# list existing port labels:
sudo semanage port -l | grep ssh
sudo semanage port -l | grep http

# add a port to a type:
sudo semanage port -a -t ssh_port_t -p tcp 2222
sudo semanage port -a -t http_port_t -p tcp 8080

# the canonical apache on 8080 incantation. and the canonical
# "I moved sshd to a non-standard port and now it won't start"
# incantation.

# delete (rare; usually you want to add, not remove):
sudo semanage port -d -t ssh_port_t -p tcp 2222


# PERMISSIVE DOMAINS — TRIAGE WITHOUT DROPPING GLOBAL ENFORCEMENT

# `setenforce 0` makes the whole system permissive. too coarse.
# instead, set ONE DOMAIN permissive while everything else stays
# enforcing. useful for "this one service is misbehaving; i need to
# see what it's trying to do without blocking it":
sudo semanage permissive -a httpd_t              # httpd permissive
sudo semanage permissive -d httpd_t              # back to enforcing

# list currently-permissive domains:
sudo semanage permissive -l


# CUSTOM POLICY MODULES — WHEN AUDIT2ALLOW ISN'T QUITE RIGHT

# audit2allow generates the simplest possible rule. sometimes you
# need something more nuanced — interfaces, transitions, conditional
# policy. write a .te file by hand.

cat > my-app.te <<'EOF'
policy_module(my-app, 1.0.0)

require {
    type httpd_t;
    type my_app_t;
    class file { read write };
}

allow httpd_t my_app_t:file { read write };
EOF

# compile + install:
sudo dnf install policycoreutils-devel selinux-policy-devel
make -f /usr/share/selinux/devel/Makefile my-app.pp
sudo semodule -i my-app.pp

# remove a custom module:
sudo semodule -r my-app


# DIAGNOSTIC TOOLING — THE FULL CHAIN

sudo journalctl -t setroubleshoot -b           # human-readable
                                                # denial summaries
sudo sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log       # suggested fixes
                                                # for recent denials
sudo ausearch -m AVC -ts today                 # raw AVCs since today
sudo ausearch -m AVC -c httpd                  # only httpd-related
sudo ausearch -m AVC --start recent --raw \
    | audit2allow                              # quick "what would
                                                # allow this"
sudo ausearch -m AVC -ts recent --interpret    # human-readable AVCs

# setroubleshoot is the "user-friendly" layer. on a desktop you may
# get desktop notifications about denials with a "View" button that
# opens the suggested-fix UI. install if missing:
sudo dnf install setroubleshoot setroubleshoot-server


# THIRD-PARTY SOFTWARE GOTCHAS

# 1. DOCKER. since cgroups v2 and recent SELinux policy, modern docker
#    plays well — `container_t` type, container_use_devices boolean
#    for /dev access. older docker installations may need
#    container_t labeling on volumes:
#       docker run -v /data:/data:Z ...                # relabel volume
#
# 2. PODMAN. same labeling concerns as docker. use :Z (per-container
#    label) or :z (shared label) volume mount options.
#
# 3. NVIDIA AKMOD-BUILT KMODS. inherit the right label automatically.
#    no special handling needed in 2026. if you see denials, it's
#    usually a relabel issue:
sudo restorecon -RFv /lib/modules
#
# 4. NFS. mount with selinux context or enable booleans:
sudo setsebool -P use_nfs_home_dirs on          # if /home is NFS
sudo setsebool -P virt_use_nfs on               # for VMs
#
# 5. SAMBA. multiple booleans depending on what you're doing:
sudo setsebool -P samba_enable_home_dirs on
sudo setsebool -P samba_export_all_rw on
#
# 6. CUSTOM SYSTEMD SERVICES IN /usr/local. unconfined by default —
#    they get the wide-open `unconfined_service_t` type. fine for
#    quick experiments; for production, write a small policy module
#    (audit2allow workflow) to confine it.


# AUTORELABEL — THE FULL SYSTEM RELABEL

# if your file-system labels are massively wrong (you ran an OS
# upgrade in some unusual way; you restored from a non-SELinux backup),
# trigger a full relabel at boot:
sudo touch /.autorelabel
sudo reboot
# takes 5-20 minutes during boot. reboots a second time when done.


# WHEN TO ESCALATE

# - PERMISSIVE GLOBALLY (`setenforce 0`) — fine for short triage. NEVER
#   leave it permissive in /etc/selinux/config. you lose all SELinux
#   protection.
#
# - PERMISSIVE PER-DOMAIN (`semanage permissive -a`) — better. lets
#   you debug one service while keeping the rest enforcing. remove
#   the permissive label after the fix is in.
#
# - DISABLED in /etc/selinux/config — essentially never the answer.
#   disabling SELinux means the next time you turn it back on, you
#   need an autorelabel boot. and you've spent the intervening time
#   with all the contexts drifting away from what policy expects.
#
# the most common "i need to disable SELinux" feeling is usually
# fixable with one boolean, one fcontext, or one port labeling
# command. give the audit2allow workflow ten minutes before reaching
# for the off switch.


FIREWALLD — ZONE-BASED FIREWALL
-------------------------------

# fedora ships firewalld enabled with the FedoraWorkstation zone.
# day-to-day usage:

# show what's active
sudo firewall-cmd --get-active-zones
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all                        # default zone
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all --zone=public

# open a port — twice (--permanent for survival, no --permanent for live)
sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp
sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp --permanent

# or in one command with auto-reload
sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp --permanent && sudo firewall-cmd --reload

# allow a service by name (curated list in /usr/lib/firewalld/services)
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=http --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

# zone assignment for an interface (default: tied to NetworkManager profile)
sudo firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --change-interface=virbr0 --permanent


NETWORKING — NMCLI, DNS, VPNs, REMOTE ACCESS
--------------------------------------------

# the stack on fedora workstation:
#
#   NetworkManager   — the canonical network daemon. settings → wi-fi
#                      and settings → network drive it. nmcli is its CLI.
#   systemd-resolved — local DNS resolver. owns /etc/resolv.conf as a
#                      symlink. per-link DNS, DNS-over-TLS optional.
#   firewalld        — covered above. zones map to NM connections.
#   Avahi (mDNS)     — preinstalled, handles .local hostnames on LAN.
#
# the older `ifconfig` / `netstat` / `route` tools are NOT installed by
# default — they're considered legacy. use `ip`, `ss`, `nstat` from the
# iproute2 package (also preinstalled).


# NMCLI — THE EVERYDAY CLI

# overview
nmcli                                       # short summary
nmcli device status                         # interfaces + state
nmcli connection show                       # saved profiles
nmcli connection show --active              # currently in use

# wi-fi
nmcli device wifi list                      # scan
nmcli device wifi connect "SSID" password "pass"
nmcli device wifi connect "SSID" --ask      # prompt for password
nmcli connection up "SSID"                  # reconnect a saved profile
nmcli connection down "SSID"
nmcli radio wifi off                        # toggle wifi
nmcli radio wifi on

# ethernet
nmcli device connect enp3s0                 # bring up an interface
nmcli device disconnect enp3s0

# delete a saved profile
nmcli connection delete "old-network"

# show every detail about a connection
nmcli connection show "home-wifi"


# STATIC IP / DNS OVERRIDES (per connection)

# switch a profile to manual IPv4 with static address + DNS:
nmcli connection modify "home-wifi" \
    ipv4.method manual \
    ipv4.addresses 192.168.1.42/24 \
    ipv4.gateway 192.168.1.1 \
    ipv4.dns "1.1.1.1 9.9.9.9" \
    ipv4.dns-search "lan"

# revert to DHCP (the default):
nmcli connection modify "home-wifi" ipv4.method auto ipv4.addresses "" \
    ipv4.gateway "" ipv4.dns "" ipv4.dns-search ""

# changes apply on the next `nmcli connection up` of the profile.


# DNS — systemd-resolved

# /etc/resolv.conf is a SYMLINK to /run/systemd/resolve/stub-resolv.conf.
# editing it directly does nothing useful. all DNS config goes through
# NetworkManager (per-link) or systemd-resolved (global).

# inspect current state:
resolvectl status                           # per-link + global DNS
resolvectl statistics                       # cache hits, queries
resolvectl flush-caches                     # clear the DNS cache

# query (faster than dig + uses your actual resolver):
resolvectl query example.com
resolvectl query --type=MX example.com

# enable DNS-over-TLS globally:
sudo mkdir -p /etc/systemd/resolved.conf.d
sudo tee /etc/systemd/resolved.conf.d/dot.conf <<'EOF'
[Resolve]
DNS=1.1.1.1#cloudflare-dns.com 9.9.9.9#dns.quad9.net
DNSOverTLS=yes
DNSSEC=allow-downgrade
EOF
sudo systemctl restart systemd-resolved


# MDNS — .LOCAL HOSTNAMES ON THE LAN

# Avahi is preinstalled. find printers, NAS boxes, raspberry pis,
# anything advertising via mDNS:
avahi-browse -ar | head -50                 # all services
avahi-browse -ar | grep -i printer
ping fileserver.local                       # resolves via mDNS

# advertise this machine's services for others to find:
sudo dnf install nss-mdns                   # already on workstation
hostnamectl set-hostname mybox              # mybox.local will resolve


# SSH CLIENT — ~/.ssh/config IS THE TOOL

# the file most people don't realize they need. saves immense typing.
cat >>~/.ssh/config <<'EOF'
# global defaults
Host *
    ServerAliveInterval 60
    ServerAliveCountMax 3
    HashKnownHosts no
    ControlMaster auto
    ControlPath ~/.ssh/cm-%r@%h:%p
    ControlPersist 10m

# per-host shortcuts — `ssh prod` instead of full hostname
Host prod
    HostName prod.example.com
    User deploy
    Port 22
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_work

# jump host (ProxyJump) — multi-hop in one command
Host internal-db
    HostName 10.0.5.12
    User postgres
    ProxyJump prod
EOF
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/config

# ControlMaster + ControlPath multiplexing means subsequent connections
# to the same host reuse the existing TCP socket — instant. huge speed
# win for ansible / scp / repeated commands.

# ssh-agent is auto-started by GNOME (gnome-keyring). add keys:
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519                   # caches until logout
ssh-add -l                                  # currently cached
ssh-add -D                                  # forget all


# WIREGUARD — THE MODERN VPN PRIMITIVE

# kernel module is in fedora's kernel; tools are a one-line install.
sudo dnf install wireguard-tools

# NetworkManager has a built-in WireGuard backend. easiest path: get a
# .conf file from your VPN provider (or wireguard server) and import:
nmcli connection import type wireguard file ~/Downloads/wg0.conf
nmcli connection up wg0

# OR the wg-quick CLI path (no NetworkManager involvement):
sudo cp ~/Downloads/wg0.conf /etc/wireguard/
sudo wg-quick up wg0
sudo systemctl enable --now wg-quick@wg0     # autostart at boot

# inspect:
sudo wg show                                 # peers, handshake times
ip addr show wg0                             # local IP


# TAILSCALE — THE "JUST WORKS" VPN

# wireguard under the hood + a coordination server. zero NAT-traversal
# config, magic-DNS hostnames, exit nodes. fedora has it via COPR or
# the official repo:
sudo dnf config-manager addrepo --from-repofile=https://pkgs.tailscale.com/stable/fedora/tailscale.repo
sudo dnf install tailscale
sudo systemctl enable --now tailscaled
sudo tailscale up                            # browser-driven login

# day-to-day:
tailscale status                             # peer list + IPs
tailscale ip                                 # this machine's tailscale IP
ssh username@laptop                          # MagicDNS — no IP needed
tailscale ssh username@laptop                # built-in ssh with tailscale auth

# advanced:
sudo tailscale up --exit-node=other-machine  # route all traffic via peer
sudo tailscale up --advertise-exit-node      # offer this machine as an exit
sudo tailscale up --advertise-routes=192.168.1.0/24   # subnet router


# DIAGNOSTIC COMMANDS — THE MODERN STACK

# iproute2 (preinstalled) replaces ifconfig / netstat / route:
ip addr                                      # all interface addresses
ip -br addr                                  # brief, columnar
ip route                                     # routing table
ip -br link                                  # interface up/down state
ip neighbor                                  # ARP cache

# open ports / listening sockets (replaces netstat):
ss -tlnp                                     # TCP listening, with proc
ss -ulnp                                     # UDP listening
ss -tap                                      # all TCP, with proc
ss -s                                        # socket summary

# bandwidth / packet counters (replaces netstat -i):
nstat                                        # interface stats since boot
ip -s link                                   # per-interface counters

# connectivity / path:
ping -c 4 1.1.1.1
mtr 1.1.1.1                                  # interactive traceroute + ping
mtr -rwzc 10 example.com                     # report mode

# DNS troubleshooting:
resolvectl query example.com                 # uses your resolver
dig example.com                              # bypasses systemd-resolved
sudo dnf install bind-utils                  # if dig is missing

# capture packets (need sudo):
sudo dnf install wireshark-cli               # tshark + capture filters
sudo tshark -i wlan0 -f 'port 53'            # DNS traffic on wifi
sudo dnf install wireshark                   # the GUI


# FIREWALLD + NETWORKMANAGER ZONES

# every NM connection is assigned a firewalld zone. that's why your
# laptop's firewall is loose on home wifi (FedoraWorkstation zone) and
# stricter on public networks — the zone is per-profile.

# see current zone assignments:
sudo firewall-cmd --get-active-zones

# change a connection's zone (persists with the NM profile):
nmcli connection modify "coffee-shop-wifi" connection.zone public
nmcli connection up "coffee-shop-wifi"

# the FedoraWorkstation zone is intentionally permissive (libvirt,
# mdns, ssh, samba-client are all open by default). don't use it on
# untrusted networks.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. NETWORKMANAGER OVERRIDES YOUR /ETC/RESOLV.CONF EDITS. it's a
#    symlink; edits don't survive a reconnect. use per-connection
#    DNS via `nmcli connection modify` (above) or set DNS globally
#    in /etc/systemd/resolved.conf.d/.
#
# 2. VPN ROUTES ALL TRAFFIC WHEN YOU JUST WANTED LAN ACCESS. wg-quick
#    sets AllowedIPs=0.0.0.0/0 by default. for split-tunnel, edit
#    the .conf to list only your VPN subnet:
#       AllowedIPs = 10.0.0.0/8, 192.168.42.0/24
#
# 3. SSH FROZEN MID-SESSION. fix by setting ServerAliveInterval in
#    ~/.ssh/config (above) so the client probes periodically.
#
# 4. CAN'T REACH SAMBA / NFS SHARE. firewalld zone is too strict, OR
#    SELinux booleans aren't set. for samba client:
sudo setsebool -P use_samba_home_dirs on
#    for nfs:
sudo setsebool -P virt_use_nfs on
#
# 5. WIFI SLOW AFTER SUSPEND. NetworkManager + driver power-save
#    interaction. disable wifi power-save permanently:
sudo tee /etc/NetworkManager/conf.d/wifi-powersave.conf <<'EOF'
[connection]
wifi.powersave = 2
EOF
sudo systemctl restart NetworkManager
#    (powersave values: 0=use default, 2=disable, 3=enable)
#
# 6. TAILSCALE + SYSTEMD-RESOLVED ORDERING. on some installs the
#    tailscale interface comes up before systemd-resolved is ready
#    and DNS breaks until restart. fix:
sudo systemctl edit tailscaled
#    add:
#       [Unit]
#       After=systemd-resolved.service
#       Wants=systemd-resolved.service
#
# 7. mDNS / .local DOESN'T RESOLVE FROM A CONTAINER. expected —
#    rootless podman uses a different netns. on the host it works.


FILE SHARING — NFS AND SAMBA ON A LAN
-------------------------------------

# sharing files between machines on your LAN. NETWORKING
# covered routing / DNS / VPN; this is the layer above —
# "the media server, the family laptop, the NAS, the phone."


# WHICH PROTOCOL? — DECIDE FIRST

# pick before configuring; switching costs more later than the
# 30-second decision now.
#
#   all-linux LAN              → NFSv4
#       Why: native POSIX semantics (real uid/gid, real perms,
#       symlinks, locking), best throughput, simplest config.
#
#   mixed mac / windows / linux→ Samba (SMB)
#       Why: the only protocol Windows speaks natively; macOS
#       Finder loves it; android / iOS file apps speak it. you
#       pay in POSIX-perm friction, but it's the universal
#       common denominator.
#
#   ad-hoc, no server install  → sshfs
#       Why: you already have ssh; reuses keys; works through
#       any network ssh works through. slow for big-file
#       transfers, fine for "browse a remote dir from Files."
#
#   internet-facing            → none of the above unsealed
#       Why: NFS / Samba on the open internet is a foot-gun
#       (auth weak, ransomware target, lateral-movement vector).
#       expose via wireguard / tailscale (NETWORKING section)
#       and treat that tunnel as your LAN.


# ============================================================
# SAMBA / SMB — THE MIXED-OS DEFAULT
# ============================================================

# --- SERVER INSTALL ---

sudo dnf install samba samba-common samba-client

# minimal /etc/samba/smb.conf for a home setup:
sudo tee /etc/samba/smb.conf >/dev/null <<'EOF'
[global]
   workgroup = WORKGROUP
   server string = fedora-nas
   security = user
   passdb backend = tdbsam
   map to guest = bad user
   server min protocol = SMB3        # refuse legacy SMB1/2
   server signing = mandatory
   client signing = mandatory
   load printers = no
   printing = bsd
   printcap name = /dev/null
   disable spoolss = yes

[media]
   path = /srv/share/media
   read only = no
   browseable = yes
   valid users = @smbusers
   create mask = 0664
   directory mask = 0775
EOF

# enable + start:
sudo systemctl enable --now smb nmb
# (nmb is the NetBIOS name service — required for the "appears
# in Windows network browser" path. modern macs and windows
# also work via WSD; on fedora that needs the wsdd2 package.)

# --- SAMBA USERS (separate from system users) ---

# samba has its OWN password database. you ADD an existing
# linux user to it, but the password is independent.
sudo useradd -M -s /sbin/nologin smbalice
sudo smbpasswd -a smbalice                # set samba password
sudo smbpasswd -e smbalice                # enable

# group for share access:
sudo groupadd smbusers
sudo usermod -aG smbusers smbalice
sudo chgrp -R smbusers /srv/share/media
sudo chmod -R 2775 /srv/share/media        # SGID for group inheritance

# --- FIREWALL ---
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=samba --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=samba-client --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

# --- SELINUX (THE FEDORA-SPECIFIC PIECE) ---

# 1) tell SELinux this directory is a samba share:
sudo semanage fcontext -a -t samba_share_t '/srv/share/media(/.*)?'
sudo restorecon -Rv /srv/share/media

# 2) booleans you'll usually want:
sudo setsebool -P samba_enable_home_dirs on   # share users' ~ via SMB
sudo setsebool -P smbd_anon_write on          # allow anonymous writes
sudo setsebool -P samba_export_all_rw on      # share anything (broad)

# the booleans are cumulative. for a media share you typically
# only need the fcontext step + restorecon. enable home-dirs
# only if you also share [homes].

# --- VERIFY THE SERVER ---
sudo testparm                                  # parse smb.conf, warn on issues
sudo smbclient -L //localhost -U smbalice      # what shares are visible?

# --- SMB CLIENT ---

# GUI (gnome Files): Other Locations → "Connect to Server" →
#   smb://servername/media
# saves credentials in gnome-keyring; auto-mounts on demand.

# CLI: list shares, browse interactively:
smbclient -L //server.local -U smbalice
smbclient //server.local/media -U smbalice
# inside: ls, get, put, cd, mget, mput, smbclient is an
# ftp-style shell.

# permanent mount via /etc/fstab + a credentials file:
sudo tee /root/smb-media.cred >/dev/null <<'EOF'
username=smbalice
password=<the-samba-password>
domain=WORKGROUP
EOF
sudo chmod 600 /root/smb-media.cred

sudo mkdir -p /mnt/media
echo '//server.local/media  /mnt/media  cifs  credentials=/root/smb-media.cred,_netdev,uid=1000,gid=1000,vers=3.0,iocharset=utf8,nofail  0 0' \
    | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo mount -a

# uid=1000,gid=1000 makes the mount "owned by you" — important
# because SMB's perm model doesn't map one-to-one onto POSIX.


# ============================================================
# NFSv4 — THE ALL-LINUX HIGH-PERFORMANCE OPTION
# ============================================================

# --- SERVER INSTALL ---

sudo dnf install nfs-utils

# enable + start (a single unit on modern fedora):
sudo systemctl enable --now nfs-server

# --- DEFINE EXPORTS in /etc/exports ---

# format: directory  client-list(options)
sudo tee /etc/exports >/dev/null <<'EOF'
/srv/share/backups   192.168.1.0/24(rw,sync,no_subtree_check,no_root_squash)
/srv/share/media     192.168.1.0/24(ro,sync,no_subtree_check,all_squash,anonuid=1000,anongid=1000)
EOF

# the option vocabulary:
#   rw / ro                    obvious
#   sync                       writes hit disk before ACK (default; safe)
#   async                      faster, BUT can lose data on power loss
#   no_subtree_check           skip path-validation (recommended; default)
#   root_squash (default)      remote root → nfsnobody (safer)
#   no_root_squash             remote root → local root (use sparingly)
#   all_squash                 every user → nfsnobody (for shared read areas)
#   anonuid=NNN, anongid=NNN   the uid/gid all_squash maps to

# reload exports without restarting nfs-server:
sudo exportfs -rav
sudo exportfs -v                              # show current exports

# --- FIREWALL ---
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=nfs --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=mountd --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=rpc-bind --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload
# NFSv4 mostly uses port 2049 only; mountd+rpcbind are needed
# for v3 fallback. if you require v4 exclusively, just nfs.

# --- SELINUX ---
sudo setsebool -P nfs_export_all_rw on        # broad: any dir, RW
sudo setsebool -P nfs_export_all_ro on        # broad: any dir, RO
sudo setsebool -P use_nfs_home_dirs on        # only on CLIENTS that
                                              # mount user homes via NFS

# --- NFS CLIENT ---

# list a server's exports (NFSv3 dialog; v4 hides them in
# pseudoroot — see below):
showmount -e server.local

# one-shot mount:
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/backups
sudo mount -t nfs4 server.local:/srv/share/backups /mnt/backups

# permanent + lazy: only mount on first access via systemd
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/media
echo 'server.local:/srv/share/media  /mnt/media  nfs4  defaults,_netdev,noauto,x-systemd.automount,x-systemd.idle-timeout=10min  0 0' \
    | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
# now `cd /mnt/media` lazily mounts; 10 min of idle unmounts.

# the NFSv4 pseudoroot — clients see exports under a single
# server-side namespace, not individual exported paths:
sudo mount -t nfs4 server.local:/ /mnt/all
ls /mnt/all                                   # shows pseudoroot tree
# this is why `showmount -e` is a v3-era idiom; v4 considers
# server-side enumeration over RPC a security smell.


# ============================================================
# NFSv4 VS v3 — DECIDE ONCE
# ============================================================

# use v4 unless you can't:
#   v4 advantages    — single port (2049), stateful (recovers
#                      cleanly), better locking, AUTH_GSS /
#                      kerberos support, ACL semantics
#   v4 cost          — slightly more setup; pseudoroot trips
#                      people up the first time
#
# stick with v3 only if:
#   - an old NAS / appliance doesn't support v4
#   - you need to use NIS or local-uid mapping that v4 won't
#   - a vendor's docs say "this only works on v3"

# force a specific version on the client:
sudo mount -t nfs -o vers=4.2 server.local:/srv/x /mnt/x
sudo mount -t nfs -o vers=3   legacy:/srv/y       /mnt/y


# ============================================================
# ON-DEMAND MOUNTS — AUTOFS VS SYSTEMD AUTOMOUNT
# ============================================================

# both let "cd /mnt/foo" trigger a mount and an idle unmount.

# SYSTEMD AUTOMOUNT (preferred on fedora):
#   - configured via fstab `x-systemd.automount` (see above)
#   - integrated with the journal and `systemctl list-units`
#   - one tool to learn (`systemctl`), one place to debug
systemctl list-units --type=automount
journalctl -u mnt-media.automount

# AUTOFS (older, still around):
sudo dnf install autofs
sudo systemctl enable --now autofs
#   /etc/auto.master            — define mount points
#   /etc/auto.misc              — define maps (NFS / SMB / etc.)
# value: lets you write WILDCARD maps where the directory name
# becomes the mount source. handy for "home directory per user"
# patterns; rarely needed on a workstation.

# rule of thumb: systemd automount on workstation, autofs on
# multi-user servers with wildcard home-dir patterns.


# ============================================================
# SSHFS — THE "NO SERVER NEEDED" OPTION
# ============================================================

# you have ssh access; sshfs gives you the remote tree mounted
# locally. great for "I want to edit one file in a VS Code that
# lives on another machine."

sudo dnf install fuse-sshfs

# one-shot:
sshfs alice@server.local:/var/www /mnt/www
fusermount -u /mnt/www                        # unmount

# permanent fstab entry (uses your ssh-agent for keys):
echo 'alice@server.local:/var/www  /mnt/www  fuse.sshfs  defaults,_netdev,noauto,x-systemd.automount,allow_other,IdentityFile=/home/alice/.ssh/id_ed25519  0 0' \
    | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab

# tradeoff: per-syscall round-trip to a remote sshd. great for
# small files / browsing; SLOW for `cp big-file` or `find`. for
# bulk-transfer or many small reads, use NFS / SMB.


# ============================================================
# mDNS / SERVICE DISCOVERY (.local names)
# ============================================================

# fedora ships avahi; mDNS resolution works out of the box for
# `.local` names. open the firewall service so clients can
# discover this host:
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=mdns --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload
systemctl status avahi-daemon

# from a client:
avahi-browse -a                                # see every service on LAN
avahi-resolve -n server.local
getent hosts server.local                       # via nss-mdns

# avahi-discover is the GUI browser; useful when "the laptop
# can't see the server" and you want to know if it's a samba/nfs
# problem or a mDNS-discovery problem.


# ============================================================
# PERFORMANCE
# ============================================================

# NFS rsize / wsize — read and write block size. defaults are
# negotiated; you usually don't need to set them. when you do
# (e.g. gigabit LAN + jumbo frames):
sudo mount -t nfs4 -o rsize=1048576,wsize=1048576,async \
    server.local:/srv/x /mnt/x
# rsize/wsize cap at 1 MiB. larger is not better; the kernel
# rejects.

# async means "ACK before disk" on the SERVER. faster, but a
# server crash during writes = data loss. only enable on a
# protected (UPS) server you trust.

# samba performance — usually a windows-client problem more
# than a linux-server problem. relevant knobs:
#   socket options = TCP_NODELAY IPTOS_LOWDELAY
#   server multi channel support = yes        (SMB3+ multichan)
#   read raw / write raw / strict sync = ...  (rarely needed today)

# bottleneck identification (these are the corners — see
# PERFORMANCE INVESTIGATION):
#   network saturated  → sar -n DEV 1
#   server disk slow   → iostat -xz 1 on the SERVER
#   server CPU pinned  → top on the SERVER (rarely; usually wire)
#   client kernel busy → check NFS in-flight: cat /proc/self/mountstats


# ============================================================
# WORKFLOWS YOU'LL ACTUALLY HAVE
# ============================================================

# "I want my laptop and desktop to share ~/Photos"
#   → NFSv4 with all_squash + anonuid mapped to your UID on
#     both ends. or move ~/Photos to syncthing (different
#     section / topic).

# "the family iPad needs to upload to a NAS folder"
#   → Samba. ios files app speaks SMB3 natively.

# "I'm spinning up a build farm and the workers need
#  /srv/sources from the controller"
#   → NFSv4, async, jumbo frames on a dedicated subnet.

# "I just need to grep a directory on another machine for
#  five minutes"
#   → sshfs. don't install a server for a one-off.

# "I want my windows box to back up to my fedora server"
#   → Samba + windows file history pointed at the share. or
#     better, switch the backup tool to restic / borg and
#     point it at a Samba share or `restic --repo s3:...` —
#     see BACKUPS.


# ============================================================
# HONEST TRADEOFFS
# ============================================================

# do not use SMB1. it has had unauth RCEs (wannacry, eternal
# blue). `server min protocol = SMB3` in smb.conf is the
# default in this section for that reason; verify in smb.conf
# any time you inherit a config from a guide.

# NFS root_squash is the default for a reason. `no_root_squash`
# means a compromised root on a client = root on your server's
# filesystem. only set it for one specific install case
# (provisioning workstations from a server image) and remove
# it after.

# samba shared with `valid users = @smbusers` is fine. NEVER
# combine `guest ok = yes` with writeable shares on a network
# you don't fully control. one device on the LAN gets owned
# and your media library is now ransomware fodder.

# SELinux contexts are the most common silent failure mode for
# fedora samba/NFS shares. when "the share is exported but
# clients see 'permission denied'", check `ausearch -m avc`
# (see SELINUX section) before changing kernel options.


# ============================================================
# QUICK REFERENCE
# ============================================================

#   mixed-OS share              → samba; smb.conf [share] + smbpasswd
#   all-linux share             → NFSv4 + /etc/exports
#   ad-hoc, no install          → sshfs
#   make samba dir visible      → semanage fcontext + restorecon
#   firewalld: samba            → firewall-cmd --add-service=samba
#   firewalld: nfs              → firewall-cmd --add-service=nfs
#   list a server's exports     → showmount -e host       (v3 only)
#   browse a samba server       → smbclient -L //host -U user
#   mount samba persistently    → fstab: cifs + credentials= file
#   mount nfs persistently      → fstab: nfs4 + x-systemd.automount
#   discover services on LAN    → avahi-browse -a
#   check shared dir contexts   → ls -lZ /srv/share
#   debug a failing samba mount → tail /var/log/samba/log.smbd
#   debug a failing nfs mount   → journalctl -u nfs-server; cat /proc/self/mountstats


