TIME / NTP — CHRONY
-------------------

# fedora's default time-sync daemon is chrony (NOT ntpd, NOT
# systemd-timesyncd). chrony handles both as a CLIENT (sync your
# clock to upstream) and as a SERVER (serve time to your LAN).
# faster convergence than ntpd, better behavior on machines that
# suspend / hibernate / have intermittent network — all the reasons
# laptops in particular benefit.


# THE STACK

#   chronyd            — the daemon. enabled + running by default
#                        on workstation.
#   chronyc            — the control / inspection CLI.
#   /etc/chrony.conf   — server config.
#   timedatectl        — systemd's high-level time UI; wraps the
#                        kernel + RTC settings, not chrony itself.
#   ntpsec / sntp      — alternative implementations; fedora doesn't
#                        ship them in workstation default.


# THE BASICS — timedatectl

# the modern "what's my time situation" command:
timedatectl                                        # local time, UTC,
                                                   # RTC, timezone,
                                                   # NTP enabled / synced

# set timezone
timedatectl list-timezones | grep America
sudo timedatectl set-timezone America/Los_Angeles

# enable / disable NTP sync (just toggles chrony)
sudo timedatectl set-ntp true
sudo timedatectl set-ntp false


# CHRONYC — DAILY INSPECTION

chronyc tracking                                   # how good is the
                                                   # current sync
chronyc sources                                    # which servers
chronyc sources -v                                 # verbose (with state
                                                   # legend)
chronyc sourcestats                                # quality stats per
                                                   # source
chronyc activity                                   # 8/8 sources online
chronyc clients                                    # who's syncing FROM
                                                   # this machine (if
                                                   # serving)
chronyc serverstats                                # if serving

# force an immediate poll + step
sudo chronyc makestep                              # step the clock now
sudo chronyc burst 5/10                            # poll 5 times in 10s
                                                   # for faster lock


# CONFIGURING NTP SERVERS

# the default config uses fedora's pool:
grep -E '^(pool|server)' /etc/chrony.conf
# typically:
#   pool 2.fedora.pool.ntp.org iburst

# to use your own (corporate, internal, cloud-provider) servers:
sudo vi /etc/chrony.conf
# replace the `pool` line with:
#   server time.example.com iburst
#   server time2.example.com iburst
# or use the popular global pools:
#   pool pool.ntp.org iburst
#   pool time.cloudflare.com iburst         # NTS-capable (encrypted)
#   pool time.nist.gov iburst

sudo systemctl restart chronyd
chronyc sources -v                                 # verify new sources


# CHRONY AS A SERVER (sharing time with your LAN)

# add to /etc/chrony.conf:
#   allow 192.168.1.0/24
# open port 123 in firewalld:
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=ntp --permanent && \
    sudo firewall-cmd --reload
sudo systemctl restart chronyd
chronyc clients                                    # see who's connecting

# useful on a home server / NAS / router replacement — keeps every
# device on your LAN syncing to one machine, which syncs to the
# internet (lower jitter, fewer external queries).


# NTS — NETWORK TIME SECURITY (encrypted NTP)

# NTS authenticates time sources cryptographically, protecting against
# someone tampering with NTP traffic. cloudflare runs an NTS server.
# add to /etc/chrony.conf:
#   server time.cloudflare.com iburst nts
# verify:
chronyc -N authdata


# HARDWARE CLOCK vs SYSTEM CLOCK

# the hardware clock (RTC) keeps time while the machine is off. on
# linux it's traditionally set to UTC; on windows it's traditionally
# set to LOCAL time. they disagree by your timezone offset.

# inspect:
timedatectl                                        # "RTC in local TZ" line
hwclock --show                                     # current RTC value
hwclock --systohc                                  # sync RTC FROM system
hwclock --hctosys                                  # sync system FROM RTC


# DUAL-BOOT WITH WINDOWS — THE RTC GOTCHA

# the recurring frustration: boot windows, set the clock right, boot
# linux, clock is 5/8/9 hours off. or vice versa. cause: linux assumes
# UTC; windows assumes local. one of them has to give.
#
# THE FIX (recommended — tell linux to use local time for the RTC):
sudo timedatectl set-local-rtc 1 --adjust-system-clock
#    now linux treats the RTC as local time. windows is happy. no
#    more drift.
#
# ALTERNATIVE (less common — tell windows to use UTC):
#   on windows side, registry tweak:
#     HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\TimeZoneInformation
#     add DWORD: RealTimeIsUniversal = 1
#   this is cleaner technically but you have to remember it on every
#   windows install.


# PTP — PRECISION TIME PROTOCOL (sub-microsecond LAN sync)

# for HFT, scientific instruments, broadcast video, professional
# audio — when NTP's millisecond precision isn't enough. PTP achieves
# sub-microsecond synchronization across a LAN, assuming PTP-capable
# switches.

sudo dnf install linuxptp                          # ships ptp4l + phc2sys
sudo systemctl enable --now ptp4l@<interface>      # configure to taste

# requires hardware support in the NIC and in the LAN switches.
# absolutely niche; almost no fedora workstation user needs PTP.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. CLOCK DRIFT AFTER SUSPEND. modern chrony handles this — it
#    notices on resume and re-syncs. if you see drift:
sudo chronyc makestep
#    or check `chronyc tracking` immediately after resume.
#
# 2. "NTP IS DOWN" AFTER UPGRADING. fedora 41+ may move some defaults
#    around with the dnf5 / chrony version bumps. verify:
systemctl status chronyd
sudo systemctl restart chronyd
#
# 3. CORPORATE FIREWALL BLOCKS NTP (UDP 123). chrony has no built-in
#    HTTP fallback. some workarounds use NTS over TCP (port 4460);
#    most corporate environments give you a permitted internal NTP
#    server.
#
# 4. CLOUD INSTANCES PREFER VENDOR NTP. AWS / GCP / Azure each run
#    their own NTP fleets on link-local addresses. on AWS:
#       server 169.254.169.123 prefer iburst
#    on GCP:
#       server metadata.google.internal prefer iburst
#
# 5. RTC ALREADY DRIFTED BADLY (hours off). chrony's default policy
#    refuses to step the clock by more than 1 second after startup.
#    force a step:
sudo chronyc makestep
#    if even that fails, set the clock manually and let chrony
#    re-sync:
sudo timedatectl set-time '2026-06-17 14:00:00'
#
# 6. "STRATUM 16" IN tracking. means chrony is NOT synchronized.
#    usually a network issue, a firewall, or no sources are responding.
#    `chronyc sources -v` will show the connection state.


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   "what's my time situation"          → timedatectl
#   "am i synced and how well"          → chronyc tracking
#   "what servers am i using"           → chronyc sources -v
#   "force resync now"                  → sudo chronyc makestep
#   "change ntp servers"                → /etc/chrony.conf + restart
#   "set local-time RTC for windows"    → timedatectl set-local-rtc 1
#                                          --adjust-system-clock
#   "share time with my LAN"            → `allow <subnet>` in
#                                          chrony.conf, firewall, restart


NVIDIA DRIVERS — RPM FUSION PATH
--------------------------------

# fedora ships nouveau (the open-source nvidia driver) out of the box.
# nouveau works for basic display but is significantly slower than the
# proprietary driver and lacks CUDA, NVENC, and full vulkan support.
# the supported path to the proprietary driver is RPM Fusion's
# akmod-nvidia (auto-rebuilds against new kernels via akmods.service,
# conceptually like DKMS but RPM-native).

# this is the kind of setup you do once per machine and want to get
# right the first time. the order below matters — installing akmod
# before the kernel headers update, or rebooting before the akmod
# build finishes, are the two ways people end up at a black screen.


# STEP 1 — IDENTIFY YOUR CARD

# the right driver variant depends on your GPU generation:
lspci | grep -iE 'vga|3d|2d'

#   - akmod-nvidia                — CURRENT branch (570.x). supports
#                                   Turing (GTX 16xx, RTX 20xx) and newer.
#                                   ALSO works for Maxwell + Pascal on
#                                   the open-kernel build but check
#                                   rpmfusion's nvidia page if unsure.
#   - akmod-nvidia-470xx          — LTS 470.x branch. Kepler (GTX 6xx /
#                                   7xx) and older Maxwell. for cards
#                                   the current driver dropped.
#   - akmod-nvidia-390xx          — legacy 390.x branch. Fermi era
#                                   (GeForce 4xx / 5xx). end-of-life
#                                   upstream; only install if you have
#                                   nothing else.
#
# unsure which to pick: check nvidia's "Supported Products" page or
# rpmfusion's "Howto/NVIDIA". if `nvidia-detect` is installed, it
# picks for you:
sudo dnf install nvidia-detect && nvidia-detect


# STEP 2 — PREREQUISITES (EVERYTHING IN SYNC)

# RPM Fusion must be enabled (see REPOS section above). then:

# fully update first — you want the kernel and kernel-headers in sync
# BEFORE akmod tries to build against them.
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo dnf install kernel-devel-$(uname -r) kernel-headers-$(uname -r)


# STEP 3 — INSTALL THE DRIVER

# CURRENT BRANCH (most people):
sudo dnf install akmod-nvidia xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-cuda
#    xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-cuda pulls in the CUDA RUNTIME libs (libcuda),
#    needed for hardware video decode (NVENC/NVDEC), pytorch GPU,
#    blender CUDA render, etc. install it unless you specifically don't
#    want CUDA on the box.

# steam / proton / wine — pull 32-bit libs:
sudo dnf install xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-libs.i686

# legacy 470xx branch (substitute the package names):
sudo dnf install akmod-nvidia-470xx xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-470xx-cuda


# STEP 4 — WAIT FOR THE AKMOD BUILD

# akmods.service builds the kmod in the background. 5-15 minutes on
# typical hardware. DO NOT REBOOT until it finishes — booting with the
# kmod half-built drops you on nouveau (or worse, a black screen on a
# system where nouveau is already blacklisted).

# watch the build:
sudo journalctl -fu akmods.service

# verify the module file exists for your running kernel:
ls /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/extra/nvidia/
modinfo -F version nvidia        # prints driver version once built

# if `modinfo` says nothing, the build hasn't finished or it failed.
# kick it manually:
sudo akmods --force


# STEP 5 — SECURE BOOT (skip if disabled in firmware)

# check your state:
mokutil --sb-state                 # SecureBoot enabled / disabled

# if enabled: akmod's built kmod is unsigned and shim will refuse to
# load it. RPM Fusion's akmod hooks generate a Machine Owner Key (MOK)
# pair at /var/lib/dkms/mok.{pub,priv} and sign the kmod with it. you
# enroll the pub side once:
sudo mokutil --import /var/lib/dkms/mok.pub
#    sets a one-time password. on next reboot, shim's MokManager menu
#    appears BEFORE GRUB — pick "Enroll MOK", confirm with that
#    password. enrollment is permanent until you remove it.

# verify enrollment after reboot:
mokutil --list-enrolled | grep -A2 "DKMS\|nvidia"

# easier path (if you don't care about secure boot): disable it in
# firmware. matters less on a desktop than a laptop you carry out.


# STEP 6 — WAYLAND / KMS MODESET

# nvidia-drm.modeset=1 enables proper KMS support, required for clean
# Wayland sessions, smooth tty switches, and gnome / kde wayland on
# nvidia. driver 545+ enables this by default, and rpmfusion configures
# it via /usr/lib/modprobe.d/nvidia-modeset.conf. verify:
cat /sys/module/nvidia_drm/parameters/modeset       # should be: Y

# if it's N, force it. either add the modprobe option:
sudo tee /etc/modprobe.d/nvidia-modeset.conf <<'EOF'
options nvidia-drm modeset=1
EOF
sudo dracut --force
#    or add it as a kernel cmdline arg:
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args='nvidia-drm.modeset=1'


# STEP 7 — REBOOT AND VERIFY

sudo reboot

# after login, confirm:
lsmod | grep -E 'nvidia|nouveau'    # nvidia loaded, nouveau ABSENT
nvidia-smi                           # GPU model + driver version + processes
glxinfo | grep -i 'opengl renderer'  # should say NVIDIA, not llvmpipe

# session type (wayland or x11):
echo $XDG_SESSION_TYPE


# HYBRID LAPTOP / OPTIMUS — RENDER OFFLOAD

# for laptops with both Intel/AMD iGPU + nvidia dGPU, the modern model
# is "on-demand": iGPU drives the display, nvidia handles render
# offload per-app. saves battery vs running everything on nvidia.

# verify both GPUs are present:
lspci -k | grep -EA3 'VGA|3D'

# launch a single app on nvidia from a terminal:
__NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia glxinfo \
    | grep 'OpenGL renderer'                # should now say NVIDIA

# convenient wrapper:
sudo tee /usr/local/bin/nv <<'EOF'
#!/bin/sh
exec env __NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia \
         __VK_LAYER_NV_optimus=NVIDIA_only "$@"
EOF
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/nv
#    then: `nv blender`, `nv steam`, etc.

# steam per-game launch options for nvidia render offload:
#     __NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia %command%


# CUDA DEVELOPMENT (vs CUDA RUNTIME)

# xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-cuda installs runtime (libcuda) only — enough to
# RUN cuda apps (pytorch, blender, ffmpeg-nvenc). for compiling cuda
# code you need the toolkit. two paths:
#
# a) nvidia's official cuda repo (most cuda versions, large download)
sudo dnf config-manager addrepo --from-repofile=https://developer.download.nvidia.com/compute/cuda/repos/fedora41/x86_64/cuda-fedora41.repo
sudo dnf install cuda-toolkit
#    fedora 44 isn't always in nvidia's repo on day one — substitute
#    fedora41 or fedora42 as a placeholder; the binaries are usually
#    forward-compatible. check developer.nvidia.com for current list.
#
# b) python-only path: install pytorch / tensorflow wheels that bundle
#    their own cuda libs. no system toolkit needed.


# COMMON FAILURES AND FIXES

# 1. "nvidia kernel module missing" / black screen after reboot.
#    you rebooted before akmod finished. boot to multi-user mode
#    (add `3` to kernel cmdline at the GRUB menu — that's why we
#    showed the GRUB menu earlier), log in, then:
sudo akmods --force
sudo systemctl isolate graphical.target
#
# 2. nouveau still loaded alongside nvidia. check the blacklist:
cat /usr/lib/modprobe.d/nvidia.conf
#    rpmfusion should drop a blacklist entry. if not:
sudo tee /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist-nouveau.conf <<'EOF'
blacklist nouveau
options nouveau modeset=0
EOF
sudo dracut --force
#
# 3. kernel update broke nvidia. akmod usually rebuilds on `dnf
#    upgrade`, but if it didn't fire:
sudo akmods --force --kernels $(uname -r)
sudo dracut --force
#
# 4. wayland tearing / glitching. driver 545+ should be fine. if
#    not, log out and pick "GNOME on Xorg" at the gdm session
#    picker — GNOME 47+ still ships the xorg session as an optional
#    package:
sudo dnf install gnome-session-xsession
#    KDE Plasma's wayland on nvidia is generally smoother than
#    GNOME's as of 2026.
#
# 5. screen tearing in X11. enable the nvidia force-composition
#    pipeline in xorg conf, or use a compositor (picom).
#
# 6. external monitor not detected after suspend. driver power
#    management quirk. on most setups this is fixed by:
sudo systemctl enable --now nvidia-suspend.service \
    nvidia-resume.service nvidia-hibernate.service


# REMOVAL / ROLLBACK TO NOUVEAU

sudo dnf remove '*nvidia*' --noautoremove
sudo dnf install xorg-x11-drv-nouveau          # if dnf removed it
sudo rm /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist-nouveau.conf 2>/dev/null
sudo rm /etc/modprobe.d/nvidia-modeset.conf 2>/dev/null
sudo dracut --force
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --remove-args='nvidia-drm.modeset=1'
sudo reboot


HARDWARE-ACCELERATED VIDEO (VAAPI / VDPAU / NVENC)
--------------------------------------------------

# the highest-leverage GPU tuning most people skip. CPU-decoded
# 1080p youtube on a laptop is a real ~30% battery hit and a
# loud fan; with vaapi wired up the same playback is silent
# and inert. on F44 this takes 15 minutes to set up and then
# works forever.


# WHY THIS IS A FEDORA QUESTION

# fedora can't ship H.264, H.265 (HEVC), or AAC decoders by
# default. those codecs are patent-encumbered, and red hat
# legal won't risk it. mesa's vaapi packages on fedora are
# COMPILED WITH THOSE CODECS DISABLED.

# every distro fedora users complain about ("video works out
# of the box on ubuntu!") simply ships what fedora can't.
# the fix is RPM Fusion's `mesa-va-drivers-freeworld` and
# `mesa-vdpau-drivers-freeworld` — recompiled with the codecs
# turned on. one-time swap; you forget about it.

# see REPOS for RPM Fusion enablement.


# THE APIS — A SHORT TAXONOMY

# four ways apps ask the GPU for help:
#
#   VAAPI   (libva)   — the modern lingua franca on linux.
#                       intel and amd implement it natively;
#                       nvidia speaks it through a shim
#                       (nvidia-vaapi-driver) over NVDEC.
#                       what mpv, ffmpeg, firefox, chromium,
#                       gstreamer all default to.
#
#   VDPAU             — older nvidia/amd API. mostly legacy.
#                       a few players still prefer it on
#                       nvidia (some mpv configs); on amd
#                       nothing new should be using it.
#
#   NVENC / NVDEC     — nvidia's native encode/decode. ffmpeg
#                       and OBS speak these directly via the
#                       proprietary driver. the highest-quality
#                       path on nvidia hardware.
#
#   QSV               — Intel Quick Sync via oneVPL. similar
#                       quality story to NVENC but intel-only.
#                       ffmpeg has -hwaccel qsv.
#
