SECURE BOOT — NOTES
-------------------

# fedora's shim is signed by Microsoft, so secure boot works out of the
# box for the default kernel and the shipped grub. third-party kmods
# (nvidia, virtualbox, dkms-built modules) need signing. options:
#   - disable secure boot in firmware (simplest, least secure)
#   - enroll a MOK and sign kmods (correct path; see above)
#   - use sbctl to manage your own keys (advanced)

# verify state:
mokutil --sb-state                                  # SecureBoot enabled / disabled
mokutil --list-enrolled


TPM2-BACKED LUKS UNLOCK
-----------------------

# fedora's LUKS root encryption is excellent, but typing a passphrase
# at every boot is friction. on hardware with a TPM2 chip + secure
# boot, you can have the kernel unlock LUKS automatically — provided
# the boot chain is intact. tamper with the firmware, bootloader, or
# kernel and the auto-unlock fails (passphrase falls back).
#
# this is the modern "TPM-backed disk encryption" model that windows
# bitlocker, macos filevault, and silverblue have been using for years.
# on fedora it's a `systemd-cryptenroll` command.


# WHAT THIS PROTECTS AGAINST — THREAT MODEL

# PROTECTS:
#   - EVIL MAID attacks (someone replaces your bootloader to capture
#     the LUKS passphrase). the TPM won't release the key to a
#     tampered boot chain.
#   - laptop theft with the disk pulled — the disk is still encrypted
#     with LUKS; without the TPM chip the data is unreadable.
#
# DOES NOT PROTECT:
#   - laptop theft with the WHOLE machine — the TPM is on the
#     motherboard. boot the laptop, you get to the gdm login screen,
#     attacker still needs your user password to actually log in.
#     this is why screen lock + strong user password still matter.
#   - rogue OS attacks while you're logged in. TPM unlock happens at
#     boot; everything past that point is unchanged.
#   - cold-boot attacks on RAM (extremely niche).
#
# this is the same threat model as bitlocker's "PIN-less" mode.
# accept it knowingly; don't treat TPM unlock as a free upgrade.


# PREREQUISITES

# 1. TPM2 chip (almost every modern laptop and motherboard has one)
#    check:
ls /dev/tpm0 /dev/tpmrm0                       # devices present
sudo dnf install tpm2-tools
sudo tpm2_getcap properties-fixed | head -20   # responds: TPM2 alive

# 2. UEFI (not BIOS)
mokutil --sb-state                             # SecureBoot enabled or not

# 3. Secure Boot ideally enabled — this is what binds PCR 7 to a
#    known-good boot chain. you CAN bind without it but the security
#    model is weaker.

# 4. LUKS-encrypted root partition (Workstation install with the
#    "Encrypt my data" anaconda checkbox; you should have entered a
#    passphrase at install time). verify:
sudo cryptsetup luksDump /dev/nvme0n1p3        # adjust device
# look for key slots; "PBKDF2" or "argon2" indicates passphrase slot 0.


# THE ENROLLMENT — ONE COMMAND

# enroll the TPM as an additional LUKS key, bound to specific PCRs:
sudo systemd-cryptenroll \
    --tpm2-device=auto \
    --tpm2-pcrs=0+2+7+12 \
    /dev/nvme0n1p3

# the command prompts for an existing passphrase (to authorize the
# new enrollment), then writes a new key slot bound to the TPM with
# the specified PCRs.


# PCR SELECTION — WHAT EACH BINDS TO

# PCRs (Platform Configuration Registers) are TPM measurements of
# specific boot-chain components. binding to a PCR means "if THIS
# component changes, the TPM refuses to release the key."
#
#   PCR 0   — firmware code (UEFI / coreboot). changes on BIOS update.
#   PCR 2   — extended firmware code (option ROMs, etc.). changes on
#             hardware swaps or PCIe / GPU firmware updates.
#   PCR 4   — bootloader (grub / shim / systemd-boot). changes on
#             package upgrades that touch shim or grub.
#   PCR 7   — secure boot policy + keys. changes if you toggle secure
#             boot or re-enroll MOK keys. THE KEY ONE for evil-maid
#             defense.
#   PCR 11  — initramfs + kernel cmdline (systemd-stub specifically).
#             changes on every dracut rebuild — usually too brittle.
#   PCR 12  — kernel command line. changes if `grubby --update-kernel
#             --args` was run.
#   PCR 14  — MOK (Machine Owner Key) — third-party signed module
#             tracking.
#
# RECOMMENDED for fedora workstation: --tpm2-pcrs=0+2+7+12
#   - tight enough to defeat evil-maid (PCR 7)
#   - tolerates kernel updates (PCR 11 not included)
#   - re-prompts on firmware update (PCR 0/2)
#   - re-prompts on kernel-cmdline change (PCR 12)
#
# MOST PARANOID: add 4 (catches bootloader tampering at the cost of
# re-enrolling on every shim/grub update). usually overkill.


# VERIFY ENROLLMENT

# inspect the LUKS slots — should now show two: passphrase + tpm2:
sudo cryptsetup luksDump /dev/nvme0n1p3 | grep -A2 'tpm2-'
# or:
sudo systemd-cryptenroll /dev/nvme0n1p3        # lists slots

# tell systemd to use the TPM at boot. edit /etc/crypttab and add
# `tpm2-device=auto` to the options column for your encrypted device:
sudo vi /etc/crypttab
# example line:
#   luks-XXXX UUID=YYYY none tpm2-device=auto,tpm2-pcrs=0+2+7+12,discard

# regenerate the initramfs so systemd-cryptsetup is rebuilt with the
# tpm2 support:
sudo dracut --force

# reboot. you should be NOT prompted for a passphrase. if you ARE
# prompted, see "WHAT TRIGGERS RE-PROMPTS" below.


# RECOVERY — THE PASSPHRASE STILL WORKS

# CRITICAL: the original LUKS passphrase remains a valid key slot.
# anything that breaks TPM unlock (firmware update, PCR change, TPM
# chip failure, motherboard replacement) just falls back to the
# passphrase prompt. you're never locked out by enrolling the TPM.
#
# don't lose the passphrase. write it somewhere physical. the TPM
# is an additive convenience, not a replacement for the passphrase.


# WHAT TRIGGERS RE-PROMPTS

# under PCR 0+2+7+12 binding, you'll fall back to passphrase prompt
# on:
#   - firmware (BIOS / UEFI) updates                    — PCR 0
#   - GPU / PCIe firmware updates                       — PCR 2
#   - secure boot enable / disable / key re-enroll      — PCR 7
#   - kernel command-line changes via grubby            — PCR 12
#
# after the change, type the passphrase to boot, then re-enroll the
# TPM with the new measurements:
sudo systemd-cryptenroll --wipe-slot=tpm2 /dev/nvme0n1p3
sudo systemd-cryptenroll --tpm2-device=auto \
    --tpm2-pcrs=0+2+7+12 /dev/nvme0n1p3

# alternative: systemd-pcrlock automates re-binding on expected
# changes (firmware updates that come through fwupd). still maturing
# in 2026; worth checking if it fits your workflow.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. "TPM IS BUSY" / ENROLL FAILS. another tool (sometimes clevis or
#    a stale dracut module) is holding the TPM. reboot fresh and
#    retry. avoid running tpm2_* commands as a user while enrolling.
#
# 2. PROMPTED FOR PASSPHRASE EVEN THOUGH NOTHING CHANGED. usually
#    PCR 11 binding (initramfs) — dracut rebuilds it. don't include
#    PCR 11 in your binding set unless you're certain about your
#    initramfs workflow.
#
# 3. ENCRYPTED /BOOT WITH TPM UNLOCK. fedora's default is unencrypted
#    /boot — TPM unlock kicks in at initramfs after grub loads the
#    kernel. if you have encrypted /boot too, GRUB has to decrypt
#    /boot via a separate passphrase, and TPM unlock only helps with
#    the root partition. usually not worth the complexity.
#
# 4. MOTHERBOARD REPLACEMENT INVALIDATES THE TPM. the new TPM is a
#    different chip; your enrolled key won't unlock. you'll fall
#    back to passphrase. enroll the new TPM after the swap.
#
# 5. TPM2 + SECURE BOOT DISABLED. PCR 7 is meaningless without secure
#    boot — you're still protected against passphrase capture (since
#    the TPM enforces the boot chain measurement) but the evil-maid
#    threat model is much weaker. enable secure boot if at all
#    possible.
#
# 6. FACTORY RESET YOUR TPM. if you ever do this from firmware, all
#    enrolled keys are gone. re-enroll after.


# DISABLING / REMOVING TPM UNLOCK

# wipe the TPM slot from the LUKS header:
sudo systemd-cryptenroll --wipe-slot=tpm2 /dev/nvme0n1p3

# remove tpm2-device=auto from /etc/crypttab, then:
sudo dracut --force

# next boot will use passphrase only.


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   first-time enrollment       → systemd-cryptenroll --tpm2-device=auto
#                                   --tpm2-pcrs=0+2+7+12 <device>
#   add to /etc/crypttab        → options column: tpm2-device=auto
#   rebuild initramfs           → dracut --force
#   re-enroll after firmware    → wipe-slot=tpm2 + re-enroll
#   recovery if it breaks       → original passphrase still works
#   list current slots          → cryptsetup luksDump <device>


GPG AND SSH KEY MANAGEMENT
--------------------------

# the per-user cryptographic identity layer. distinct from
# LUKS (disk), TPM (hardware), MOK (kernel modules), and
# secure boot (firmware) — all of which we cover elsewhere.
# this is "the keys YOU carry."


# MENTAL MODEL — WHAT EACH KEY IS FOR

#   ssh keys  → authenticate YOU to remote machines (git push,
#               server login, scp, rsync, ansible). cheap to
#               make, easy to rotate, store on disk + agent.
#
#   gpg keys  → identity that signs and encrypts. used for:
#                 - signing git commits and tags
#                 - signing rpms you build (see RPM PACKAGING)
#                 - encrypting files / email
#                 - identity proofs (sigstore, trust anchors)
#               longer-lived than ssh keys, more ceremony.
#
#   FIDO2 / WebAuthn → hardware-backed authentication for web
#               and now for ssh and sudo. YubiKey is the
#               canonical token. covered briefly below.
#
#   x509 / PIV → certificates on a smartcard (YubiKey PIV slots).
#               used for some corporate VPNs, smartcard sudo,
#               some SSH setups. niche on workstation.
#
# the rule of thumb: ssh for auth, gpg for signing+encrypting,
# yubikey (or similar) to make either of those hardware-bound.


# SSH KEYS — THE EVERYDAY LAYER

# fedora 44 ships openssh 9.x. the modern default is ed25519
# (small, fast, secure). RSA is still legal but no reason to
# prefer it for new keys.

# generate a key (you can take all defaults):
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "alice@laptop"
# files produced:
#   ~/.ssh/id_ed25519       — private key (chmod 600)
#   ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub   — public key (chmod 644)

# generate with a hardware-bound passkey (requires libfido2):
ssh-keygen -t ed25519-sk -C "alice@laptop-yubikey"
# the private "key" is a stub that the YubiKey signs through.
# losing the YubiKey = losing the key. keep a recovery key.

# always use a passphrase on the on-disk private key. the agent
# (next section) means you only type it once per session.

# ~/.ssh layout (memorize these — every file matters):
#
#   id_ed25519, id_ed25519.pub   — your private / public key pair
#   authorized_keys              — keys allowed to log INTO this
#                                  account (mode 600)
#   known_hosts                  — host keys you've trusted before
#   config                       — per-host shortcuts and options
#
# directory must be mode 700; files generally 600 (private) or
# 644 (public). sshd refuses to use the directory otherwise.

# ~/.ssh/config — the single best ssh productivity unlock:
cat >> ~/.ssh/config <<'EOF'
Host gh
    HostName github.com
    User git
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
    IdentitiesOnly yes

Host prod-*
    User deploy
    Port 2222
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_prod
    ForwardAgent no                # default no; only opt-in per host

Host *.internal
    User alice
    ProxyJump bastion.example.com  # ssh through a jump host
EOF
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/config

# now: `ssh gh`, `ssh prod-web01`, `ssh db.internal` all just
# work without flags.

# copy your public key onto a remote server's authorized_keys:
ssh-copy-id -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub user@host

# fingerprint check (paste into a side channel to verify a
# host or key out-of-band):
ssh-keygen -lf ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub                 # local key
ssh-keyscan -t ed25519 host.example.com | ssh-keygen -lf -


# SSH-AGENT ON FEDORA WORKSTATION

# fedora workstation runs gnome-keyring as the default SSH agent.
# its SSH agent listens on $SSH_AUTH_SOCK, unlocks at GNOME login,
# and re-prompts for the key passphrase the first time you use
# the key.

echo $SSH_AUTH_SOCK
# typical: /run/user/1000/keyring/ssh   ← gnome-keyring
# (older: $XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/ssh-XXXXXX/agent.NNN   ← openssh)

# add a key to the running agent (prompts for passphrase ONCE):
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
ssh-add -L                                            # list loaded keys
ssh-add -D                                            # drop all loaded keys

# when to disable gnome-keyring's SSH agent — if you want:
#   - YubiKey-backed keys exclusively (gnome-keyring doesn't
#     speak the sk-* family well)
#   - a real openssh agent with per-key expiration / confirm
#   - to run a specific agent (1password, bitwarden) for ssh
#
# disable the gnome-keyring SSH component:
mkdir -p ~/.config/autostart
cp /etc/xdg/autostart/gnome-keyring-ssh.desktop \
   ~/.config/autostart/
echo 'Hidden=true' >> ~/.config/autostart/gnome-keyring-ssh.desktop
# log out and back in. now use the upstream openssh agent or
# your tool of choice's agent.


# HARDWARE-BACKED SSH (YUBIKEY)

# two paths, both useful:
#
# 1. FIDO2 ed25519-sk — easiest, modern. the YubiKey signs ssh
#    handshakes. requires openssh 8.2+ on both ends (fine on f44).
ssh-keygen -t ed25519-sk -O resident -C "alice-yubikey"
# `resident` lets you re-derive the key on a fresh machine
# with `ssh-keygen -K`. without `resident`, you keep the stub
# files in ~/.ssh and the key is bound to those files + token.
#
# 2. PIV — older corporate-style. a certificate lives in a
#    PIV slot on the YubiKey; ssh uses pkcs11.
sudo dnf install ykman opensc
ykman piv keys generate 9a /tmp/pub.pem
ykman piv certificates generate 9a /tmp/pub.pem
# then in ~/.ssh/config:
#   PKCS11Provider /usr/lib64/opensc-pkcs11.so
ssh-add -s /usr/lib64/opensc-pkcs11.so               # load from token
ssh-add -e /usr/lib64/opensc-pkcs11.so               # remove

# ykman is the command-line YubiKey manager:
sudo dnf install ykman
ykman info
ykman fido credentials list                           # resident FIDO2 creds
ykman piv info


# GPG KEYS — THE SIGNING / ENCRYPTING LAYER

# fedora ships GnuPG 2.x as `gpg2`, symlinked to `gpg`.
gpg --version

# generate a modern key (master + signing + encryption + auth):
gpg --full-generate-key
# pick: (9) ECC sign and encrypt → (1) Curve 25519 → 0 (never
# expires on the master, expirations on subkeys) → real name,
# email, comment, passphrase.

# what you get (verify with --list-secret-keys):
#   sec    ed25519                     — master (cert/sign)
#   ssb    cv25519                     — encryption subkey
#
# the conventional shape is: master that ONLY certifies, plus
# subkeys for sign / encrypt / auth. add them after creation:
gpg --edit-key alice@example.com
> addkey                  # ed25519, sign
> addkey                  # cv25519, encrypt
> addkey                  # ed25519, auth (for ssh-via-gpg)
> save

# why subkeys? you can rotate signing/encryption keys yearly
# without changing your identity. the master cert key lives
# offline (USB stick in a safe).

# list / inspect:
gpg --list-keys
gpg --list-secret-keys
gpg --fingerprint alice@example.com                  # 40-hex full fp
gpg -K --with-keygrip                                 # internal handles


# GPG BACKUP — DO THIS THE DAY YOU GENERATE A KEY

# export EVERYTHING you'd need to recover from a fresh machine:
gpg --export-secret-keys --armor alice@example.com  > ~/gpg-backup-secret.asc
gpg --export-secret-subkeys --armor alice@example.com > ~/gpg-backup-subkeys.asc
gpg --export-ownertrust > ~/gpg-backup-trust.txt
gpg --gen-revoke alice@example.com > ~/gpg-revoke.asc

# paper backup — paperkey extracts only the actually-needed
# secret material (no metadata bloat) so it prints small:
sudo dnf install paperkey
gpg --export-secret-keys alice@example.com | paperkey -o ~/gpg-paper.txt
# print, store in a safe deposit box, fireproof safe, or
# similar. burn the digital copy.

# store the revocation certificate offline. if your private key
# leaks, this is the ONLY way to invalidate it on keyservers.


# GPG-AGENT + PINENTRY ON WAYLAND

# gpg-agent is started on demand by gpg. on wayland it needs a
# graphical pinentry — fedora workstation ships pinentry-gnome3
# which is the right default.

# verify which pinentry is wired in:
cat ~/.gnupg/gpg-agent.conf 2>/dev/null
which pinentry pinentry-gnome3 pinentry-curses

# common failure: "Inappropriate ioctl for device" or no pinentry
# popup. fix — write an explicit pinentry-program line:
mkdir -p ~/.gnupg && chmod 700 ~/.gnupg
cat > ~/.gnupg/gpg-agent.conf <<'EOF'
pinentry-program /usr/bin/pinentry-gnome3
default-cache-ttl 600
max-cache-ttl 7200
EOF
gpg-connect-agent reloadagent /bye

# if you SSH and want pinentry on the LOCAL machine for remote
# gpg, gpg-agent has socket forwarding — niche, skip unless you
# need it.


# SIGNING GIT COMMITS — THE TWO MODERN PATHS

# you have a choice in 2026: sign with GPG (long-established) or
# sign with SSH (newer, simpler, increasingly preferred).

# Path A — sign with GPG:
git config --global user.signingkey  <KEYID>
git config --global commit.gpgsign   true
git config --global tag.gpgsign      true
git commit -S -m "signed commit"        # explicit
# github / gitlab will display the "Verified" badge after you
# upload the public key to your account settings.

# Path B — sign with SSH (git ≥ 2.34):
git config --global gpg.format        ssh
git config --global user.signingkey   ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
git config --global commit.gpgsign    true

# verify a commit locally requires an allowed_signers file:
echo "alice@example.com $(cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub)" \
    > ~/.config/git/allowed_signers
git config --global gpg.ssh.allowedSignersFile \
    ~/.config/git/allowed_signers
git log --show-signature

# ssh-key signing is simpler because you already have an ssh
# key. github accepts ssh-signed commits since 2022. use it
# unless you specifically need gpg's web-of-trust semantics.


# SIGNING RPMS — FORWARD POINTER

# building and signing your own rpms — gpg-key creation, the
# %_gpg_name macro, rpm --addsign, rpmsign — lives in the
# RPM PACKAGING section. you'll reuse the same gpg key from
# above.


# YUBIKEY FOR GPG (SMARTCARD MODE)

# moves your gpg PRIVATE keys onto the YubiKey. master cert key
# can also live there. once moved, the keys NEVER leave the
# token — every signature/decryption requires a touch.

gpg --card-status                            # YubiKey detected?
gpg --card-edit                              # interactive
> admin
> name / lang / sex                          # cardholder info
> kdf-setup                                  # secure PIN hashing
> passwd                                     # change admin PIN
> quit

# move a subkey onto the card:
gpg --edit-key alice@example.com
> key 1                                       # select signing subkey
> keytocard                                   # move it
> save
# CAREFUL: keytocard moves, doesn't copy. make sure you have
# the backup from earlier BEFORE you do this.

# now on any machine: insert YubiKey → `gpg --card-status` to
# pick up the stubs → sign / decrypt as normal. no private
# material on disk.


# PUBLISHING + DISCOVERING KEYS

# WKD (Web Key Directory) is the modern way. domain owners
# publish keys at https://<domain>/.well-known/openpgpkey/...
gpg --auto-key-locate clear,wkd,nodefault --locate-key bob@example.com

# keys.openpgp.org is the cleanest keyserver — it validates
# email control and strips unverified third-party signatures.
gpg --keyserver hkps://keys.openpgp.org --send-keys <KEYID>
gpg --keyserver hkps://keys.openpgp.org --recv-keys <KEYID>

# the SKS keyserver network is dead (poisoning attack, 2019).
# don't bother with pgp.mit.edu, sks-keyservers.net, or
# similar — they're either offline or unreliable.

# keybase still works for old identities but stopped getting
# meaningful development after the Zoom acquisition. don't
# build new flows on it.


# ROTATION + REVOCATION

# rotation cadence (rule of thumb, not gospel):
#   ssh keys                        → no schedule; rotate on
#                                     suspicion of compromise
#                                     or hardware change
#   gpg signing/encryption subkeys  → yearly
#   gpg master cert key             → 3-5 years, or on compromise
#   yubikey-resident keys           → lifetime of the YubiKey

# extend a subkey's expiration (without rotating):
gpg --edit-key alice@example.com
> key 1
> expire
> 1y
> save
gpg --send-keys <KEYID>        # republish

# revoke a leaked key — use the pre-generated revocation cert:
gpg --import ~/gpg-revoke.asc
gpg --send-keys <KEYID>
# the revocation propagates to anyone who fetches from the
# keyserver. this is why you generate the revoke cert and
# store it BEFORE you need it.


# HONEST TRADEOFFS

# the security upgrade from "ssh key + passphrase on disk" to
# "YubiKey-backed ed25519-sk" is real but small. the upgrade
# from "no agent, no passphrase, no signed commits" to "any
# agent + passphrase + signed commits" is much bigger. don't
# skip the easy wins chasing the hard ones.

# gpg gets a reputation as user-hostile partly because the
# defaults pre-2018 were genuinely bad. modern gpg 2.x with
# ed25519/cv25519 and pinentry-gnome3 is fine. start there.

# rotating gpg subkeys is unsexy but easy and worth doing.
# rotating the master key is a real ceremony — re-publishing,
# losing your old web-of-trust signatures, etc. push that out
# as far as the cadence above suggests.

# ssh commit signing is increasingly the right default. gpg
# signing matters if you also sign rpms or care about WKD /
# Sequoia / web-of-trust semantics.


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   make an ssh key                  → ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "me@host"
#   copy pubkey to server            → ssh-copy-id user@host
#   start using ssh aliases          → ~/.ssh/config (chmod 600)
#   hardware-backed ssh              → ssh-keygen -t ed25519-sk -O resident
#   load key into agent              → ssh-add
#   make a gpg key                   → gpg --full-generate-key
#   list secret keys                 → gpg -K
#   backup a gpg key                 → gpg --export-secret-keys --armor > file
#   paper-print a gpg key            → gpg --export-secret-keys | paperkey
#   sign git commits with gpg        → commit.gpgsign + user.signingkey
#   sign git commits with ssh        → gpg.format=ssh + ssh pubkey path
#   move gpg key onto YubiKey        → gpg --edit-key → key N → keytocard
#   publish a gpg key                → keys.openpgp.org + WKD
#   revoke a leaked gpg key          → gpg --import revoke.asc + --send-keys


