PRINTING AND SCANNING
---------------------

# the stack on fedora workstation:
#
#   CUPS                 — the print daemon. always running, listens
#                          on localhost:631 with a web interface.
#   IPP-Everywhere       — driverless printing standard. covers most
#                          printers manufactured since 2018. zero-config
#                          for the user; no vendor driver needed.
#   cups-filters         — translates print jobs through ghostscript
#                          and friends.
#   HPLIP (hp-*)         — HP's vendor printer stack. needed for many
#                          HP printers (scanner side especially).
#   SANE                 — the scanner driver framework. sane-utils
#                          (CLI), simple-scan / document-scanner (GUI).
#   Avahi (mDNS)         — network printer discovery. preinstalled.
#                          covered in NETWORKING section.


# ADDING A PRINTER — THE EASY PATH

# Settings → Printers → Add Printer (GNOME)
# (KDE: System Settings → Printers)
# the GUI scans for IPP-Everywhere + mDNS printers automatically.
# pick yours from the list, name it, done.

# the CUPS web interface — when the GUI isn't enough:
#   http://localhost:631
# add printer, manage queues, view jobs. login as a sudoers user.

# from the CLI — useful for headless or scripted setup:
sudo dnf install cups-pdf                          # virtual PDF printer
lpinfo -v                                          # discovered printers
lpinfo -m                                          # available drivers
lpadmin -p MyPrinter \
    -E \
    -v "ipp://192.168.1.20/ipp/print" \
    -m everywhere
lpoptions -d MyPrinter                             # set as default


# IPP-EVERYWHERE — DRIVERLESS PRINTING

# IPP-Everywhere (a.k.a. "driverless printing") means the printer
# speaks the IPP protocol natively + advertises its capabilities over
# mDNS. CUPS picks them up without per-vendor drivers. supports:
#   - most HP, Brother, Canon, Epson, Xerox printers since 2018
#   - AirPrint printers (apple's marketing name for IPP-Everywhere)
#   - most modern network laser printers

# verify a printer is IPP-Everywhere capable:
sudo dnf install ipp-usb avahi-tools
avahi-browse -rt _ipp._tcp                         # IPP printers on LAN
ippfind                                            # canonical scan


# HP PRINTERS — HPLIP

# many HP printers (especially MFPs with scanners) need HPLIP for
# full functionality. the GUI walks through detection + queue setup:
sudo dnf install hplip hplip-gui
hp-setup                                           # interactive setup

# CLI variants:
hp-info -i                                         # device info
hp-check                                           # diagnostic
hp-firmware -l                                     # firmware status


# NETWORK PRINTER DISCOVERY

# Avahi handles mDNS / DNS-SD. printers advertising _ipp._tcp,
# _ipps._tcp, or _printer._tcp show up automatically. inspect:
avahi-browse -rt _ipp._tcp                         # IPP
avahi-browse -rt _ipps._tcp                        # IPPS (secured)
avahi-browse -rt _printer._tcp                     # LPD-style
avahi-browse -art                                  # everything (filter manually)

# if printers aren't appearing:
#   - firewall: make sure mDNS UDP/5353 is open in your zone
#   - firewalld zone: FedoraWorkstation allows mDNS by default; if
#     you're on the public zone, allow it:
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=mdns --permanent && \
    sudo firewall-cmd --reload


# AIRPRINT COMPATIBILITY

# AirPrint = IPP-Everywhere + Bonjour. if your printer supports
# AirPrint, it works with linux out of the box. nothing to configure.
# CUPS also exposes attached USB printers via AirPrint for iOS / mac
# clients on the LAN — set "Share This Printer" in CUPS web ui.


# SCANNING — SANE

sudo dnf install sane-backends sane-utils \
    simple-scan gnome-document-scanner

# CLI scanning:
scanimage -L                                       # list scanners
scanimage --format=png > scan.png                  # default settings
scanimage --device=epson2:libusb:002:003 --format=png > scan.png

# GUI: simple-scan (lightweight) or Document Scanner (newer GNOME app)
simple-scan                                        # one-shot scans
# or: launch "Document Scanner" from Activities

# HP MFPs: scanner is reached through HPLIP + hp-scan:
hp-scan -m flatbed                                 # one-shot
hp-scan --output=scan.png


# NETWORK SCANNERS

# many MFPs share their scanner over the network (eSCL protocol,
# Apple's marketing name "AirScan"). detection:
sudo dnf install sane-airscan
scanimage -L                                       # should now show
                                                   # network MFPs


# SELINUX + PRINTING/SCANNING

# default policy covers normal use. if you hit denials:
# - allow CUPS to write to NFS-mounted spool:
sudo setsebool -P cups_execmem 1
# - allow scanning from a user-mounted USB device:
sudo setsebool -P sanlock_use_usb 1
# - debug with:
sudo ausearch -m AVC -ts recent -c cupsd
sudo sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. PRINTER FOUND BUT JOBS STAY "PROCESSING" FOREVER. likely a queue
#    problem. clear and restart:
sudo systemctl restart cups
cancel -a                                          # cancel all jobs
#    if persistent, check the printer's web ui — often a paper-out
#    or toner-low pause that CUPS doesn't surface clearly.
#
# 2. DOUBLE-SIDED PRINTING DEFAULTS BACKWARDS. set the per-printer
#    default:
lpoptions -p MyPrinter -o sides=two-sided-long-edge
#    options: one-sided / two-sided-long-edge / two-sided-short-edge.
#
# 3. JOBS COME OUT SCALED WRONG (page area). default media size
#    mismatch:
lpoptions -p MyPrinter -o media=Letter             # or A4, Legal, etc.
#
# 4. COLOR PROFILE LOOKS OFF. install gnome-color-manager and
#    calibrate via Settings → Color (needs a colorimeter for proper
#    profiling; default sRGB is fine for most use).
#
# 5. PRINTING TO A LAN PRINTER THAT WORKED YESTERDAY. the printer
#    likely got a new DHCP-assigned IP. either set a static lease on
#    your router, or use the printer's mDNS .local hostname instead
#    of an IP in the URI:
#       ipp://myprinter.local/ipp/print
#
# 6. WIFI PRINTER DROPS OFF THE NETWORK. usually printer-side power-
#    save. check the printer's own settings for "always-on wifi" or
#    "deep sleep disabled".
#
# 7. SCANNING FROM AN HP MFP DOESN'T WORK BUT PRINTING DOES. install
#    hplip-common and run hp-setup with --type=scan. some older HP
#    MFPs need a specific scanner backend selected.
#
# 8. CUPS WEB UI REJECTS YOUR LOGIN. you need to be in the
#    `lpadmin` group:
sudo usermod -aG lpadmin "$USER"
#    log out + back in.


# SHARING A PRINTER FROM THIS MACHINE

# turn this fedora box into a print server other devices can use:
sudo cupsctl --share-printers --remote-any
# then per-printer: enable sharing in CUPS web UI → Printers →
# MyPrinter → Administration → Set Default Options → Set as Server
# Default. other clients (iOS, mac, windows, other linux) will see
# it via Avahi automatically.


# DECISION MATRIX

#   "I have a modern (2018+) network printer"     → IPP-Everywhere auto-detect
#   "I have an HP printer or MFP"                 → HPLIP + hp-setup
#   "I want CLI scanning automation"              → scanimage
#   "I want a GUI for occasional scans"           → simple-scan
#   "MFP scanner on the LAN"                      → sane-airscan
#   "I want this fedora to be a LAN print server" → cupsctl --share-printers
#   "old USB printer with no IPP support"         → CUPS web UI add manually,
#                                                   pick driver from list


TUNED PROFILES — PERFORMANCE / LATENCY TUNING
---------------------------------------------

# tuned is fedora's system-tuning daemon: declarative performance
# profiles that adjust kernel sysctls, CPU governors, IO schedulers,
# network buffers, transparent hugepages, vm dirty ratios, and more.
# shipped since F8; the canonical perf-knob manager on RHEL.
#
# how it fits next to POWER MANAGEMENT's power-profiles-daemon (PPD):
# PPD is desktop-oriented (Performance / Balanced / Power Saver,
# UI-driven, GNOME integrated). tuned is workload-oriented (latency-
# performance, network-throughput, virtual-host, etc., CLI-driven,
# RHEL heritage). they CAN coexist on workstation but generally one
# should be in charge of CPU governor at a time.


# INSTALL + DAILY

# tuned is preinstalled on workstation / server / atomic. enable:
sudo systemctl enable --now tuned

# core CLI:
tuned-adm active                                # current profile
tuned-adm list                                  # all shipped profiles
tuned-adm recommend                             # auto-pick based on
                                                # platform detection
sudo tuned-adm profile latency-performance      # apply a profile
sudo tuned-adm verify                           # check applied vs current
sudo tuned-adm off                              # stop tuning (revert)


# THE SHIPPED PROFILES — BY CATEGORY

# DESKTOP / GENERAL
#   balanced              — sensible default; mild power saving.
#                           default on workstation if PPD isn't owning
#                           the governor.
#   desktop               — derives from balanced; more interactive
#                           weights.
#   powersave             — aggressive power saving; longer battery,
#                           lower perf. similar to PPD's "Power Saver".
#
# PERFORMANCE
#   throughput-performance — max throughput; performance governor,
#                           no power saving. databases, batch jobs,
#                           build farms.
#   latency-performance   — minimize latency over throughput. HFT,
#                           pro audio, real-time response.
#   network-throughput    — large TCP buffers, conservative CPU; ideal
#                           for sustained network transfers.
#   network-latency       — low-latency network tuning; sysctl tweaks
#                           for tail-latency-sensitive apps.
#   accelerator-performance — for GPU / NPU compute workloads.
#
# VIRTUALIZATION
#   virtual-host          — KVM hypervisor host; transparent hugepages,
#                           CPU isolation for guests.
#   virtual-guest         — running INSIDE a VM; disables host-side
#                           tuning (paravirt aware).
#
# SPECIALIZED
#   realtime              — strict realtime kernel tuning; pairs with
#                           `kernel-rt`. for industrial control,
#                           studio audio.
#   realtime-virtual-host — both at once.
#   hpc-compute           — supercomputing / parallel workloads.
#   optimize-serial-console — for headless server install with serial
#                           console primary.
#
# ATOMIC / IoT
#   atomic-host           — fedora CoreOS host tuning.
#   atomic-guest          — coreOS guest.


# CUSTOM PROFILES

# create your own based on a shipped one:
sudo mkdir -p /etc/tuned/my-profile
sudo tee /etc/tuned/my-profile/tuned.conf <<'EOF'
[main]
summary=My workload-specific tuning
include=throughput-performance

[sysctl]
vm.swappiness=1
vm.dirty_ratio=10
net.core.netdev_max_backlog=300000
net.ipv4.tcp_congestion_control=bbr

[cpu]
governor=performance
energy_perf_bias=performance

[disk]
elevator=mq-deadline
readahead=>4096

[vm]
transparent_hugepages=always
EOF

sudo tuned-adm profile my-profile
sudo tuned-adm verify


# CPU PARTITIONING — ISOLATING CORES FOR LATENCY-CRITICAL APPS

# the `cpu-partitioning` profile (or a custom one with the
# `cpu-partitioning` plugin) reserves specific cores for your latency-
# critical workload, leaving the kernel + housekeeping on the others.
# pair with `nohz_full=` and `isolcpus=` on the kernel cmdline (see
# KERNEL CMDLINE section).

# example custom config:
sudo tee /etc/tuned/no-housekeeping/tuned.conf <<'EOF'
[main]
summary=Isolate cores 2-7 for app, leave 0-1 for kernel
include=cpu-partitioning

[variables]
isolated_cores=2-7
not_isolated_cores=0-1
EOF


# HOW TUNED AND POWER-PROFILES-DAEMON COEXIST

# fedora workstation ships BOTH by default. both can adjust the CPU
# governor; running both unconstrained can fight.
#
# common arrangements:
#   - DESKTOP USE: let PPD drive (GNOME UI integration is the win),
#     mask tuned:
#         sudo systemctl mask tuned
#   - SERVER USE: tuned drives, no PPD installed.
#   - WORKLOAD-AWARE DESKTOP (rare): tuned drives, mask PPD:
#         sudo systemctl mask power-profiles-daemon


# WORKLOADS WHERE TUNED MATTERS

#   - DATABASES (postgres, mysql, redis, mongo) → throughput-performance
#     plus dirty-ratio tuning. measurable wins on write-heavy workloads.
#   - HFT / LOW-LATENCY TRADING → realtime or custom latency-performance
#     plus cpu-partitioning, RT kernel, IRQ pinning.
#   - VIDEO ENCODING (ffmpeg, handbrake) → throughput-performance.
#     5-15% wall-clock improvement on long jobs.
#   - PRO AUDIO (ardour, jack-based) → latency-performance plus
#     pipewire low-latency tuning (see AUDIO).
#   - KVM HOSTS → virtual-host. essential for production.
#   - HOMELAB NAS → balanced (most files at rest); throughput-performance
#     during large rsync / borg runs.
#   - DPDK / HIGH-PPS NETWORKING → network-latency plus cpu-partitioning.


# PLUGINS — WHAT TUNED CAN TWEAK

# tuned profiles use plugins to actually apply changes. the common ones:
#
#   sysctl              — kernel parameters via /proc/sys
#   cpu                 — governor, energy_perf_bias, idle states
#   disk                — IO scheduler, readahead, alpm
#   net                 — wake-on-lan, ring buffers, coalescing
#   vm                  — transparent hugepages, swappiness, dirty_*
#   scheduler           — CPU isolation, IRQ pinning, polling
#   selinux             — booleans (for very narrow tuning needs)
#   script              — run arbitrary shell on profile switch
#   sysfs               — write arbitrary /sys files
#   modules             — load / unload kernel modules
#   bootloader          — add kernel args (modifies grub config)
#
# full reference: man tuned.conf, /usr/lib/tuned/profiles/


# VERIFICATION AND DEBUGGING

tuned-adm verify                                # current vs applied
sudo journalctl -u tuned -b                    # tuned logs this boot
sudo journalctl -u tuned -f                    # follow
ls /usr/lib/tuned/                              # shipped profiles
ls /etc/tuned/                                  # your overrides
cat /sys/devices/system/cpu/cpu*/cpufreq/scaling_governor   # confirm
                                                # governor change


# CROSS-REFERENCES

# - POWER MANAGEMENT: power-profiles-daemon (the desktop counterpart)
# - GAMING: gamemode (which is essentially an ad-hoc, per-launch
#   throughput-performance applier)
# - AUDIO: pro audio + pipewire low-latency tuning pairs with the
#   latency-performance profile
# - KERNEL CMDLINE: isolcpus, nohz_full, mitigations work hand in hand
#   with cpu-partitioning


# DECISION MATRIX

#   "default fedora workstation"                  → balanced (or PPD)
#   "long laptop battery life"                    → powersave / PPD saver
#   "database server"                             → throughput-performance
#   "real-time audio production"                  → latency-performance
#                                                    + RT kernel
#   "HFT / low-latency trading"                   → realtime + cpu-
#                                                    partitioning
#   "video encoding farm"                         → throughput-performance
#   "KVM host"                                    → virtual-host
#   "running INSIDE a vm"                         → virtual-guest
#   "DPDK / high-PPS networking"                  → network-latency +
#                                                    cpu-partitioning
#   "i don't know"                                → tuned-adm recommend


PERFORMANCE INVESTIGATION TOOLKIT
---------------------------------

# TUNED PROFILES gave you levers; this section gives you the
# DIAGNOSTIC muscle to know which lever to pull. the goal is to
# answer two questions fast: which of the four resources is the
# bottleneck, and which process is responsible.


# THE FOUR-CORNERS MODEL

# every performance problem is one (or more) of:
#
#   CPU      — cores are pinned, runqueue is long
#   MEMORY   — RSS pressure, swap thrash, OOM kills
#   DISK     — I/O saturated, queue depth high, fsync stalls
#   NETWORK  — bandwidth maxed, retransmits, latency spikes
#
# the most common diagnostic mistake is drilling down before
# identifying the corner. always do a fast top-down sweep
# first. if you can't identify the corner in 60 seconds, you
# either don't have the right top-down tool installed, or the
# bottleneck is in a fifth place (GPU, scheduler latency,
# noisy-neighbor in a cgroup) — covered below.


# INSTALL THE TOOLKIT ONCE

# fedora's defaults are minimal. install the diagnostic set on
# every machine you care about:
sudo dnf install \
    htop btop sysstat                          \
    iotop-c                                    \
    nethogs iftop bmon mtr-gui                 \
    bcc-tools bpftrace                         \
    perf strace lsof                           \
    nvme-cli smartmontools                     \
    dool                                       \
    # zram-stats included with util-linux
sudo systemctl enable --now sysstat            # sar history collection


# THE 60-SECOND TRIAGE

# run this top-down sweep BEFORE drilling in. it answers
# "which corner?" in under a minute.

uptime                                          # 1, 5, 15 min loadavg
# loadavg > #CPUs ≈ runqueue building. > 2×#CPUs = bad.

free -h                                         # memory + swap
# "available" matters more than "free". if available is small
# AND swap is climbing → memory pressure.

vmstat 1 5                                      # full-system 5 samples
# si/so > 0 → swapping. high "wa" → I/O wait. high "us"+"sy"
# → CPU-bound.

iostat -xz 1 5                                  # disk per-device 5 samples
# %util near 100 → disk saturated. high await → I/O latency
# is the bottleneck even if utilization is low.

sar -n DEV 1 5                                  # network rate per iface
# rxkB/s + txkB/s near link speed → network saturated.

cat /proc/pressure/cpu /proc/pressure/memory /proc/pressure/io
# PSI: avg10 > 10 means SOMETHING is waiting for that resource
# 10%+ of the time over the last 10s. very fast way to spot
# pressure that top-level utilization misses.

# pick the highest signal corner. drill into that one ONLY.


# CPU — DRILLING DOWN

mpstat -P ALL 1                                 # per-core breakdown
# one core pinned but others idle = single-threaded hot path
# (a real fedora workstation gotcha — pin the bottleneck
# process to multiple cores or fix the app).

htop                                            # interactive top
btop                                            # prettier; same data
# F4 to filter, F6 to sort by various counters. mark threads
# of one process with `t` view.

# the single most useful CPU command in linux:
sudo perf top                                   # live cpu-cycle histogram
# shows which kernel/user functions are eating cpu RIGHT NOW.
# almost always identifies the hot path on the first run.

# capture a profile of one command:
sudo perf record -F 99 -ag -- sleep 30          # 30s, all cores
sudo perf report                                # ncurses browser
# render a flamegraph (install brendangregg/FlameGraph or use perf script):
sudo perf script | stackcollapse-perf | flamegraph > out.svg

# CPU counters (cache, branches, etc.) for a single command:
sudo perf stat -d ./mybinary
# look at IPC ("insns per cycle"). < 0.5 typically means
# cache-miss heavy or memory-bound.


# MEMORY — THE CONFUSING ONE

# the right "is memory tight?" number on linux is NOT "free":
free -h
#   used   = real memory in use
#   free   = literally untouched
#   shared = tmpfs + shm
#   buff/cache = page cache + slab (RECLAIMABLE)
#   available = the meaningful "could be used by a new alloc"

# the rule: "available" is your headroom. if available is
# small AND swap activity is climbing AND PSI memory shows
# pressure, you have a memory problem.

vmstat 1                                        # si/so columns = swap activity
swapon --show
# zram-swap is fedora's default (a compressed in-RAM swap).
# moderate so > 0 is OK; sustained so > si means active eviction.

# per-process memory usage that doesn't double-count shared pages:
sudo dnf install smem
smem -tk -s rss                                 # rss
smem -tk -s pss                                 # proportional set size
# pss is the right "this process's share of memory" number on
# linux. rss double-counts shared libs.

# kernel slab cache (filesystem inodes, dentries, network
# buffers) — overlooked source of pressure:
sudo slabtop -o
# huge dentry / inode caches after a `find /` are normal and
# reclaimable. huge unreclaimable slabs are bug territory.

# detailed view of one process's memory map:
sudo pmap -X <pid> | head -30                   # who's holding what

# /proc/meminfo as the canonical source:
grep -E '^(MemTotal|MemAvailable|Cached|SReclaimable|Slab|Committed_AS)' \
    /proc/meminfo

# OOM kills — when memory ran out and the kernel started reaping:
sudo journalctl -k | grep -iE 'oom|killed process'


# DISK — IOPS, THROUGHPUT, AND THE LATENCY YOU FEEL

iostat -xz 1                                    # per-device, 1-sec samples
# columns to watch:
#   %util    — saturation
#   await    — total I/O latency (ms)
#   r_await  / w_await — read vs write latency split
#   r/s w/s  — IOPS
#   rkB/s wkB/s — throughput
#   aqu-sz   — average queue depth (high + high await = busy)

# per-process disk I/O (the answer to "who's hammering the disk?"):
sudo iotop -ao                                  # accumulated, only-IO procs
sudo pidstat -d 1                               # text equivalent
# also:
sudo dool --top-bio-adv 5                       # dstat's rust replacement

# kernel-level disk latency histogram (bcc-tools):
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/biolatency 10 1
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/biosnoop                # per-IO trace

# nvme-specific telemetry:
sudo nvme list
sudo nvme smart-log /dev/nvme0n1
# look at percentage_used (wearout %), media_errors, available_spare

# fsync stalls (the classic "my journal is full" symptom):
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/fsync                  # not always present;
# alternative: bpftrace one-liner:
sudo bpftrace -e 'tracepoint:syscalls:sys_enter_fsync { @[comm]=count(); }'

# disks supporting SMART (covered in DISK MANAGEMENT):
sudo smartctl -a /dev/nvme0n1


# NETWORK — RATES, CONNECTIONS, AND LATENCY

# per-interface rates:
sar -n DEV 1                                    # 5 samples by default
ip -s -c link                                   # colored interface stats
bmon                                            # interactive bandwidth meter
iftop -i wlp3s0                                 # per-flow live view

# per-process network usage (the easiest "who's hogging the link"):
sudo nethogs

# active connections — the modern replacement for netstat:
ss -tunap                                       # tcp+udp, numeric, with proc
ss -tlnp                                        # what's LISTENING
ss -tup state established                       # only established tcp

# latency to a host (more useful than ping for path problems):
mtr -rwn -c 100 8.8.8.8                         # 100 packets, report mode
# packet loss at hop 3 means the problem is upstream of hop 3.

# bandwidth between two hosts (need iperf3 on both ends):
sudo dnf install iperf3
# host A: iperf3 -s
# host B: iperf3 -c <host-A-ip> -t 30

# packet capture (mostly when ss + mtr aren't enough):
sudo tcpdump -i any -nn -w /tmp/cap.pcap host 192.0.2.5 and port 443
# capture for ~30s, ctrl+c, then:
wireshark /tmp/cap.pcap                         # GUI analysis

# what FILES (sockets included) a process has open:
sudo lsof -p <pid>                              # everything
sudo lsof -i -p <pid>                           # only sockets
sudo lsof -i :443                               # who's bound to 443
sudo lsof +D /var/log                           # who has files open under a dir


# PROCESS-LEVEL DRILL-DOWN

# the most common per-process inspection chain:
ps auxf | head -20                              # process tree
pidstat 1 5                                     # cpu per process
pidstat -d 1 5                                  # disk I/O per process
pidstat -r 1 5                                  # rss / page faults per process
pidstat -w 1 5                                  # context switches per process

# /proc/<pid> is the canonical source for everything kernel
# knows about a process:
cat /proc/<pid>/status                          # state, threads, RSS, sigs
cat /proc/<pid>/io                              # bytes read/written
cat /proc/<pid>/limits                          # ulimits
cat /proc/<pid>/cgroup                          # which cgroup it's in
ls -l /proc/<pid>/fd/                           # every open fd
cat /proc/<pid>/stack                           # kernel stack (where it's blocked)

# resource limits (file descriptors, processes, memlock):
prlimit -p <pid>
prlimit -p <pid> --nofile=65536                 # change a limit at runtime

# strace — what syscalls is the process making?
sudo strace -fp <pid>                           # follow, attach
sudo strace -c -p <pid>                         # summarize on detach
# CAUTION: strace pauses the process at every syscall. heavy
# overhead. for production load, prefer:
sudo perf trace -p <pid>                        # lighter syscall tracer


# BPF / BCC — KERNEL OBSERVABILITY WITHOUT THE OVERHEAD

# bcc-tools is the canonical collection. installed above. the
# scripts live at /usr/share/bcc/tools/. high-value ones:
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/execsnoop             # every exec() in real time
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/opensnoop             # every open() in real time
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/biolatency            # block I/O latency histogram
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/cachestat             # page cache hit/miss
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/runqlat               # scheduler runqueue latency
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/tcpconnect            # outbound tcp connect attempts
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/tcpretrans            # tcp retransmits — network-blame
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/profile               # cpu profile via bpf

# bpftrace one-liners (the awk of kernel tracing):
sudo bpftrace -e 'tracepoint:syscalls:sys_enter_openat { @[comm]=count(); }'
sudo bpftrace -e 'kprobe:vfs_read { @bytes[comm] = hist(arg2); }'

# bpf is the right tool when strace would distort the workload.
# it runs in-kernel, attaches to tracepoints/kprobes, aggregates
# in maps, and emits summaries. nearly zero overhead per call.


# SYSTEMD — UNITS, CGROUPS, BOOT

# resource by service (the missing "top by systemd unit"):
sudo systemd-cgtop                              # interactive
sudo systemctl status myapp.service             # one unit's cpu / mem
sudo systemctl show myapp.service \
    -p MemoryCurrent,CPUUsageNSec,IOReadBytes

# failed units:
systemctl --failed
sudo journalctl -p err -b                       # errors this boot

# boot time investigation (covered in SYSTEMD too):
systemd-analyze                                 # total + per-phase
systemd-analyze blame                           # slowest units
systemd-analyze critical-chain                  # slowest serialization chain
systemd-analyze plot > /tmp/boot.svg            # SVG timeline

# cap resource use of an existing service via drop-in (see SYSTEMD):
sudo systemctl edit myapp.service
# under [Service]:
#   CPUWeight=50
#   MemoryHigh=2G
#   IOWeight=50


# GPU

# pick the right tool for the GPU:
nvidia-smi dmon -s u                            # nvidia, 1s sample
radeontop                                       # amd
amdgpu_top                                      # newer amd (rust)
intel_gpu_top                                   # intel
nvtop                                           # vendor-agnostic, htop-style

# GPU bottleneck symptoms:
#   - smooth video / game stutters but CPU is idle → check GPU
#   - vaapi-decoded video uses high CPU → vaapi isn't actually
#     wired up. see HARDWARE-ACCELERATED VIDEO.


# PRESSURE STALL INFORMATION (PSI)

# linux 4.20+ exposes a single, statistical signal per resource:
# "what % of the last 10s/60s/300s was SOMETHING stalled on this?"
cat /proc/pressure/cpu                          # often "some" only
cat /proc/pressure/memory                       # some + full
cat /proc/pressure/io                           # some + full

# `some` = at least one task waiting. `full` = ALL tasks waiting.
# `full memory` > 5% sustained means the system is thrashing
# even if `free -h` looks OK. this is the most reliable
# "memory is tight" signal on modern fedora.

# per-cgroup PSI (any systemd service):
cat /sys/fs/cgroup/system.slice/myapp.service/cpu.pressure


# LOGS — DON'T FORGET TO READ THEM

journalctl -p warning -b                        # this boot, warning+
journalctl -p err -b -p err                     # errors only
journalctl -k -b                                # kernel only
dmesg -T --color=always | less                  # kernel ring with timestamps
journalctl -o short-precise -u myapp            # microsecond timestamps

# correlate timestamps with monitoring data. a service blip at
# 14:32:17 + a kernel I/O error at 14:32:16 is the answer.


# COMMON WORKFLOWS

# "the system feels sluggish"
uptime; free -h; vmstat 1 5; iostat -xz 1 5
cat /proc/pressure/{cpu,memory,io}
# whichever shows the highest signal: that's your corner.

# "this one app is slow"
sudo perf record -F 99 -p <pid> -g -- sleep 30
sudo perf report
# also:
sudo strace -c -p <pid>                         # syscall summary
sudo pidstat -d -p <pid> 1                      # disk per process

# "memory pressure suspected"
free -h; smem -tk -s pss | tail -20
cat /proc/pressure/memory
sudo journalctl -k | grep -i oom

# "is the network the bottleneck?"
ss -tunap | wc -l                               # how many sockets
mtr -rwn -c 100 <target>
sar -n DEV 1 5
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/tcpretrans

# "is the disk the bottleneck?"
iostat -xz 1 5                                  # which device
sudo iotop -ao                                  # which process
sudo /usr/share/bcc/tools/biolatency 10 1       # latency distribution

# "did this commit make things slower?"
sudo perf stat -d ./before
sudo perf stat -d ./after
# IPC, cache misses, branch mispredictions side-by-side.


# HONEST TRADEOFFS

# building muscle memory on this stack pays off forever.
# memorize the 60-second triage; once "which corner?" is
# instant, everything else slots into place.

# don't reach for strace on production. it pauses the target
# at every syscall. for hot paths, perf trace or bpftrace are
# nearly free.

# `top` / `htop` / `btop` are diagnostic-tools-as-eye-candy.
# fine to leave open in a corner; not where the answers come
# from. the answers come from `vmstat`, `iostat`, `mpstat`,
# `pidstat`, `perf`, `bpftrace` — none of which are pretty.

# PSI is the single best "is this tight?" signal that wasn't
# available pre-2019. learn to read it before you trust
# averages from top/free/iostat.


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   "which corner is saturated?"      → uptime + vmstat + iostat + sar -n DEV + PSI
#   "what's eating the CPU?"          → perf top   (then perf record -g for a profile)
#   "what's eating memory?"           → smem -tk -s pss   +   /proc/pressure/memory
#   "what's eating the disk?"         → iotop -ao   +   biolatency
#   "what's eating the network?"      → nethogs   +   sar -n DEV   +   tcpretrans
#   "who's listening on port X?"      → ss -tlnp | grep :X
#   "who has this file open?"         → lsof <file>
#   "why is the app blocked?"         → cat /proc/<pid>/stack
#   "is memory really tight?"         → /proc/pressure/memory `full` > 5%
#   "boot is slow"                    → systemd-analyze blame / critical-chain
#   "what just ran?"                  → bcc-tools execsnoop
#   "what just opened?"               → bcc-tools opensnoop
#   "kernel says what?"               → journalctl -k -b   +   dmesg -T


# cross-references
# - TUNED PROFILES section: once you've identified the corner,
#   the right tuned profile is the first lever to pull
# - SYSTEMD section: CPUWeight / MemoryHigh / IOWeight resource
#   control, cgroup-level limits per service
# - DISK MANAGEMENT section: smartmontools, nvme-cli, the
#   long-term disk-health side
# - HARDWARE-ACCELERATED VIDEO section: video stutter that
#   looks like CPU usually means vaapi isn't wired up
# - POWER MANAGEMENT section: the scaling governor and the
#   "why is my system slow on battery" answer
# - GAMING section: frame pacing, the per-process resource
#   knobs that benefit gamescope


GNOME TIPS (Workstation default)
--------------------------------

# fedora ships GNOME on Wayland by default. xorg session is removable
# but still available — install gnome-session-xsession to add it back
# to gdm's session picker. KDE Plasma is its own Edition (and Spin);
