WAYLAND — WHAT'S STILL DIFFERENT
--------------------------------

# fedora has been wayland-first for almost a decade — GNOME wayland
# default since F25 (2016), plasma wayland default since F36 (2022),
# F41 (2024) DROPPED the GNOME X11 session from the default install.
# you can put it back (`dnf install gnome-session-xsession`) but the
# direction is clear.
#
# the wayland transition is mostly complete for native apps and
# painfully incomplete for specific edge cases (automation, color
# pickers, some accessibility tooling). this section is what's still
# different.


# THE MENTAL MODEL — SECURITY OVER COMPATIBILITY

# X11 lets any app see / control any other app. that's the security
# bug, not a feature. wayland's design says: apps see only their own
# windows; system-wide capture / control requires explicit permission
# brokered by the compositor.
#
# every "thing that doesn't work the same on wayland" follows from
# that: screen recording (needs portal permission), global hotkeys
# (only the compositor can grab keys), clipboard managers (need to be
# part of the compositor), color pickers (need portal permission to
# read pixels), automation tools (need accessibility APIs or
# permission portals).
#
# the answer to "why doesn't X11 tool X work" is almost always: it
# would have to read or write things wayland doesn't let it. the
# answer is usually "use the portal-aware replacement".


# XWAYLAND — THE BACKWARDS COMPATIBILITY LAYER

# XWayland is an X11 server that runs as a wayland CLIENT. legacy X11
# apps connect to XWayland, which renders into a wayland surface. for
# most apps you don't notice — the app says "i'm an X app" and
# XWayland handles it.
#
# check what an app is using:
echo $XDG_SESSION_TYPE                         # wayland or x11
xlsclients -l                                  # X11 apps currently running

# you'll see things like Steam, older Electron apps, some JetBrains
# IDEs, OBS (in older configs), Wine apps — all via XWayland.
# performance is generally fine; HiDPI scaling is the most common
# pain point (XWayland apps may render blurry on fractional scales).

# the long tail: XWayland is here forever. it's not deprecated; both
# wayland and X11-via-XWayland will coexist indefinitely. don't worry
# about "porting" your X11 apps unless YOU maintain them.


# PIPEWIRE PORTALS — THE MAGIC THAT MAKES MODERN WAYLAND DESKTOPS WORK

# desktop portals (xdg-desktop-portal) are the system that brokers
# permission-needing operations: screen recording, file picker, screen
# sharing, GPU access, notifications. on wayland, screen capture
# specifically goes through PipeWire's video pipeline.
#
# verify the portal stack is running:
systemctl --user status xdg-desktop-portal
systemctl --user status xdg-desktop-portal-gnome     # GNOME backend
systemctl --user status xdg-desktop-portal-gtk       # GTK fallback
# (KDE users: substitute xdg-desktop-portal-kde)
#
# if these aren't running, browser screen sharing, OBS screen capture,
# flatpak file pickers, and GNOME's built-in screen recorder all fail
# silently or weirdly.


# SCREEN RECORDING

# native built-in (GNOME): Ctrl+Shift+Alt+R toggles recording. saved
# to ~/Videos/. limited but zero setup.
#
# OBS Studio — the canonical option. since OBS 28+ it speaks PipeWire
# portals natively. pick a "Screen Capture (PipeWire)" source; a
# portal dialog appears the first time asking which monitor / window.
sudo dnf install obs-studio
#
# gpu-screen-recorder — replay-buffer-focused option. low overhead.
# good for gaming highlights.
sudo dnf install gpu-screen-recorder
#
# wf-recorder — CLI for wlroots-based compositors (sway, hyprland).
# overkill for GNOME / Plasma which have built-in or OBS paths.


# SCREEN SHARING IN BROWSERS

# works on chrome / chromium / firefox via PipeWire portals. if it
# DOESN'T work, in order of probability:
#
# 1. xdg-desktop-portal services aren't running (see above)
# 2. browser is too old (chrome <90, firefox <94 don't support it)
# 3. flatpak browser missing PipeWire socket access — should be
#    automatic, but for the manually-paranoid:
flatpak override --user --filesystem=xdg-run/pipewire-0:ro \
    org.mozilla.firefox
# 4. you're on XWayland chromium (the Ozone flag — see ELECTRON below)


# MIGRATED TOOL NAMES — QUICK REFERENCE

#   X11 tool         wayland replacement
#   ────────────     ──────────────────────────────────────────────
#   xdotool          ydotool (kernel uinput; needs setup) or
#                    wtype (sway/wlroots only)
#   xrandr           wlr-randr (wlroots), kscreen-doctor (KDE),
#                    GNOME has no CLI — use Settings → Displays
#   xclip / xsel     wl-copy / wl-paste (from wl-clipboard)
#   xev              wev (wayland event viewer)
#   xprop            no direct replacement; window props aren't
#                    exposed to other clients
#   xkill            no replacement; killing other windows is not
#                    a wayland-native concept
#   xset s off       gsettings or busctl call to org.gnome.ScreenSaver
#   xrandr brightness  brightnessctl (kernel sysfs)
#   xdg-screensaver  busctl org.gnome.ScreenSaver (via dbus)


# YDOTOOL — XDOTOOL'S WAYLAND-COMPATIBLE COUSIN

# xdotool's input synthesis worked because X11 let any app inject
# events into any window. wayland doesn't. ydotool uses the kernel's
# uinput device instead — works regardless of display server.

sudo dnf install ydotool
sudo systemctl enable --now ydotoold
sudo usermod -aG input "$USER"                 # log out + back in

ydotool type "hello"
ydotool key 29:1 30:1 30:0 29:0                # Ctrl+A (keycodes)
ydotool mousemove --absolute 500 300


# WL-CLIPBOARD — XCLIP / XSEL'S WAYLAND COUSIN

sudo dnf install wl-clipboard

echo "hello" | wl-copy                         # copy to clipboard
wl-paste                                       # paste
wl-copy --primary < /etc/hostname              # primary selection
wl-paste --watch <command>                     # run command on clip changes


# GLOBAL HOTKEYS / CLIPBOARD MANAGERS / LAUNCHERS

# wayland doesn't let arbitrary clients grab system-wide keys. the
# COMPOSITOR has to grab them, then dispatch via D-Bus or a global
# shortcut framework. workarounds vary:
#
#   - GNOME: Settings → Keyboard → View and Customize Shortcuts.
#     add a custom shortcut → runs any command. enough for most
#     "launch my terminal on Ctrl+Alt+T".
#   - KDE: KGlobalAccel handles this natively (more flexible than
#     GNOME's UI).
#   - CLIPBOARD HISTORY: GNOME extension "gnome-clipboard-history" or
#     "Clipboard Indicator". for KDE, Klipper is built-in. for sway,
#     cliphist + wofi.
#   - LAUNCHERS: GNOME's Activities + search is the canonical answer;
#     rofi / wofi for wlroots compositors. ulauncher works on both
#     X11 and wayland (with caveats).


# WHAT STILL DOESN'T WORK CLEANLY

# 1. COLOR PICKERS that grab arbitrary pixels — XWayland-only. gcolor3
#    works via xdg-portal in some configs. for "what color is that"
#    quick checks: GNOME has "Color Picker" extension via xdg-portal.
#
# 2. SCREEN MAGNIFIERS / ACCESSIBILITY ZOOM — GNOME's built-in zoom
#    (Settings → Accessibility) works fine. third-party tools may not.
#
# 3. OBS SOURCE FILTERS that grab specific X11 windows — broken on
#    pure wayland. either capture the whole monitor or run OBS via
#    XWayland.
#
# 4. AUTOMATION TOOLS that watch arbitrary window state (AutoKey-style
#    text expanders, keyboard macro tools watching window class) —
#    limited. AT-SPI accessibility APIs are the modern path but
#    coverage is uneven.
#
# 5. SCREEN-SHARING VLC OUTPUT or specific app windows in older apps
#    that don't speak portals — fall back to XWayland or update the app.
#
# 6. SOME REMOTE-DESKTOP CLIENTS (TigerVNC viewer, x2go) — these
#    assume X11. GNOME's built-in "Remote Desktop" (Settings → Sharing)
#    speaks RDP and works fine over wayland.


# ELECTRON APPS + WAYLAND

# electron apps default to XWayland. they LOOK fine but you lose:
# fractional scaling, native window decoration, smooth touchpad
# gestures. force native wayland with the Ozone flag:
#
#   chromium / chrome / brave / vivaldi / opera:
#       --enable-features=UseOzonePlatform --ozone-platform=wayland
#   electron apps (vscode, slack, discord, signal, obsidian, etc.):
#       same flag works for most modern electron versions
#
# persistent for chrome via /etc/chromium-browser/default or a flag
# file. for vscode:
mkdir -p ~/.config
cat >> ~/.config/code-flags.conf <<'EOF'
--enable-features=UseOzonePlatform
--ozone-platform=wayland
EOF
#
# for flatpak electron apps, use Flatseal or `flatpak override`:
flatpak override --user --env=ELECTRON_OZONE_PLATFORM_HINT=auto \
    com.slack.Slack


