# THE TAKEAWAY

# wayland's "missing features" are mostly features that were security
# holes in X11. the wayland answer is portals + per-app permissions,
# brokered by the compositor. once your stack is current (recent
# fedora, recent browser, recent electron) and the portal services
# are running, the daily experience is indistinguishable from x11 —
# better, actually, on HiDPI and fractional scaling.
#
# the long tail of edge cases is real but shrinking each release. by
# F46-F48, this section should be much shorter.


DISPLAYS — MULTI-MONITOR, HiDPI, FRACTIONAL SCALING
---------------------------------------------------

# the display-side complement to WAYLAND. how to drive 1-N
# monitors with mixed DPI on fedora 44 without misery.


# THE DISPLAY STACK — WHO DOES WHAT

# from kernel up:
#
#   KMS / DRM           — the kernel driver for the GPU. mode
#                         setting, EDID parsing, framebuffer
#                         management. /sys/class/drm/...
#   mesa / vulkan       — userspace graphics stack; renders to
#                         GPU buffers.
#   mutter              — gnome's wayland compositor. owns
#                         arrangement, scaling, refresh, VRR,
#                         HDR plumbing. eats dbus + gsettings.
#   wayland clients     — apps that draw natively (firefox,
#                         gnome apps, modern electron).
#   XWayland            — translation layer for X11 apps under
#                         a wayland compositor; source of most
#                         scaling weirdness.

# when something's wrong, ask: did the kernel see the panel
# (KMS / EDID)? does mutter list it? does the app draw native
# or through XWayland? — that's most of the diagnosis.


# THE 95% PATH — GNOME SETTINGS → DISPLAYS

# this UI is now genuinely good. it handles:
#   - arrangement (drag and drop)
#   - per-monitor scale (100% → 200%, with fractional in between)
#   - refresh rate (per-monitor, including modes the panel reports)
#   - rotation (portrait monitors)
#   - "primary display" (where the top bar lives)
#   - mirror vs join
#   - night light schedule
#
# for one or two monitors, this is the whole story. drop to the
# CLI only when you need automation or you hit something weird.


# FRACTIONAL SCALING IN FEDORA 44

# fractional scaling (125% / 150% / 175%) has been default-on in
# GNOME on wayland since fedora 40. on F44 it's just there in
# the Scale picker in Settings → Displays.

# if you're on a downgraded gnome or you want to confirm the
# experimental flag is on (legacy systems):
gsettings get org.gnome.mutter experimental-features
# should include 'scale-monitor-framebuffer'. if not:
gsettings set org.gnome.mutter experimental-features \
    "['scale-monitor-framebuffer']"

# mixed-DPI multi-monitor "just works" on wayland: each output
# gets its own scale. drag a window across monitors and it
# resizes correctly — that's mutter doing per-output rendering,
# which X11 fundamentally couldn't.


# XWAYLAND AND THE BLURRY-LEGACY-APP PROBLEM

# the most common "ugh" — an old X11 app (electron 12, jetbrains
# tools on certain JDKs, legacy java swing apps, older steam UI)
# looks fuzzy under fractional scaling because XWayland scales
# the X11 buffer up before display.

# inventory: what's actually running on XWayland vs wayland-native?
xlsclients                          # wayland session lists X11 clients
# or per-app: about:support in firefox shows "Window Protocol".

# the modern workarounds, in order of preference:

# 1. switch the app to a wayland-native build. firefox, chromium,
#    electron 22+, jetbrains 2024.1+, java 21+ all have wayland.
#    set hints per-app:
export MOZ_ENABLE_WAYLAND=1                          # firefox/thunderbird
export ELECTRON_OZONE_PLATFORM_HINT=wayland          # vscode, slack, etc.
export _JAVA_AWT_WM_NONREPARENTING=1                 # old swing apps
# (modern jetbrains: set in idea.properties)

# 2. set GDK_SCALE for integer scaling on still-X11 GTK apps:
export GDK_SCALE=2 GDK_DPI_SCALE=0.5
# (this gives 200% via X11; clean but loses fractional steps.)

# 3. force Qt apps to obey wayland-scale:
export QT_QPA_PLATFORM="wayland;xcb"                 # try wayland, fall back
export QT_AUTO_SCREEN_SCALE_FACTOR=1

# 4. enable mutter's xwayland fractional scaling (F40+):
gsettings set org.gnome.mutter experimental-features \
    "['scale-monitor-framebuffer','xwayland-native-scaling']"
# this makes XWayland speak fractional scale instead of crude
# integer-then-downscale. the F44 default keeps it OFF; turn it
# on if you have a workflow that's heavy in X11 apps. some apps
# (cad, old game launchers) can misbehave with it on.


# HiDPI FONT RENDERING

# on a 4K 27" panel at 200% scale, fonts look great by default.
# the tuning knobs that matter when they don't:

# subpixel order, hinting, antialiasing — these are fontconfig:
mkdir -p ~/.config/fontconfig
cat > ~/.config/fontconfig/fonts.conf <<'EOF'
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!DOCTYPE fontconfig SYSTEM "fonts.dtd">
<fontconfig>
  <match target="font">
    <edit name="antialias" mode="assign"><bool>true</bool></edit>
    <edit name="hinting" mode="assign"><bool>true</bool></edit>
    <edit name="hintstyle" mode="assign"><const>hintslight</const></edit>
    <edit name="rgba" mode="assign"><const>rgb</const></edit>
    <edit name="lcdfilter" mode="assign"><const>lcddefault</const></edit>
  </match>
</fontconfig>
EOF
fc-cache -fv

# verify what a specific font is doing:
fc-match 'JetBrains Mono'
fc-match -s 'monospace' | head -5

# the LOCALE / FONTS / INPUT METHODS section covers font
# installation in more depth.


# COLOR MANAGEMENT — colord + ICC

# fedora ships colord and gnome-color-manager out of the box.
# Settings → Color shows every output, lets you assign an ICC
# profile per display, and runs nightly color sync.

# install a calibration utility:
sudo dnf install displaycal argyllcms
# argyllcms supports common hardware: X-Rite/Calibrite i1Display
# Pro, ColorMunki, DataColor SpyderX. plug in, run displaycal,
# generate a .icc, assign in Settings → Color → "Add Profile".

# command-line color tooling:
colormgr get-devices                                 # what colord knows
colormgr device-set-profile <DEVICE> <PROFILE>
colormgr import-profile ~/Downloads/sRGB-v4.icc

# the per-app color side (firefox color management, kdenlive
# project color spaces, krita) is out of scope here.


# NIGHT LIGHT / BLUE-LIGHT FILTER

# GNOME's built-in: Settings → Displays → Night Light.
# schedule (sunset/sunrise via geoclue, or manual hours) and
