# moved, some commercial tools):

# at login: gear icon → "GNOME on Xorg" before signing in.
# if "GNOME on Xorg" is missing on F44, install:
sudo dnf install gnome-session-xsession

# inside an Xorg session, xrandr is fully functional and the
# tooling generations of guides assume "just works."

# WAYLAND section covers when XWayland is enough vs when you
# actually need a full Xorg session.


# MULTI-GPU LAPTOPS — PRIME RENDER OFFLOAD

# many laptops have an integrated iGPU plus a discrete dGPU
# (Intel + NVIDIA, AMD + AMD, etc.). the desktop runs on the
# iGPU for battery; you offload specific apps to the dGPU.

# AMD / Intel (mesa-driven):
DRI_PRIME=1 glxinfo | grep "OpenGL renderer"          # which GPU rendered?
DRI_PRIME=1 myapp                                     # run on the dGPU

# NVIDIA hybrid (PRIME render offload):
__NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia myapp
# steam → game launch options:
#   __NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia %command%
# verify:
nvidia-smi                                            # processes running on dGPU

# the NVIDIA section covers driver install + the akmod path.
# DKMS-style packaging is rare for nvidia on fedora.


# EXTERNAL DISPLAY — USB-C, THUNDERBOLT, DP-MST

# USB-C and Thunderbolt 3/4 carry DisplayPort. for thunderbolt
# specifically, fedora gates new devices behind `bolt` (the
# thunderbolt authorization daemon) — otherwise rogue devices
# could DMA-attack you.

# inspect connected thunderbolt devices:
boltctl list
boltctl authorize <UUID>                              # one-shot
boltctl enroll <UUID> --policy auto                   # remember it
# GNOME Settings → Privacy → Thunderbolt is the GUI.

# DisplayPort MST (multi-stream — one DP cable carrying multiple
# monitors via a hub): supported by KMS; mutter shows the
# individual outputs after the kernel enumerates them. some
# hubs misreport EDID; the recipe is below.


# TROUBLESHOOTING RECIPES

# 1. EXTERNAL MONITOR NOT DETECTED
sudo dmesg | grep -iE 'drm|edid' | tail -40
ls /sys/class/drm/                                     # connected outputs
cat /sys/class/drm/card1-DP-1/status                  # "connected" / "disconnected"
cat /sys/class/drm/card1-DP-1/edid | edid-decode      # what the panel reports
# check the cable / dongle if the kernel doesn't see "connected."

# 2. SCALING LOOKS BLURRY ON ONE APP
xlsclients                                            # is the app X11?
# if yes: enable xwayland-native-scaling (above) OR find a
# wayland-native build. if no, check the app's HiDPI flag
# (electron --enable-features=UseOzonePlatform).

# 3. DISPLAY DOESN'T WAKE FROM SLEEP
# common cause: dGPU suspend state. tail kernel:
sudo journalctl -k -b -1 | grep -iE 'drm|gpu' | tail -50
# common fix on intel:
#   kernel cmdline: i915.enable_psr=0
# common fix on amd:
#   kernel cmdline: amdgpu.dpm=0  (rare, last resort)
# common fix on nvidia hybrid:
#   make sure nvidia-suspend.service / nvidia-resume.service
#   are enabled (akmod package installs them).
# see KERNEL CMDLINE for how to add args; POWER MANAGEMENT for
# the sleep-state knobs.

# 4. MONITOR FORCES A WRONG REFRESH RATE / RESOLUTION
# usually bad EDID. tell the kernel to use a custom EDID blob:
sudo cp my.edid /lib/firmware/edid/dp1-edid.bin
# kernel cmdline:
#   drm.edid_firmware=DP-1:edid/dp1-edid.bin
# verify:
cat /sys/class/drm/card1-DP-1/edid | edid-decode
sudo dracut --force                                    # rebuild initramfs

# 5. FRACTIONAL SCALING BROKE AFTER GNOME UPDATE
gsettings reset org.gnome.mutter experimental-features
# then reset to the F44 default:
gsettings set org.gnome.mutter experimental-features \
    "['scale-monitor-framebuffer']"


# HONEST TRADEOFFS

# wayland on fedora 44 handles mixed-DPI multi-monitor better
# than any other linux setup, full stop. the cost is that any
# remaining X11 app pays an XWayland scaling penalty. for most
# users in 2026, this is fine — the X11 long tail is short.

# fractional scaling looks good but bumps GPU usage on weak
# integrated graphics (battery cost on older laptops). on a
# fanless / older machine, integer scaling (100% or 200%) is
# noticeably easier on the GPU.

# HDR and VRR are genuinely useful but still in active dev.
# turn them on if you want them, but don't be surprised when
# behavior changes across two gnome point releases.

# bolt's "ask before trusting" prompt on thunderbolt looks
# annoying. it's not — DMA attacks via thunderbolt are real.
# enroll trusted dock/peripherals with `--policy auto`, leave
# the prompt on for everything else.


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   set scale / refresh / arrangement       → Settings → Displays
#   confirm fractional scaling is on        → gsettings get org.gnome.mutter experimental-features
#   turn on xwayland fractional scale       → add 'xwayland-native-scaling' to that key
#   turn on HDR (experimental)              → add 'hdr'
#   turn on VRR                             → add 'variable-refresh-rate'
#   list outputs from cli                   → gnome-randr / wlr-randr / xrandr
#   what protocol is this app using?        → xlsclients (anything listed = X11)
#   external monitor not detected           → dmesg | grep edid; check cable
#   thunderbolt dock not working            → boltctl list / authorize
#   blurry app                              → XWayland; switch to native build
#   sleep / wake regression                 → journalctl -k -b -1 | grep gpu
#   color calibration                       → Settings → Color + displaycal
#   automation across dock/undock           → kanshi (wlroots) / gnome-randr (gnome)


