LOCALE / FONTS / INPUT METHODS
------------------------------

# fedora ships sensible defaults for english-speaking western locales.
# for everyone else — CJK input, RTL languages, non-latin glyphs in
# the terminal, mixed-script document editing — there's a small set
# of tools that bring the experience up to parity.


# LOCALE + TIMEZONE

# locale = language + region + encoding. set system-wide:
localectl                                      # current state
localectl list-locales | grep ja               # available japanese
sudo localectl set-locale LANG=ja_JP.UTF-8
sudo localectl set-locale LC_TIME=en_US.UTF-8  # split: japanese
                                                # interface but
                                                # english dates

# per-user (overrides system):
echo 'LANG=ja_JP.UTF-8' > ~/.config/locale.conf
echo 'LC_ALL=ja_JP.UTF-8' >> ~/.config/locale.conf

# keyboard layout:
localectl list-keymaps | grep us
sudo localectl set-keymap us

# X11 / wayland keyboard layout (separate from console):
localectl set-x11-keymap us pc105 altgr-intl
# or via GNOME: Settings → Keyboard → Input Sources

# timezone (covered in TIME / NTP, repeated for completeness):
timedatectl list-timezones | grep Tokyo
sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Tokyo


# INPUT METHODS — FCITX5 vs IBUS

# fedora ships IBUS as the default input-method framework. it covers
# CJK, indic scripts, and emoji adequately for most users.
#
# FCITX5 is the modern community-preferred alternative — better
# performance, more flexible configuration, smoother experience for
# heavy CJK typists.

# IBUS (default; no install needed):
ibus-setup                                     # GUI to add input methods
# add input methods via GNOME: Settings → Keyboard → Input Sources →
# Add an Input Source → pick from "Japanese (Mozc)" / "Chinese
