# HINTING + ANTIALIASING

# the defaults are good on modern displays. when they're not:
#
#   - HINTING: "slight" is the modern recommended default.
#     "full" was useful on low-res displays; on hidpi, set "slight"
#     or "none" for cleaner glyph shapes.
#   - ANTIALIASING: rgba for sub-pixel rendering on LCDs; greyscale
#     for hidpi (sub-pixel breaks down past ~150 dpi).
#
# GNOME tweaks: Tweaks → Fonts → "Hinting" and "Antialiasing" sliders.
# system-wide config (rarely needed):
mkdir -p ~/.config/fontconfig
cat > ~/.config/fontconfig/conf.d/10-hinting.conf <<'EOF'
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!DOCTYPE fontconfig SYSTEM "fonts.dtd">
<fontconfig>
  <match target="font">
    <edit name="hinting" mode="assign"><bool>true</bool></edit>
    <edit name="hintstyle" mode="assign"><const>hintslight</const></edit>
    <edit name="antialias" mode="assign"><bool>true</bool></edit>
    <edit name="rgba" mode="assign"><const>rgb</const></edit>
  </match>
</fontconfig>
EOF
fc-cache -fv


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. "JAPANESE CHARACTERS LOOK SLIGHTLY OFF." you're rendering them
#    in the chinese font. fix the fontconfig preference (above).
#
# 2. INPUT METHOD WORKS IN GNOME APPS BUT NOT IN VSCODE / ELECTRON.
#    electron apps need the environment variables set (the
#    environment.d/im.conf recipe above) AND they need to be relaunched
#    after the change. some need additional flags
#    (--enable-features=UseOzonePlatform for native wayland +
#    fcitx5).
#
# 3. EMOJI RENDER AS MONOCHROME / WRONG. you have a monochrome emoji
#    font higher in the cascade than color emoji. install
#    `google-noto-color-emoji-fonts` and make sure it's preferred for
#    emoji glyphs.
#
# 4. CONSOLE / TTY DOESN'T SHOW CJK. the linux console only renders
#    glyphs from a small bitmap font. CJK in the TTY is essentially
#    not supported. use a terminal emulator instead.
#
# 5. RTL LANGUAGES (arabic, hebrew). most apps render correctly. CLI
#    apps in terminals depend on the terminal — recent ghostty,
#    ptyxis, alacritty handle bidi reasonably. older terminals
#    (gnome-terminal pre-VTE-bidi-merge) don't.
#
# 6. KEYBOARD INDICATOR DOESN'T SHOW IN GNOME TOPBAR. add input
#    source via Settings → Keyboard → Input Sources. the indicator
#    appears in the panel once 2+ sources are configured.


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   "set system locale"                  → sudo localectl set-locale
#   "set user-only locale"               → ~/.config/locale.conf
#   "switch to fcitx5"                   → ~/.config/environment.d/im.conf
#   "add CJK input"                      → ibus / fcitx5 + mozc/pinyin/hangul
#   "emoji picker"                       → Ctrl+. (GNOME builtin)
#   "what font renders this language"    → fc-match :lang=<code>
#   "fix wrong CJK font"                 → fontconfig prefer rule
#   "rebuild font cache"                 → fc-cache -fv


