#   - desktop or "couch mode" (gamescope session, like steam deck)
#
# install via rebase from silverblue or fresh install. covered in
# SILVERBLUE section.
#
# when to pick bazzite:
#   - you want a steamOS-style experience on your hardware
#   - you don't want to configure the gaming stack manually
#   - you accept the immutable model (most casual gaming workflows fit)
#
# when to stay on workstation:
#   - you want full mutable system control
#   - you do non-gaming work that doesn't fit the atomic model
#   - you're integrating with existing development workflows


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. GAME CRASHES ON LAUNCH. order of operations:
#    a. update Proton (Steam restart, settings → in-game)
#    b. try GE-Proton (via ProtonUp-Qt)
#    c. check protondb.com for known workaround
#    d. delete shader cache: ~/.steam/steam/steamapps/shadercache/
#
# 2. STEAM STORE NOT LOADING / WEBVIEW BROKEN. delete the cache:
rm -rf ~/.steam/steam/appcache ~/.steam/steam/htmlcache
#
# 3. CONTROLLER NOT DETECTED. check steam-devices is installed and
#    udev rules loaded:
sudo udevadm control --reload-rules && sudo udevadm trigger
#    log out + back in if you just installed steam-devices.
#
# 4. FSR / DLSS NOT AVAILABLE. game-specific. FSR 2.x and FSR 3 work
#    on most cards. DLSS requires nvidia + proton's vulkan layer for
#    the game.
#
# 5. SAVE GAME CLOUD SYNC NOT WORKING. usually a permissions issue
#    in the Proton prefix. delete ~/.steam/steam/userdata/<id>/
#    cloud and let Steam re-sync.
#
# 6. ANTI-CHEAT BLOCKS GAME EVEN THOUGH PROTONDB SAYS WORKS. the
#    game may need EAC's runtime files explicitly enabled — Steam →
#    game → Properties → Compatibility → toggle. or the game's
#    anti-cheat backend may have changed since the protondb report.
#
# 7. GAME RUNNING ON THE WRONG GPU (hybrid laptop). force
#    nvidia render-offload (see NVIDIA section):
#    Steam launch options:
#        DRI_PRIME=1 %command%       # AMD/intel discrete
#        __NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia %command%
#
# 8. AUDIO CRACKLE / STUTTER. PipeWire quantum may be too tight.
#    raise to 1024 in steam launch options:
#        PIPEWIRE_QUANTUM=1024/48000 %command%
#    or persistent (see AUDIO section).


# DECISION MATRIX

#   "I want to play steam games"               → steam + proton (default)
#   "this game has minor proton issues"        → GE-Proton via ProtonUp-Qt
#   "non-steam: epic / GOG / amazon"           → Heroic
#   "non-steam: battle.net / old wine games"   → Lutris
#   "isolate wine prefixes per game"           → Bottles
#   "want FPS overlay"                         → MangoHud
#   "auto-tune system on game launch"          → gamemode + gamemoderun
#   "post-process shaders / sharpening"        → vkBasalt
#   "stream to phone or other device"          → Sunshine + Moonlight
#   "steamOS-style preconfigured experience"   → Bazzite (rebase)
#   "does this game work on linux?"            → protondb.com


RPM PACKAGING — BUILDING YOUR OWN
---------------------------------

# the primer covers using `dnf` and `rpm` deeply. this section is the
# OTHER side: how to BUILD an RPM. you'll do this when:
#   - you maintain an in-house tool you want to deploy via dnf
#   - upstream doesn't ship an RPM and you want one
#   - you're packaging something for fedora itself (copr → koji →
#     official repos — see the CONTRIBUTOR PIPELINE stub below)
#   - you're learning packaging mechanics before joining the
#     fedora packaging team


# THE MENTAL MODEL

# an RPM is built from a .spec file + source tarball(s). the .spec
# is a declarative recipe with build steps, file lists, and metadata.
# rpmbuild runs the steps in a sandbox and produces:
#   - a SRPM (source RPM): your sources + spec, distributable as a
#     buildable archive
#   - one or more binary RPMs: the actual installable packages
#
# the build sandbox uses a standard directory layout:
#
#   ~/rpmbuild/SOURCES   — input tarballs, patches, supporting files
#   ~/rpmbuild/SPECS     — your .spec files
#   ~/rpmbuild/BUILD     — extracted sources, where the build happens
#   ~/rpmbuild/BUILDROOT — the fake filesystem root used for install
#   ~/rpmbuild/RPMS      — finished binary RPMs (per arch)
#   ~/rpmbuild/SRPMS     — finished source RPMs


# SETUP

sudo dnf install \
    rpm-build rpmdevtools rpmlint mock \
    redhat-rpm-config gcc make

# create the standard directory layout:
rpmdev-setuptree                                # creates ~/rpmbuild/...

# verify the layout:
ls -la ~/rpmbuild/                              # SOURCES SPECS BUILD ...

# .rpmmacros — per-user defaults (rpmdev-setuptree creates a minimal one):
cat ~/.rpmmacros
# common addition for your maintainer identity:
echo '%packager Your Name <you@example.com>' >> ~/.rpmmacros


# A MINIMAL WORKED EXAMPLE — "hello" PACKAGE

# 1. SOURCE TARBALL. drop the upstream tarball in SOURCES/:
cd ~/rpmbuild/SOURCES
wget https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/hello/hello-2.12.1.tar.gz

# 2. SPEC FILE. minimal but complete:
cat > ~/rpmbuild/SPECS/hello.spec <<'EOF'
Name:           hello
Version:        2.12.1
Release:        1%{?dist}
Summary:        GNU Hello — a friendly greeting program
License:        GPL-3.0-or-later
URL:            https://www.gnu.org/software/hello/
Source0:        https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/hello/%{name}-%{version}.tar.gz

BuildRequires:  gcc, make, gettext

%description
GNU Hello is a program that prints "Hello, world!" to the screen.
It's the canonical example of a GNU package — useful as a packaging
exercise more than as a tool.

%prep
%autosetup

%build
%configure
%make_build

%install
%make_install
%find_lang %{name}

%files -f %{name}.lang
%license COPYING
%doc README NEWS
%{_bindir}/hello
%{_mandir}/man1/hello.1*
%{_infodir}/hello.info*

%changelog
* Tue Jun 17 2026 Your Name <you@example.com> - 2.12.1-1
- Initial RPM packaging
EOF

# 3. BUILD. -ba = build all (both SRPM and binary RPM):
rpmbuild -ba ~/rpmbuild/SPECS/hello.spec

# OUTPUT:
#   ~/rpmbuild/SRPMS/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.src.rpm
#   ~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.x86_64.rpm
#   ~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/hello-debuginfo-...rpm
#   ~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/hello-debugsource-...rpm

# 4. INSPECT:
rpm -qpi ~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.x86_64.rpm
rpm -qpl ~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.x86_64.rpm

# 5. INSTALL + RUN:
sudo dnf install ~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.x86_64.rpm
hello


# SPEC FILE TAGS — THE COMMON ONES

# HEADER (required + recommended):
#   Name:            package name (lowercase, no spaces)
#   Version:         upstream version
#   Release:         packaging revision (start at 1; bump on respin).
#                    %{?dist} appends the disttag (.fc44, .el9, etc.)
#   Summary:         single-line description (< 80 chars)
#   License:         SPDX identifier (e.g. GPL-3.0-or-later, MIT, Apache-2.0)
#   URL:             upstream project URL
#   Source0:         primary source tarball (URL form is recommended)
#   Source1+:        additional source files
#   Patch0+:         patches to apply during %prep
#
# DEPENDENCIES:
#   BuildRequires:   what you need TO BUILD this package
#   Requires:        what the installed package needs at RUN time
#   Recommends:      soft dep (installs unless --no-recommends)
#   Suggests:        very soft dep (informational)
#   Provides:        virtual capabilities this package satisfies
#   Conflicts:       packages this one cannot coexist with
#   Obsoletes:       packages this one replaces

# SECTIONS (in order):
#   %prep            extract sources, apply patches. usually:
#                    %autosetup (handles tarball + patches together)
#   %build           compile. usually %configure + %make_build for
#                    autotools; %cmake / %meson_build for those
#   %install         install into %{buildroot}. usually %make_install
#                    or %meson_install
#   %check           run upstream tests (optional but recommended)
#   %files           list of installed files (the binary package
#                    contents). wildcards OK.
#   %changelog       chronological log; newest first


# COMMON MACROS

#   %{name}        — Name: value (e.g. "hello")
#   %{version}     — Version: value
#   %{release}     — Release: value
#   %{?dist}       — disttag (.fc44 on fedora 44, .el9 on RHEL 9)
#   %{_bindir}     — /usr/bin
#   %{_sbindir}    — /usr/sbin
#   %{_libdir}     — /usr/lib64 (or /usr/lib on 32-bit)
#   %{_datadir}    — /usr/share
#   %{_sysconfdir} — /etc
#   %{_mandir}     — /usr/share/man
#   %{_docdir}     — /usr/share/doc
#   %{_infodir}    — /usr/share/info
#   %{_unitdir}    — /usr/lib/systemd/system
#   %{_userunitdir}— /usr/lib/systemd/user
#   %{buildroot}   — the fake root for %install (~/rpmbuild/BUILDROOT/...)
#   %{_arch}       — x86_64, aarch64, etc.

# list every defined macro:
rpm --showrc | less


# RPMBUILD COMMAND VARIANTS

rpmbuild -ba foo.spec          # build all (SRPM + binary)
rpmbuild -bb foo.spec          # binary only
rpmbuild -bs foo.spec          # SRPM only
rpmbuild -bp foo.spec          # %prep only (debug source extraction)
rpmbuild -bc foo.spec          # %prep + %build
rpmbuild -bi foo.spec          # %prep + %build + %install
rpmbuild -bl foo.spec          # lint check, no actual build
rpmbuild --rebuild foo.src.rpm # rebuild from a SRPM


# RPMLINT — STATIC ANALYSIS FOR YOUR PACKAGE

rpmlint ~/rpmbuild/SPECS/hello.spec
rpmlint ~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.x86_64.rpm
rpmlint -i <pkg>                                # include explanations

# common rpmlint warnings worth fixing:
#   - W: spelling-error          — typo in summary / description
#   - W: no-version-in-last-changelog
#   - E: hardcoded-library-path  — using /usr/lib instead of %{_libdir}
#   - W: incorrect-fsf-address    — old GPL boilerplate
#   - W: invalid-license          — License: field isn't an SPDX id


# GPG SIGNING

# generate (or use an existing) GPG key:
gpg --full-generate-key                         # interactive

# tell rpm about your key fingerprint:
echo '%_signature gpg' >> ~/.rpmmacros
echo '%_gpg_name your-key-id' >> ~/.rpmmacros

# sign:
rpmsign --addsign ~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.x86_64.rpm
rpm --checksig ~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.x86_64.rpm


# THE DISTTAG (%{?dist})

# %{?dist} expands to ".fc44" on fedora 44, ".el9" on RHEL 9, ".eln"
# on Fedora ELN, etc. lets the same spec produce builds tagged for
# different targets:
#
#   hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.x86_64.rpm     # built on fedora 44
#   hello-2.12.1-1.fc45.x86_64.rpm     # built on fedora 45
#
# this is why you rarely need different specs per release.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. "FILES LISTED TWICE." you wildcarded /usr/share/% AND listed a
#    specific file inside it. pick one approach per directory.
#
# 2. "INSTALLED (BUT UNPACKAGED) FILES." %install produced files that
#    %files doesn't claim. either add them to %files or remove them
#    in %install. RPM refuses to ship a build with orphaned files.
#
# 3. "UNPACKAGED INSTALL DIRECTORY." you created an empty subdir in
#    %install that nothing else owns. add `%dir /path` to %files
#    to claim the directory itself.
#
# 4. "DEBUGINFO IS BROKEN." you stripped the binary in %install
#    yourself. don't — fedora's `redhat-rpm-config` automatically
#    extracts debuginfo into the -debuginfo subpackage. skip
#    `strip` commands.
#
# 5. "FILE CONFLICTS BETWEEN PACKAGES" on install. you tried to ship
#    a file already owned by another package. either rename, or use
#    `Conflicts:` to declare incompatibility, or work around with an
#    alternatives mechanism.
#
# 6. CHANGELOG DATE FORMAT. must be: `* DAY MMM DD YYYY Name <email>
#    - VERSION-RELEASE`. exact format. typos = build failure.
#
# 7. SOURCE0 IS A URL BUT YOU PUT THE TARBALL IN SOURCES/. fine.
#    `spectool -g foo.spec` will FETCH source URLs automatically if
#    you want to automate that step:
spectool -g -R ~/rpmbuild/SPECS/foo.spec


# WORKING WITH SRPMS (source RPMs)

# unpack a SRPM to inspect it:
mkdir /tmp/srpm-unpack && cd /tmp/srpm-unpack
rpm2cpio /path/to/foo-1.0-1.fc44.src.rpm | cpio -idmv
# gives you the spec + sources back.

# rebuild someone else's SRPM:
rpmbuild --rebuild foo-1.0-1.fc44.src.rpm

# install a SRPM into your own rpmbuild tree (modify + rebuild):
rpm -ivh foo-1.0-1.fc44.src.rpm
ls ~/rpmbuild/SOURCES/ ~/rpmbuild/SPECS/


# QUICK REFERENCE

#   "new package from scratch"              → rpmdev-newspec foo
#   "build a binary RPM"                    → rpmbuild -bb foo.spec
#   "check spec quality"                    → rpmlint foo.spec
#   "produce a SRPM for distribution"       → rpmbuild -bs foo.spec
#   "rebuild someone's SRPM"                → rpmbuild --rebuild foo.src.rpm
#   "fetch upstream sources from URL"       → spectool -g -R foo.spec
#   "sign a finished RPM"                   → rpmsign --addsign foo.rpm
#   "see what macros exist"                 → rpm --showrc


CONTRIBUTOR PIPELINE (MOCK / FEDPKG / KOJI / COPR)
--------------------------------------------------

# the RPM PACKAGING section covered building a working RPM on your
# machine. this section covers what comes after — sharing it (COPR),
# verifying it builds cleanly elsewhere (mock), and getting it INTO
# fedora as an official package (fedpkg → koji → bodhi).


# THE PIPELINE — FROM LOCAL SPEC TO OFFICIAL FEDORA

#   rpmbuild  →  mock  →  COPR        →  fedpkg / dist-git  →  koji  →  bodhi
#   (covered) (chroot) (personal repo)  (maintainer workflow)  (build)  (updates)
#
# you don't have to go through all of these. typical exits:
#   - "i just want clean builds locally"           → mock + done
#   - "i want others to dnf install this"          → COPR + done
#   - "i want this to become an official fedora    → full pipeline,
#      package i co-maintain"                       this section


# MOCK — CLEAN-CHROOT BUILDS

# rpmbuild builds in YOUR environment. mock builds in a clean chroot
# matching a specific fedora / RHEL / EPEL target. it catches:
#   - missing BuildRequires (you had a dep installed; the chroot
#     doesn't)
#   - "works on F44, breaks on F45" issues
#   - file ownership / permissions surprises
# you should always mock-build before submitting an RPM anywhere.

sudo dnf install mock
sudo usermod -aG mock "$USER"                     # log out + back in

# list available targets:
ls /etc/mock/*.cfg | head -20                     # fedora-44-x86_64,
                                                  # rhel+epel-9-x86_64, etc.

# build from a SRPM (most common):
mock -r fedora-44-x86_64 --rebuild ~/rpmbuild/SRPMS/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.src.rpm

# build from a spec directly:
mock -r fedora-44-x86_64 --buildsrpm \
    --spec=~/rpmbuild/SPECS/hello.spec \
    --sources=~/rpmbuild/SOURCES/

# output lands in:
#   /var/lib/mock/<target>/result/<package>-...rpm

# common mock commands:
mock -r fedora-44-x86_64 --shell                  # interactive chroot
mock -r fedora-44-x86_64 --clean                  # reset the chroot
mock -r fedora-44-x86_64 --scrub=all              # nuclear: wipe target

# build against MULTIPLE targets in one go:
for t in fedora-44-x86_64 fedora-45-x86_64 rhel+epel-9-x86_64; do
    mock -r "$t" --rebuild foo.src.rpm
done


# PERSONAL COPR — SHARE WITHOUT BECOMING A MAINTAINER

# COPR (Cool Other Package Repos — yes, really) is fedora's
# user-controlled build service. you upload SRPMs, COPR builds them
# for the targets you select, gives you a dnf-installable repo URL.
# zero gatekeeping; no review.
#
# good for:
#   - your own tools you want on multiple machines
#   - betas of upstream projects that aren't in fedora yet
#   - hosting a customized build of an existing fedora package
#   - prototyping before going through formal review

sudo dnf install copr-cli

# auth — go to copr.fedoraproject.org, log in with FAS account, copy
# the API token from "API" tab into ~/.config/copr.

# create a project:
copr-cli create my-tools \
    --chroot fedora-44-x86_64 \
    --chroot fedora-45-x86_64 \
    --description "My personal tools" \
    --instructions "dnf copr enable user/my-tools && dnf install hello"

# build a SRPM:
copr-cli build my-tools ~/rpmbuild/SRPMS/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.src.rpm

# watch the build:
copr-cli watch-build <build-id>

# users install with:
#   sudo dnf copr enable youruser/my-tools
#   sudo dnf install hello


# FEDORA ACCOUNT SYSTEM (FAS) — THE PREREQUISITE

# before fedpkg / official packaging you need a FAS account:
#   https://accounts.fedoraproject.org/
# - register, agree to the CLA / FPCA license
# - sign up for the @packager group (gated by sponsor)
# - generate an SSH key and add it to your account
# - configure krb5 for authenticated requests (kinit your-fas@FEDORAPROJECT.ORG)


# FEDPKG — THE MAINTAINER CLI

sudo dnf install fedpkg

# clone an existing package (the dist-git URL pattern):
fedpkg clone hello                              # anonymous (read-only)
fedpkg clone --anonymous hello                  # explicit anonymous
# OR (maintainer, needs FAS access):
fedpkg clone -B hello                           # all branches

cd hello/

# dist-git layout:
#   hello.spec                          (the spec file)
#   sources                             (sha512sums of source tarballs)
#   .gitignore                          (excludes the actual tarballs)
#
# fedpkg uses LOOKASIDE CACHE for source tarballs — actual sources live
# in a separate object store, not in git. git holds the spec + patches.

# common workflow:
fedpkg sources                                  # download tarballs
                                                # from the lookaside
fedpkg new-sources foo-1.2.tar.gz               # upload new tarball
fedpkg srpm                                     # build a SRPM locally
fedpkg local                                    # build binary RPM locally
fedpkg mockbuild                                # mock-build for the
                                                # current branch's target
fedpkg push                                     # push spec changes
fedpkg build                                    # submit a koji build
fedpkg update                                   # submit to bodhi

# switching branches (per fedora release):
fedpkg switch-branch f44                        # spec for fedora 44
fedpkg switch-branch f45                        # spec for fedora 45
fedpkg switch-branch rawhide                    # rolling development


# KOJI — THE OFFICIAL BUILD SYSTEM

# koji is fedora's build farm. fedpkg build submits a job there;
# koji rebuilds your spec in a sealed chroot, signs the result, and
# stores it in the fedora repos.

# watch a build:
koji watch-task <task-id>
koji buildinfo <NVR>                            # done build info

# scratch builds (test, don't publish):
koji build --scratch f44-candidate \
    ~/rpmbuild/SRPMS/hello-2.12.1-1.fc44.src.rpm

# browse builds:
#   https://koji.fedoraproject.org/koji/


# BODHI — THE UPDATES SYSTEM

# a successful koji build doesn't immediately reach users. you
# submit it through bodhi, which:
#   - moves it to updates-testing
#   - collects karma (+/- feedback) from testers
#   - promotes to updates-stable after 7 days OR 3 positive karma
#   - posts security / bug fix / enhancement classification

sudo dnf install bodhi-client

# submit a build (after fedpkg build succeeded):
bodhi updates new \
    --type bugfix \
    --notes "Fix segfault in --version" \
    --bugs 12345 \
    hello-2.12.1-1.fc44

# users can opt into updates-testing:
sudo dnf update --enablerepo=updates-testing <pkg>

# leave karma:
bodhi updates request <update-id> testing       # request testing
bodhi updates comment "Works for me, +1" --karma 1 <update-id>


# THE NEW-PACKAGE REVIEW PROCESS

# when you've packaged something that isn't yet IN fedora, you go
# through the package review process:
#
# 1. file a Package Review bug at bugzilla.redhat.com:
#       component: Package Review
#       title: "Review Request: hello — GNU Hello"
#       attach the SRPM URL (typically from COPR) and the spec URL
# 2. find a REVIEWER (community member; volunteer)
# 3. iterate based on review feedback (typically several rounds)
# 4. once approved, get a SPONSOR (existing packager) if you're a new
#    packager — sponsorship is the trust-establishment step
# 5. once sponsored: request the dist-git repo creation
# 6. fedpkg clone + push your reviewed spec
# 7. fedpkg build → bodhi update → done


# THE MAINTAINER LADDER

# - PROSPECTIVE PACKAGER: anyone with a FAS account
# - PACKAGER: completed a package review, has a sponsor, can maintain
#   packages they've created and any they've been added to
# - PROVENPACKAGER: longstanding packager with broad commit rights
#   (across many packages, used for emergency fixes)
# - SPONSOR: can vouch for and bring in new packagers; has reviewed
#   ~5+ packages
# - PACKAGING COMMITTEE (FPC): governance body for packaging policy


# EPEL — EXTRA PACKAGES FOR ENTERPRISE LINUX

# EPEL is the community repository of fedora packages BUILT for RHEL
# and rebuilds (Rocky, Alma, etc.). many fedora packages have a
# matching EPEL branch:
#
#   fedpkg switch-branch epel9       # the EPEL 9 spec for your package
#
# the build pipeline is the same (koji → bodhi); the target is RHEL/EPEL.
# significant volunteer effort goes into keeping EPEL fresh; it's a
# good entry point for new packagers (lots of small useful packages
# need maintainers).


# HONEST TRADEOFFS

# 1. OFFICIAL PACKAGING IS AN ONGOING COMMITMENT. you have to
#    respond to FTBFS bugs (Failed To Build From Source), security
#    notifications, and version bumps. not a one-shot.
#
# 2. THE REVIEW PROCESS IS SLOW. expect weeks for a new package
#    review. reviewers are volunteers. don't take iteration personally.
#
# 3. COPR FOR PERSONAL USE; FEDORA FOR THE COMMONS. if your package
#    is only useful to you, COPR is the right answer. push to fedora
#    proper only when there's broader demand and you'll maintain it.
#
# 4. ABANDONED PACKAGES ARE A REAL PROBLEM. if you stop maintaining,
#    your package eventually gets orphaned. think hard before
#    committing.
#
# 5. EPEL IS WHERE THE LEVERAGE IS. fedora has many packagers; EPEL
#    is chronically short-handed. picking up an EPEL package nobody
#    is maintaining helps both the RHEL and the fedora ecosystem.


# DECISION MATRIX

#   "test that my RPM builds clean"             → mock
#   "share my RPM with friends or coworkers"    → personal COPR
#   "ship a fedora package i'll co-maintain"    → review → fedpkg
#                                                  → koji → bodhi
#   "build for RHEL 9 / 10 too"                 → EPEL branch
#   "scratch-build to test before publishing"   → koji --scratch
#   "make a build live for users"               → bodhi updates new
#   "i want to learn packaging, low stakes"     → EPEL adoption +
#                                                  COPR experimentation


# WHERE TO GET HELP

# - discussion.fedoraproject.org → category "Project Discussion"
#   → tag "packaging"
# - #fedora-devel on matrix / IRC
# - the fedora-devel mailing list
# - the FPC (Fedora Packaging Committee) for policy questions
# - cross-link to WHERE TO GO WHEN STUCK section


