# WHY FEDORA WORKSTATION FEELS "MOSTLY THERE"

# the default install is deliberately curated for the system-level
# user — someone who'll bring their own toolchain, terminal, and
# editor preferences. that's why C devs, sysadmins, and SREs often
# find fedora "has most of what i need" without configuration:
# the things you'd want to install yourself anyway aren't preinstalled
# (because preferences differ), and the things everyone needs
# (firefox, file manager, terminal, image viewer, network tools)
# are there.
#
# this is also why GNOME developers themselves tend to use it as a
# daily driver — it's the reference platform for new GNOME releases,
# without the philosophical overhead of an immutable variant like
# Silverblue.


RUST REWRITES — THE MODERN USERLAND
-----------------------------------

# a real trend over the past decade: GNU / BSD core CLI tools (some
# 50+ years old) are getting memory-safe replacements written in
# rust. better defaults, faster, often safer. fedora ships most of
# them in repos.


# THE THESIS

# the original GNU coreutils (1990s) and POSIX tools (1980s) are
# remarkably reliable but they:
#   - are written in C with manual memory management
#   - have decades of UX accreted by historical accident (find's
#     syntax, sed's escape rules, awk's quoting)
#   - frequently sit at the heart of security incidents (sudo CVEs,
#     bash shellshock, the openssl Heartbleed era)
#
# the rewrite thesis: REPLACE THE BUSIEST C TOOLS WITH RUST EQUIVALENTS,
# starting where memory-safety matters most (sudo, coreutils) and
# where UX improvements compound (find → fd, grep → ripgrep).


# THE USERLAND MAPPING — DROP-IN-ISH REPLACEMENTS

#   classic            rust replacement      install
#   ──────────────     ──────────────────    ────────────────────────────
#   grep               ripgrep (rg)          dnf install ripgrep
#   find               fd                    dnf install fd-find
#   cat                bat                   dnf install bat
#   ls                 eza (was exa)         dnf install eza
#   du                 dust                  dnf install dust
#   df                 duf                   dnf install duf
#   top                bottom (btm)          dnf install bottom
#   ps                 procs                 dnf install procs
#   sed                sd                    dnf install sd
#   cd                 zoxide (z)            dnf install zoxide
#   man                tealdeer (tldr)       dnf install tealdeer
#   diff               difftastic            cargo install difftastic
#   tar (compress)     ouch                  dnf install ouch
#   time               hyperfine             dnf install hyperfine
#   prompt             starship              dnf install starship
#   bash (paradigm)    nushell               dnf install nushell


# CORE-INFRASTRUCTURE REWRITES — THE BIG BETS

# COREUTILS → UUTILS
#   the canonical "rewrite GNU coreutils in rust" project. covers
#   the GNU coreutils binaries (ls, cp, mv, rm, mkdir, cat, echo,
#   etc.). UBUNTU 25.10 (Oct 2025) MADE UUTILS THE DEFAULT
#   coreutils — a major signal that the technology is ready.
#
#   fedora's stance (mid-2026): packaged but not default. install
#   explicitly:
sudo dnf install uutils-coreutils
#   it lands at /usr/bin/uu-* (uu-ls, uu-cp, etc.) to avoid
#   clobbering the GNU binaries. you opt in per-tool by aliasing or
#   adjusting PATH.

# SUDO → SUDO-RS
#   ISRG's Prossimo memory-safety project (same org behind let's
#   encrypt). sudo has had several CVEs in C; sudo-rs is the strict
#   subset rewrite focused on security. fedora packages it:
sudo dnf install sudo-rs
#   side-by-side install initially; you can symlink it as /usr/bin/sudo
#   if you want it as the default. not yet the default but the
#   direction of travel.


# ALREADY-RUST FEDORA INFRASTRUCTURE (you didn't notice)

# - librsvg — SVG rendering. converted to rust years ago. every time
#   you view an SVG icon, it's rust.
# - rustls — TLS implementation. used in increasingly many places
#   instead of openssl.
# - bootupd — the bootloader updater for atomic desktops.
# - bcachefs / btrfs — userspace tools include rust components.
# - asahi DRM driver — apple silicon GPU driver. mainline rust.
# - rust-binary kernel modules — landing for NVMe and networking.


# FEDORA'S PACKAGING POSTURE

# the official policy (per the fedora packaging guidelines):
#   - rust applications can be packaged as RPMs in the official repos
#   - rust libraries are packaged as cargo-* RPMs (e.g. cargo-toml)
#   - the cargo packaging team handles policy + builds
#   - `cargo install <pkg>` works for end users but binaries land in
#     ~/.cargo/bin/ — OUTSIDE the package manager
#
# practical guidance: PREFER `dnf install` over `cargo install`. you
# get integrity verification, system-update integration, and clean
# removal. reach for cargo only when a tool isn't in the repos AND
# you actually need the latest version.


# HONEST TRADEOFFS

# 1. ECOSYSTEM FRAGMENTATION. you can now have both `grep` AND
#    `ripgrep`. learning two tools for the same job is overhead. most
#    users settle on the rust tool for interactive use and keep the
#    GNU tool for script portability.
#
# 2. SCRIPT PORTABILITY. if your bash scripts parse `ls` or `find`
#    output, GNU quirks are documented across 30 years of stack
#    overflow. switching changes output formats and breaks parsing.
#    DON'T USE RUST REPLACEMENTS IN SHIPPED SCRIPTS unless you're
#    committing to them as deps.
#
# 3. COMPILE TIMES. rust compilation is famously slow. on fedora
#    you `dnf install` precompiled binaries so it's invisible.
#    source-build distros (gentoo, building from cargo) feel it.
#
# 4. BINARY SIZE. rust binaries are larger than C (~2-5x typically).
#    on disk negligible; in container layers it adds up.
#
# 5. NOT EVERY TOOL BENEFITS. `wc` is 200 lines of C; there's no
#    meaningful safety or perf win from rewriting it. the trend is
#    targeted at busy / security-critical tools, not universal.


# CONNECTION TO FEDORA'S BIGGER PICTURE

# see THE NEXT 5-10 YEARS section, point 6 ("Rust in the kernel and
# userspace"). the userland rewrites are the visible surface of a
# deeper transition: memory-safe languages replacing C for new system
# code. by 2030, expect rust to be the default for new fedora packages
# targeting the system layer. you're watching a generational shift.


# RECOMMENDED MODERN CLI SET (fedora install)

# the rust toolkit most people end up with:
sudo dnf install \
    ripgrep fd-find bat eza dust duf bottom procs sd zoxide \
    starship hyperfine tealdeer

# add to your shell config:
echo 'eval "$(starship init zsh)"' >> ~/.zshrc
echo 'eval "$(zoxide init zsh)"' >> ~/.zshrc

# optional but increasingly mainstream:
sudo dnf install sudo-rs uutils-coreutils nushell


