# MAILING LISTS — FOR DEVS AND DEEP-DIVE DISCUSSIONS

# subscribe via lists.fedoraproject.org:
#   - users@                — general user-level questions
#   - devel@                — development discussion (high traffic)
#   - test@                 — test day announcements, beta testing
#   - announce@             — release announcements only (low traffic)
#   - rpm-list@             — packaging / rpm-related


# READING THE SOURCE

# pkgs.fedoraproject.org/<package>
#   the dist-git for any fedora package. you can read the .spec file
#   (build instructions), see the patches applied, see who maintains
#   it. essential for "what is this package actually doing".
#
# example: how is the firefox package built?
#   https://src.fedoraproject.org/rpms/firefox

# bodhi.fedoraproject.org
#   tracks every update going through the testing pipeline. useful
#   for "is the fix for my bug already pending in updates-testing?"
#   you can opt into updates-testing per-package:
sudo dnf update --enablerepo=updates-testing <package>

# koji.fedoraproject.org
#   the build system. tracks every build of every package, all
#   architectures. usually only relevant if you're packaging.

# COPR (copr.fedoraproject.org)
#   community-built repos. for community/per-developer packages.
#   useful as a search target when an upstream project says "we
#   ship via COPR".


# ESCALATION DISCIPLINE — HOW TO ACTUALLY GET HELP

# the difference between "i posted a question and got a useful answer
# in 20 minutes" and "i posted a question and got nothing" is almost
# always how the question was asked. before posting:
#
# 1. ISOLATE WHAT CHANGED. "it broke after the upgrade" is not enough.
#    which package? `dnf history info <transaction-id>` shows the
#    actual transaction. `journalctl -b -p err` shows boot errors.
#    `coredumpctl list` shows crashes.
#
# 2. CHECK THE COMMON ISSUES THREAD FIRST. if your problem is on it,
#    the answer is on it. nothing kills your goodwill faster than a
#    "this is already in common issues" reply.
#
# 3. SEARCH DISCUSSION + BUGZILLA. someone has probably already hit
#    it. paste an error message verbatim into google with
#    `site:discussion.fedoraproject.org` and `site:bugzilla.redhat.com`.
#
# 4. PRODUCE A MINIMAL REPRODUCER. "X is broken" is unhelpful.
#    "fresh fedora 44 workstation install, install package Y, run
#    command Z, get error E" is actionable.
#
# 5. COLLECT THE OBVIOUS LOGS. for bugzilla:
#       sudo dnf info <package>                   # version installed
#       uname -r                                  # kernel
#       cat /etc/fedora-release                   # release
#       journalctl -b -u <unit> -n 100            # service logs
#       coredumpctl info <pid-or-program>         # crash details
#       rpm -q <package>                          # versions
#
# 6. ATTACH, DON'T PASTE. logs longer than 30 lines go in attachments
#    or paste sites (paste.centos.org, dpaste.com), not inline.
#
# 7. STATE WHAT YOU'VE TRIED. helpers don't want to suggest things
#    you've already done. listing the failed attempts speeds the
#    conversation 10x.


# FINDING WHO MAINTAINS A PACKAGE

# every fedora package has a maintainer. if you've found a real bug
# and bugzilla is taking too long, find them:
dnf info <package>                           # "URL" field often points to source
rpm -qi <package> | grep -i packager         # rarely set; usually generic

# better: pkgs.fedoraproject.org/<package> shows the maintainer
# group and recent commits. you can open an issue against the
# dist-git repo directly, or @-mention the maintainer in
# discussion.fedoraproject.org.


# THE NUCLEAR OPTIONS

# when nothing on the above has worked:
#
#   - file a bug against the UPSTREAM project (the actual software,
#     not fedora's package). often the right move for application bugs
#     vs distro packaging bugs.
#   - cross-post to the kernel mailing list (lkml.org) for kernel
#     bugs — but only after you've verified it's actually a kernel
#     bug, not a userspace problem. you'll get a tough crowd.
#   - reach out to red hat directly only if you have a RHEL
#     entitlement; for community fedora users there's no commercial
#     support path.


# REMEMBER: FEDORA IS VOLUNTEER-DRIVEN

# the people answering your question are not paid. they're maintaining
# packages on the side because they care. respect their time:
#   - search before asking
#   - report back when something works ("the suggestion fixed it")
#   - if you get an answer, mark it as the solution on discussion
#   - update bugzilla bugs when they're resolved
#   - contribute back when you learn something (write a wiki page,
#     answer someone else's question)
#
# the community survives on this etiquette. you joined the moment you
# installed fedora — you're part of it now.


